{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

Welcome to the Candidates 2026!! The tournament has started with a furious start: three out of four games had a decisive result and one interesting draw between Bluebaum and Wei Yi.

The games had it all: they were very interesting from the opening stage, great middlegame battles and some very interesting endgames as it occured between Caruana-Naka and Pragg-Giri (sadly, I had the difficult decision of choosing 2 out of the 4).

The dream scenario for every chess fan, enjoy! }
1. Nf3!? { Already a surprise from Fabi. We all know that he is capable of playing every opening, but he is mostly an 1.e4 player.
These two players know each other very well. Not only they are the top seeds, but they are the pair of players who have played against each other the most. And again, they didn't disappoint! } { [%clk 1:59:55] } (1. a3) 1... d5 { [%clk 1:59:43] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:50] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:59:34] } 3. g3 { [%clk 1:59:43] } 3... d4!? { Hikaru decides to play with ...d4. Of course 3...Nf6 would have led to a Catalan setup. We will have to wait to see what Caruana had for that. } { [%clk 1:59:07] } 4. Bg2 { [%clk 1:59:08] } 4... Nc6 { [%clk 1:59:02] } 5. O-O { [%clk 1:58:04] } 5... Bc5 { The most natural move. 5...Nh6 is also pretty interesting in this position, trying to get to f5 to support the d4 square. } { [%clk 1:58:41] } (5... Nh6 6. d3 (6. e3 Nf5 7. e4 Nfe7 8. e5 d3 $132) 6... Nf5 7. e4 dxe3 8. fxe3 h5!? { Could have been another possibility. The position is always very complex for both sides. } { [%cal Gh5h4,Gd3d4] }) 6. e3 { [%clk 1:52:48] } 6... Nge7 { [%clk 1:56:04] } 7. Nxd4!? { A bit of a surprise: I'm pretty sure Fabi had this prepared, considering the time spent in the move. More natural would have been: } { [%clk 1:52:27] } (7. d3 O-O 8. Na3 dxe3 (8... e5 9. exd4 exd4) 9. Bxe3) 7... Nxd4 { Hikaru shows he was well prepared by playing the next sequence of moves pretty fast. } { [%clk 1:55:52] } 8. b4 { [%clk 1:52:15] } 8... Bxb4 { [%clk 1:55:47] } 9. exd4 { White's center looks vulnerable, but the dynamic factor justifies having a worse pawn structure. The most interesting part of the game starts now: } { [%clk 1:52:11] } 9... O-O { [%clk 1:52:57] } (9... Qxd4?? 10. Qa4+) 10. Qb3 { This shows very well White's intention. Instead of defending passively, White will always try active ideas to stop Black from capturing on d4. } { [%clk 1:42:31] } (10. Bb2?! Nf5 11. d5 exd5 12. cxd5 Bd7 $10) 10... Ba5 { [%clk 1:51:28] } 11. Nc3!? { [%clk 1:42:03] } 11... Nf5 { Practical choice. It would have been very dangerous to take on d4 as we will see. } { [%clk 1:34:53] } (11... Qxd4 12. Ba3 { I think this looks more dangerous than Qa3. } (12. Qa3!? Bxc3 13. dxc3) 12... Bxc3 (12... Re8?? 13. Bxe7 Rxe7 14. Qa3) (12... Qd8 13. Qa4 Bxc3 14. dxc3 $36 { [%cal Ba3f8,Bg2b7,Bf1d1,Bd1d8] }) 13. dxc3 Qf6 (13... Qd8 14. Rad1) 14. Rad1 { Despite being down a pawn, White's pieces are way more active. } { [%cal Gb3b4,Ga3e7] } 14... e5 15. Qb4 Ng6 16. Qa5 $14 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Ga5c7,Ga3f8] }) 12. Ba3 { [%clk 1:39:34] } 12... Re8 { [%clk 1:29:14] } (12... Nxd4!? 13. Qa4 b6! { Very interesting resource that creates a big, big mess! Despite having both rooks in danger, Black is getting some amazing play. } 14. Bxf8 Bd7 15. Qd1 Qxf8 $132) 13. d5 { [%clk 1:39:06] } 13... Nd4 { [%clk 1:08:25] } (13... exd5 { Was an option for Black, although White still has some chances to create some interesting play after: } 14. Rae1!? (14. cxd5 Nd4 $15 { [%cal Ga5b6] }) 14... Bxc3! { Since the N is dangerous and the B is a bit misplaced on a5, this trade should make sense. } (14... dxc4?? 15. Qb5) (14... Rxe1 15. Rxe1 $36 { Due to more active pieces, Black is far from being on safe land. }) 15. dxc3 dxc4 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Qxc4 c6 18. Qb4 $132) 14. Qa4 { [%clk 1:37:09] } 14... b6!? { [%clk 1:07:56] } (14... Bxc3 15. dxc3 Ne2+ 16. Kh1 exd5 17. cxd5 $36 { Engine evaluates this as equal, but this is far from balance from a human standpoint. It is definitely a clear example that Fabi has succeeded in his aim to create opportunities in the position. } { [%csl Re2] }) 15. Rae1! { Always energetic! Worse was: } { [%clk 0:59:01] } (15. dxe6?! Bxe6 { Black is already safe and even playing for the edge! } 16. Bxa8?? Qxa8 $19 { [%csl Rf3,Rh3][%cal Ge6h3,Gd4f3] }) 15... Bd7 { [%clk 1:06:41] } 16. Qd1 { [%clk 0:57:18] } 16... c5! { Great move by Hikaru. I was following live, and I truly thought that Black was doing fine after the resource. I completely underestimated White's chances to create chances here. } { [%clk 1:06:37] } 17. Bb2 { [%clk 0:40:15] } 17... Rb8 { [%clk 1:01:24] } 18. a4!? { White already had the idea of occupying d5, but didn't want to allow b5 so easily. } { [%clk 0:27:43] } (18. dxe6 Bxe6 19. Nd5 b5 { Seems ok for Black. }) 18... a6?! { Insisting with the idea of playing b5, but it was prob better to eliminate the N at this point. } { [%clk 0:56:53] } (18... Bxc3! 19. Bxc3 (19. dxc3 Nf5 20. Bc1 Qf6 { Black is more comfortable here, despite the B pair. }) 19... exd5 20. Bxd5 Qc7 $14 { Objectively, White should be better but the pawn on a4 and Black's intention to go Bc6 makes me feel that chances are pretty balanced. } { [%cal Gd7c6] }) 19. dxe6 { [%clk 0:25:27] } 19... Bxe6 { [%clk 0:38:23] } 20. Nd5! { [%clk 0:25:09] } 20... Qd6 { [%clk 0:38:07] } 21. Bxd4 { The start of a great transition. } { [%clk 0:13:48] } 21... cxd4 { [%clk 0:37:27] } 22. Re4! { Nice detail. White is moving towards an opposite color bishop and, with the heavy pieces on the board, his chances to win are still very alive. } { [%clk 0:13:45] } 22... Bxd5 { Knowing what ended up happening, 22..d3 would have been an interesting try for Naka to stay active. But I would have done the same as he did (Sorry Hikaru :). } { [%clk 0:33:53] } (22... d3!? 23. Qf3 b5! $132 { With very good activity. Black's bishops definitely compensate the weakness on d3. }) 23. Rxe8+ { [%clk 0:13:33] } 23... Rxe8 { [%clk 0:33:49] } 24. Bxd5 { [%clk 0:13:30] } 24... Bb4 { This is the moment where Hikaru seemed to have lost the path. Considering White's hard pressure against f7, the best way to defend is prob by putting his pawn on g6 and K on g7. } { [%clk 0:30:23] } (24... g6 $10 { [%cal Gg8g7] }) 25. h4! { The start of an amazing maneuver! } { [%clk 0:13:03] } 25... a5 { [%clk 0:29:52] } 26. d3 { [%clk 0:12:46] } 26... Qf6?! { I guess Naka didn't sense the danger and was trying to speed up, considering Fabi was lower on time. } { [%clk 0:29:05] } (26... g6) 27. Kg2 { [%clk 0:12:32] } 27... Qe5 { Hikaru started to invest more time, and probably realized that the position wasn't as simple. } { [%clk 0:18:55] } 28. Qf3 { [%clk 0:11:02] } 28... Qf6 { [%clk 0:13:16] } 29. Qg4! $14 { Always with Qs on the board. But in reality Black should still be able to hold with g6 } { [%clk 0:10:58] } 29... Bc5?! { Final chance to play g6. After this, Hikaru will start to suffer a lot! } { [%clk 0:12:34] } (29... g6 30. h5 Qf5! (30... Re5 31. h6 Bf8 32. Qc8 { Should be pretty dangerous. }) 31. Qxd4 (31. Qxf5 gxf5 32. h6 Kf8 $10) 31... Bc5 32. Qb2 Qe5! $14 { Active defense. But definitely hard to find: first because it sacrifices a pawn to stay active and, most importantly, because it is already accepting that staying passive is not going to be the way! }) 30. h5! $16 { [%clk 0:10:31] } 30... h6 { [%clk 0:11:26] } 31. Rh1! { Playing fast and very well! Beautiful maneuver by Fabi, who is planning to bring the R through the h4 square. White's advantage is real. } { [%cal Gh1h4] [%clk 0:10:21] } 31... Qg5 { [%clk 0:11:11] } 32. Qd1 { [%clk 0:07:33] } (32. Qd7 Qe7) 32... Qe7?! { [%clk 0:11:09] } 33. Bc6 { Definitely more human. } { [%clk 0:06:55] } (33. Rh4!? { Also very good and not afraid of letting Black's Q getting in } 33... Qe2 (33... Qe1 34. Qf3) 34. Qh1 $18 { Lovely move that leaves the pawn on d3 for the very strong initiative. } 34... Qxd3 35. Qh3 $18 { [%cal Gh4f4,Gh3d7] }) 33... Rc8 { [%clk 0:10:57] } 34. Re1 { [%clk 0:05:40] } 34... Qc7 { [%clk 0:08:57] } 35. Bd5 { [%clk 0:05:22] } 35... Kf8 { [%clk 0:08:52] } 36. Qg4 { [%clk 0:04:51] } 36... Rd8 { Important to notice that both players are approaching time control, so that probably explains some of the shuffling around. } { [%clk 0:08:24] } 37. Qe4 { Definitely better was: } { [%clk 0:02:38] } (37. Qf5! Re8 (37... Kg8 38. Be4) 38. Rh1 $18 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Bh1h4,Bf5h7] }) 37... Kg8 { [%clk 0:08:09] } 38. Qf5 { [%clk 0:02:33] } 38... Qd7 { [%clk 0:07:59] } 39. Qf3 { [%clk 0:01:40] } 39... Rf8 { [%clk 0:05:30] } 40. Re5!? { Interesting move by Fabi to get passed the time control. } { [%clk 0:32:05] } 40... Bd6 { [%clk 0:31:56] } 41. Rf5 { [%clk 0:30:38] } (41. Qf5!? { We have been talking about how important it was to play with Qs on the board, but now that f7 is so weak, White has the possibility to move to an endgame that should be winning as illustrated: } 41... Qxf5 (41... Qc7 42. Re4 Bc5 43. Rg4 $18) 42. Rxf5 { [%csl Rf7,Rg8][%cal Gf2f4,Gg2f3,Gg3g4,Gg4g5] }) 41... Qe7 { [%clk 0:32:21] } 42. Qg4 { [%clk 0:28:12] } 42... Be5 { [%clk 0:32:01] } 43. Rf3 { [%clk 0:28:14] } 43... Bf6 { [%clk 0:30:24] } 44. Rf4 { [%clk 0:28:07] } 44... Qd8 { [%clk 0:29:40] } 45. Be4 { [%clk 0:25:13] } 45... Re8 { [%clk 0:25:06] } 46. Rf5 { [%clk 0:22:35] } 46... Qd7 { [%clk 0:16:45] } 47. Qf4! { Finally breaking in! } { [%clk 0:22:05] } 47... Bg5 { [%clk 0:14:05] } (47... Qxa4 48. Rb5! { [%cal Gb5b6,Gf4f5] }) (47... Qc8 48. Rb5 Bg5 49. Qd6 { [%csl Rd4,Rb6] }) 48. Qf3 { [%clk 0:22:23] } 48... Qc7 { [%clk 0:14:32] } (48... Rf8!? 49. Rb5 Bd8 50. Rd5 Qc8 (50... Qxa4 51. Qf5) 51. Rxd4) 49. Rxf7! $18 { We all thought it was pretty much over at this point, but Hikaru was only getting started! } { [%clk 0:20:00] } 49... Qxf7 { [%clk 0:14:48] } 50. Bd5 { [%clk 0:20:29] } 50... Re6 { [%clk 0:15:13] } 51. Qg4 { [%clk 0:20:54] } 51... Kf8 { [%clk 0:15:41] } 52. Bxe6 { Although the game should be winning due to the extra pawn and the very weak king, the game is far from over as we will see. } { [%clk 0:21:18] } 52... Qe8 { [%clk 0:16:07] } 53. Bd7 { [%clk 0:19:59] } 53... Qa8+ { [%clk 0:14:54] } 54. Kg1 { [%clk 0:20:05] } 54... Bf6 { [%clk 0:15:20] } 55. Qe6 { [%clk 0:18:59] } 55... Qd8 { [%clk 0:15:49] } 56. Bc6 { [%clk 0:16:47] } 56... Qe7 { [%clk 0:16:06] } 57. Qc8+ { [%clk 0:14:45] } 57... Qd8 { [%clk 0:16:35] } 58. Qb7 { [%clk 0:15:08] } 58... Be5 { [%clk 0:14:14] } 59. Bd5 { [%clk 0:14:40] } 59... Qc7 { [%clk 0:13:42] } 60. Qa8+ { [%clk 0:15:05] } 60... Ke7?! { [%clk 0:14:08] } (60... Qb8 { Hikaru has been very tenacious at this point, which was extremely difficult. Maybe bringing his K to the Q side would have been a good try to resist. } 61. Qc6 Qd6 62. Qc8+ Ke7 63. Bc6 { [%csl Rd7] } 63... Qd8 64. Qg4 Kd6!? { [%cal Gd6c5,Gc5b4] } 65. Bb5 (65. Bd5 Qd7) 65... Kc5 { The K march! The K is going to be safer on the Q side. }) 61. Qg8 { [%clk 0:13:46] } 61... Kd6 { [%clk 0:14:20] } 62. Be4 { [%clk 0:10:53] } (62. Qf8+ Qe7 63. c5+!? { Extremely interesting resouce! } 63... bxc5 64. Qa8 Qc7 65. Bc4 { The idea is to expose a5 a bit more, to force Black's Q to stay passive, and close any sort of escape for the K who was trying to use c5 to escape. } { [%csl Bd6] }) 62... Ke7 { [%clk 0:10:33] } (62... Kc5! { Again, the K is always happier on the Q side. }) 63. Bg6 { [%clk 0:11:05] } 63... Bf6 { [%clk 0:09:11] } 64. Qf7+ { [%clk 0:08:58] } 64... Kd6 { [%clk 0:09:38] } 65. Qd5+ { [%clk 0:09:26] } 65... Ke7 { [%clk 0:10:07] } 66. Bf5 { [%clk 0:09:35] } 66... Be5?? { In a very difficult position, Hikaru finally blunders. } { [%clk 0:07:06] } 67. f4?? { But Fabi misses! It was winning after: } { [%clk 0:08:01] } (67. Qe6+ Kd8 (67... Kf8 68. Bg6) 68. f4 Bf6 (68... Bd6 69. Qg8+ { [%cal Gg8g7] }) 69. Kf1! { Beautiful zugwang! Any move for Black loses something } 69... Qb7 (69... Be7 70. Qg8+) 70. Qd6+ { [%cal Gf5g6] }) 67... Bf6 { Back to work! } { [%clk 0:07:17] } 68. Kg2 { [%clk 0:08:19] } 68... Qd6 { [%clk 0:06:29] } 69. Qb7+ { [%clk 0:08:43] } 69... Kf8 { [%clk 0:06:58] } 70. Kf3? { It was always better for W to put the B on g6, because it cuts and creates constant difficulties. At this point, it was clear that Caruana was not finding a clear path to victory. } { [%clk 0:08:03] } (70. Bg6 Qe7 71. Qa8+ Qd8 72. Qc6 Qe7 73. Kh3 Qd8 74. Qe6 $18 { [%cal Ge6f7,Ge6b6] }) 70... Qe7 { [%clk 0:07:14] } 71. Qe4 { [%clk 0:05:32] } 71... Qxe4+?? { Not a good trade, at this point it was a better idea to keep Qs. on the board (again lol). } { [%clk 0:07:42] } (71... Qd8) 72. dxe4! { Finally winning (or not) } { [%clk 0:05:23] } 72... Be7 { [%clk 0:05:25] } 73. e5 { [%clk 0:05:49] } 73... Bb4 { [%clk 0:05:54] } 74. Bd3! { Nice detail. Better than the very natural } { [%clk 0:06:13] } (74. Ke4 Be1 75. g4 Bg3 { Where Black still creates some difficulties. }) 74... Be1 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 75. g4 { [%clk 0:06:36] } 75... Ke7 { [%clk 0:04:29] } 76. Ke4 { [%clk 0:07:03] } 76... Bg3 { [%clk 0:04:52] } 77. f5 { [%clk 0:06:28] } 77... Kd7 { [%clk 0:03:47] } 78. Kd5 { Investing 5 out of his 6 minutes, Caruana couldn't find the win here. } { [%clk 0:01:26] } (78. g5! hxg5 (78... Bh4 79. gxh6 gxh6 80. f6 Ke6 81. c5 { [%cal Gd3c4,Ge4f5] }) 79. f6 gxf6 80. Kf5! $18 { Probably the detail tha he missed. } { [%cal Gh5h8] } (80. h6 Ke6! $10 81. h7 Bxe5 { [%cal Gf6f5,Ge5h8] })) 78... Bh4 { [%clk 0:03:59] } 79. f6?? { Crazy turn of events, Fabi goes for a line that throws away all the beautiful work that he has put. White was still winning after: } { [%clk 0:01:09] } (79. Kxd4 Kc6 80. Be4+ Kd7 81. Bb7 Kc7 82. Kd5! { Shirov's style: the K need to get in. } 82... Kd7 (82... Kxb7 83. Ke6) 83. Bc8+ Ke7 84. Kc6 Bf2 85. g5 hxg5 86. f6+ gxf6 (86... Kf7 87. fxg7 Kxg7 88. e6 $18) 87. h6 Kf7 88. e6+) 79... gxf6 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 80. e6+ { [%clk 0:01:37] } 80... Ke7?? { Oh no! After an epic effort, Hikaru misses the draw: } { [%clk 0:04:07] } (80... Kc7 81. e7 Kd7 82. e8=Q+ Kxe8 83. Kc6 f5! { Beautiful resource that keeps the very important pawn of b6. } { [%cal Gh4d8] } 84. Bxf5 Bd8 $10) 81. Kc6 { [%clk 0:02:02] } 81... Kxe6 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 82. Kxb6 { [%clk 0:02:29] } 82... Be1 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 83. c5 { 1-0 White wins.
Caruana finally gets the full point, after an amazing defensive effort by Naka. One of the most intense games that I've ever witnessed and we just wanna thank these two gladiators. } { [%cal Gc5c7,Gb6b7,Gd3f5] [%clk 0:01:55] } 1-0


