{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - lichess.org/@/ABachmann

Round 1 offered a very interesting match between two very different talents: the very aggressive Javokhir Sindarov against the more positional Andrey Esipenko. As expected, they didn't disappoint! }
1. d4 { A bit of a surprise as well: Sindarov decides to try d4 instead of his most common 1.e4 } { [%clk 1:59:56] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:59:30] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:46] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:59:22] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:35] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:14] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:30] } 4... Be7 { [%clk 1:59:01] } 5. cxd5 { [%clk 1:58:45] } 5... exd5 { [%clk 1:58:53] } 6. Bf4 { [%clk 1:58:41] } 6... O-O { [%clk 1:58:22] } 7. e3 { [%clk 1:55:55] } 7... c5 { [%clk 1:58:03] } 8. Bd3 { After investing a bit of time, Sindarov decides to keep the tension instead of trading. } { [%clk 1:49:48] } (8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Be6 { This would have been the natural course, which should be a slight plus for White but probably more comfortable to Andrey's style of play. }) 8... Nc6 { [%clk 1:57:24] } 9. O-O { [%clk 1:49:43] } 9... c4 { Still playing fast and definitely on prep, Esipenko decides to close the center. An alternative was to } { [%clk 1:55:14] } (9... Bg4 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 d4 13. Ne4 $14 { White is definitely better here. }) 10. Bc2 { [%clk 1:49:36] } 10... Nh5 { [%clk 1:54:42] } (10... Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Ne5 { Probably the kind of position you want to avoid against the very dangerous Sindarov. }) 11. Be5 { Typical move in this kind of positions. White's B cannot be captured. } { [%clk 1:43:40] } 11... f6 { [%clk 1:52:10] } (11... Nxe5? 12. dxe5 { [%csl Rh5][%cal Bd1d5,Bf3d4] }) 12. Bg3 { [%clk 1:42:12] } (12. Ng5 { In my opinion, it is probably White's best chance to achieve something. But looking at how fast Esipenko was still playing, I am pretty sure that he was very well prepared for it. } 12... g6 (12... fxg5?! { Simply worse. } 13. Qxh5 Bf5 $7 (13... g6 14. Bxg6) 14. Bxf5 Rxf5 15. Qg4 $14 $36) 13. Nxh7 fxe5 14. Bxg6 Ng7 15. Nxf8 exd4 16. exd4 Bxf8 17. Qf3 Be6 $13 { The position is extremely unclear, but I would feel this is more in the style of Sindarov. }) 12... f5 { [%clk 1:46:18] } 13. Be5?! { This is already a slight mistake, White had to occupy the e5 square with the N if he wants to fight for something. } { [%clk 1:28:52] } (13. Ne5 g6 14. Qf3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Be6 16. Rad1 $14 { Despite Black's position looking solid, I could definitely see White having some chances with b3, Nxc4-d5, etc. } { [%cal Ge5c4,Gd4d5,Gc2a4,Gb2b3] }) 13... Be6 { [%clk 1:41:09] } (13... a6 { Trying the typical expansion. My guess is that Esipenko wanted to prioritize finishing his development over any sort of offensive effort. } { [%cal Gb7b5] }) 14. b3 { [%clk 1:12:47] } 14... Qa5! { Good move. Black needs to support b5 and puts his Q in a square that is far from the natural d7 square. But just momentarily, as we will see. } { [%clk 1:35:12] } 15. Ne2 { [%clk 1:12:32] } 15... b5 { [%clk 1:20:27] } 16. Nf4 { [%clk 1:00:45] } 16... Nxf4 { [%clk 1:19:43] } 17. exf4 { Right capture, it was simply worse to take with the B } { [%clk 1:00:42] } (17. Bxf4 Nb4 $15 { Black gets the B and a very promising initiative on the Q side. }) 17... Qd8! { Beautiful move. As we said, the right square for the Q was d7. } { [%clk 1:10:17] } 18. Re1 { [%clk 0:59:53] } 18... Qd7 { [%clk 1:07:34] } 19. Re3 { [%clk 0:59:11] } 19... Rae8 { [%clk 0:52:26] } 20. h4 { [%clk 0:56:18] } 20... h6 { Probably better than } { [%clk 0:47:49] } (20... Bf7 21. Ng5 Bxg5 22. hxg5 { Which seems to be ok for White. }) 21. g3?! { Already failing to see anything concrete, Sindarov weakens his position with this move. At this point, it was very clear that Esipenko approach was a huge success. It was necessarily to stay active with: } { [%clk 0:48:35] } (21. Qb1!? a6 22. h5 Nb4 23. Bd1 Bf7 24. a4 { Nice resource, White will justify the weakness on h5 with active moves. } 24... Bxh5?! (24... Ra8 25. bxc4 { [%cal Gf3h4,Gb1b4] }) 25. axb5 axb5 26. bxc4? bxc4 (26... dxc4 27. Bxg7 Bxf3 28. Bxf8) 27. Bxg7 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gd1h5] }) 21... a6 { [%clk 0:43:44] } (21... Bf7 { Was already very strong. }) 22. Kg2 { [%clk 0:28:06] } 22... Bf7! $15 { Black is simply better and with more time on the clock. } { [%clk 0:41:24] } 23. Qd2 { [%clk 0:22:41] } 23... Bb4 { [%clk 0:38:07] } 24. Qe2 { [%clk 0:18:45] } 24... Bh5 { [%clk 0:34:21] } 25. a4!? { Great resource by Sindarov in an already very difficult position. It shows very well how resourceful he is. Instead of going for a passive defense, he tries his best to complicate. } { [%clk 0:16:53] } (25. Bd1 Nxe5 26. Nxe5 (26. Rxe5 Rxe5 27. Nxe5 Bxe2 28. Nxd7 Re8) 26... Rxe5 27. Qxh5 Rxe3 28. fxe3 Bd2 $15 { If we look with the engine, it might be holdable but it still very uncomfortable for White. } { [%cal Gc4c3] }) 25... Ba5 { [%clk 0:30:23] } 26. axb5 { [%clk 0:12:43] } 26... axb5 { [%clk 0:30:01] } 27. Bd1! { [%clk 0:06:39] } 27... Bxf3+? { After playing a perfect game, Esipenko goes very wrong, despite having the right idea. It was better to } { [%clk 0:22:20] } (27... Bb6 28. Qb2 (28. Ra6 Qb7 $19) 28... b4 $17 { White's position looks strategically lost. And he was also down almost 25 minutes on the clock! }) 28. Qxf3 $13 { [%clk 0:06:34] } 28... Bb6?! { [%clk 0:06:12] } (28... Bd2 29. Re2 c3 $132) 29. Ra6! $36 { Sindarov doesn't miss his chance! After this move, Black's position will be extremely dangerous as we will see: } { [%clk 0:06:28] } 29... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:04:40] } (29... Bxd4 30. Rxc6! Bxe5 (30... Bxe3 31. Rc7 $18) (30... Rxe5 31. Rxe5 Bxe5 (31... Qxc6 32. Rxd5 $16) 32. Rc5) 31. Rc5 $16 { [%csl Rf5,Rb5,Rc4,Rg8][%cal Gc5d5] }) 30. Qh5! { The kid never misses! Sindarov shows why he has achieved so much in the recent months. } { [%clk 0:05:15] } 30... Rxe5! { Already low on time, Andrey starts well.. } { [%clk 0:03:31] } (30... Qb7 31. Rxb6 Qxb6 32. Bxd4 $18 { [%cal Ge3e8,Gh5e8] }) 31. Rxe5 { [%clk 0:05:10] } 31... Qc6?? { But immediately collapses in a very difficult position. It was necessary to find: } { [%clk 0:02:51] } (31... Bc7! 32. Re3 $14 $36 { With very promising position for whute }) (31... Qb7 32. Qg6! $16 Bc5 (32... Qxa6 33. Re7)) 32. bxc4! $18 { The game is over. } { [%clk 0:02:51] } 32... bxc4 { [%clk 0:02:38] } (32... dxc4+ 33. Bf3) 33. Ba4 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 33... Qc5 { [%clk 0:01:00] } (33... Qb7 34. Qg6! { [%cal Ge5e7,Gb7a6] }) 34. Qg6 { [%clk 0:01:18] } 34... Ba7 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 35. Re8! { With both players with less than a minute, the result seems to be decided. } { [%clk 0:00:38] } 35... Rxe8 { [%clk 0:00:28] } 36. Qxe8+ { [%clk 0:00:33] } 36... Kh7?! { [%clk 0:00:25] } 37. Qg6+ { [%clk 0:00:29] } 37... Kg8 { [%clk 0:00:23] } 38. Bd7 { [%clk 0:00:10] } (38. Rd6 { Should win as well. }) 38... c3 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 39. Qe8+ { [%clk 0:00:05] } 39... Kh7 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 40. Qg6+ { Making it to the time control! } { [%clk 0:30:34] } 40... Kg8 { [%clk 0:30:39] } 41. Re6 { 1-0 White wins.
Very interesting game played by both youngsters. Sindarov is off to a great start while Esipenko misses a great chance to score a very important win as Black. Great day of chess! } { [%clk 0:28:14] } 1-0


