{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

We have finally started the long-awaited Candidates Tournament. It's really exciting to see what the players have prepared for this, the most important tournament of the year. In the first round, all the games ended in a draw, but they were quite thrilling nonetheless. I found the match between the two Chinese GMs to be the most fascinating. }
1. e4 { All the games started with the king's pawn move, 1.e4. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { The fashionable Italian variation. } 3... Nf6 4. d3 Be7 (4... Bc5 { This is the other main setup. }) 5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3!? { A safe move. White aims to gain control of the d5 square. } 6... d6 { Black has protected the e5 pawn, and White needs to prepare for ...♞a5. } 7. a4!? { Here, Black has many setups. 7...a5, 7...♝e6, 7...♝g4 are the main moves. } { [%cal Gc4a2] } (7. a3 { The other possible move. }) 7... Na5 8. Ba2! c5 9. Bg5!? { A very logical move. The goal is to capture on f6 and utilize the d5 square. } 9... Nc6 10. Bxf6! Bxf6 11. Nd5 g6 { Preparing ♝g7 allows Black an opportunity to play for the f7-f5 pawn advance. } (11... Be6 { This is of course a natural move and has happened in several games. } 12. c3 g6 13. Qd2 Rc8 (13... Bg7 14. Rab1 { [%cal Gb2b4] } 14... b6 15. b4 Kh8 16. Bc4 $14 { Sargsyan-Bharath, Sharjah 2024 }) 14. h3 b6 15. Rac1 Bg7 16. b4! h6 17. Rfe1 Kh7 18. b5 Na5 19. Qe2 $14 { Wei-Sindarov, Hangzhou rapid 2023 }) 12. c3 Bg7 13. Qd2 Bg4 (13... Kh8 $132 { Exiting from the diagonal also makes sense. } { [%cal Gf7f5] }) (13... Ne7 14. Qg5!? (14. b4 Be6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Rfb1 Rab8 17. Qe3 $14 { Divya-Cyfka, Lublin 2023 }) 14... Nxd5 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Bxd5 $14 { With a strong control over the d5 square, White's natural plan is to play ♖fb1 followed by b2-b4. }) 14. Ng5!? { The players quickly made their moves up to this point. White's plan is f2-f4 for all costs. The roller castle begins now. } 14... h6 15. f4!? { White had a well-prepared, impressive attacking plan for this game. } 15... Kh8?! { A logical move, but ultimately a mistake. Black has spent 10 minutes on this move, likely going beyond her preparation. Now, White has a powerful idea. } (15... hxg5? 16. f5! { The bishop is trapped on g4. } 16... gxf5 17. exf5 $16 { [%csl Rg4] }) (15... exf4! 16. Nxf7! Rxf7 17. Nxf4 Ne5! 18. d4 { Obviously, if Black did not prepare for this, will not pursue this extremely complicated line. } 18... cxd4! 19. cxd4 Kh7! 20. dxe5 Rf8 21. exd6 Be5! $132) (15... Bd7! { The bishop is positioned awkwardly on g4, so it makes sense to retreat it. } 16. Nh3!? { [%cal Gf4f5] } 16... exf4! 17. Nhxf4 Kh7 $132) 16. Ne3! hxg5 17. f5! { The bishop on g4 is poorly placed, and the f5 pawn is quite troublesome for Black. } 17... gxf5 18. exf5 Bh5 19. g4! e4!? { Black makes a clever move. Opening up the g7 diagonal also allows the light pieces access to e5. } 20. dxe4 (20. gxh5! exd3 21. f6! { Opening up the f-file is beneficial, and the f5 square is also a crucial square for White. } 21... Bxf6 22. Qxd3 Be5 23. Rae1! { A very clever prophylactic move against the f7-f5 advance. } 23... Qe7 (23... f5 24. Nxf5 Bf4 { [%cal Gc6e5] } 25. Re6! { [%cal Ge6h6] } 25... Rf6 26. Nxd6! $18) 24. Bb1 f5 25. Nxf5 Qh7 26. Qh3!? $16) 20... Ne5?! { Black played this move immediately in the game; however, transferring the bishop to f4, followed by moving the knight to e5, would have been more precise. I believe this was a critical position where White could have gained a better stance. Jiner didn’t capitalize on this moment and consequently lost the advantage. } (20... Be5! 21. gxh5 Bf4! { [%cal Gc6e5] } 22. f6 Ne5 23. Qe2 Qxf6 24. Kh1 $14) 21. h3?! (21. gxh5! g4 { White likely feared this variation, where Black's plan appears straightforward with ...♝h6, ...♚h7, and ...♜g8. However, White has a powerful maneuver to transfer the knight to e7. } 22. Nd5! Kh7 23. f6! Bh6 24. Qe2 Rg8 25. Ne7 Rg5 26. Bd5 $16) 21... Bg6! 22. fxg6 fxg6 23. Kg2 Qd7 { The position is roughly equal. } 24. Nc4 Rf4 { This is an interesting move that will lead to numerous trades from this point on. } (24... Qxa4 25. Nxe5! Bxe5 26. Bd5 Qb5 27. c4 Qxb2 28. Qxb2 Bxb2 29. Rxa7!? { I believe this was one of the main lines that Jiner calculated on move 24. } 29... Be5 30. Rxf8+ Rxf8 31. Rxb7) 25. Rxf4 gxf4 26. Qxf4 Qxa4 27. Nxe5 dxe5 28. Qg5! Qxe4+ 29. Kg1 c4!? { Locking the bishop is clever; however, White was alert and quickly resolved all problems regarding her rook and bishop positions. } 30. Qh4+ Kg8 31. Re1! Qf4 32. Rf1 Qe3+ 33. Qf2 Qxf2+ 34. Rxf2 Rc8 35. Bb1 Bh6 36. Re2 Kf7 37. Rxe5 Rd8 38. Ba2 Rd1+ 39. Kf2 Rd2+ 40. Ke1 Rxb2 41. Bxc4+ Kf6 { Potential variations could include ♖e6+, ♚g7 and ♖e7+. The position is very much drawish. It was a very exciting first game for the strong Chinese players. } 1/2-1/2


