{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 { Avoiding the main "Marshall" opening is expected in high-level tournaments. } 6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. Nc3 d6 { Now Black is threatening ♞a5, so White needs to save her bishop by playing either a3 or a4. } 9. a3!? Bg4 10. Be3! { Taking control of the d4 square. } 10... Qd7 { The second main move could come as a small surprise to Aleksandra. } (10... Nd4 { This is a big alternative line: } 11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd5 $13 { Black is doing quite well; however, not everyone has a taste for a double-pawn structure like this. }) 11. h3 (11. Nd5 { Although it was a natural move, White immediately questioned what Black intended to do with the g4 pawn. } 11... Rab8!? (11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Be6 13. c4!? $14) 12. c3 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Be6 $132) 11... Be6! (11... Bh5? 12. Nd5! { The black bishop would be poorly placed. } 12... Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Rab8 (13... Bg6 14. c4 $16) 14. Nxe5! { A typical tactical idea against the undefended h5♝. } 14... Nxe5 15. Qxh5 $18) 12. Nd5 Bd8!? { Clearing the e7 square for the bishop is a rather original idea prepared by Kateryna. } 13. Nxf6+ { This is a very simple approach yet highly practical. } (13. Rc1!? { Clearly, the aim is to play c2-c4 as in the game, but with a more unbalanced pawn structure, which was not intended during the game. } 13... Bxd5 (13... h6 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Bxe6 Qxe6 16. c4 Qd7 17. b4 { would be an improved version of game variation. }) 14. exd5 Ne7 15. c4 Rb8! $13) 13... Bxf6 14. Bxe6 Qxe6 15. Rc1!? { The idea of playing c2-c4 seems quite obvious now. } 15... d5 { Kateryna played this move too quickly, suggesting it was part of her preparation. However, it may not be practical if she doesn't recall everything perfectly, as Black has several variations that require precise moves to maintain balance. Black had other solid options available as well. } (15... Ne7!? 16. c4 c5 17. b4 cxb4 18. axb4 Rfb8 $132) (15... a5!? $132) 16. exd5 Qxd5 17. c4! { It could really be expected with the rook on c1. } 17... bxc4 18. Rxc4 { The pawn structure became dubious for Black, and she needed to find a pawn sacrifice to keep the balance. } 18... Rfd8? (18... Nd8!! { A crucial move: Black must transfer the knight to e6 and then occupy the b and d files with rooks. } 19. Rxc7 (19. Rc5!? Qa2!? 20. b4 Ne6 21. Ra5 Rfd8 $132) 19... Ne6! 20. Rc2 Rab8 $44 { Black has a fine compensation. } { [%cal Gf8d8,Gb8b3] }) 19. Qc2! Ne7 20. d4! $16 { It seems that Black may have overlooked this move. } (20. Rxc7 Qxd3 { With a normal, equal position. }) 20... Ng6 { After about 30 minutes of thought, Kateryna made a "best of the worst" strategic move. } (20... exd4 21. Bxd4 Bxd4 22. Rxd4 Qb7 23. Re1! { White is very active, while Black has a significant issue: her queen is awkwardly positioned, and her c7 pawn is quite weak. } 23... Ng6 24. Rb4 Qa7 25. Rc4 $16) (20... e4 21. Ne5! Bxe5 22. dxe5 Qxe5 23. Rxe4 Qf6 24. Rc1 $16 { [%csl Rc7] }) 21. Rc5! Qe6 (21... Qd6 22. dxe5 Nxe5 23. Ng5 $16) 22. Re1! { Aleksandra played another clever move. The rook stands pretty well surely on e1. } 22... Qd6 { This is just losing, but the position is already very sad anyway. } (22... e4 23. Bg5! $16) 23. dxe5! Nxe5 24. Nxe5?? { Unbelievable! There was so much tension in the first round, or perhaps something else, but White missed a very simple trick. } (24. Rxe5! Bxe5 25. Bc5! { And then just taking the bishop with a totally winning position. } { [%cal Gc5d6,Gf3e5] } 25... Qd3 26. Qxd3 Rxd3 27. Rxe5 $18) 24... Bxe5 25. b4 { Fixing some long-term positional pressure, but now Black has found some strong defending ideas. } 25... Re8! { A great regroup. The plan is ♛f6 followed by ♜ad8. } 26. Rd1 (26. Rc6!? Qd7 27. Rd1 Bd6 28. Kf1!? $14) 26... Qf6! { Black needs to be precise, and she does it! } (26... Qe6?! 27. Rc6 Bd6? 28. Bf4 $18 { [%csl Rd6] }) 27. Rcd5 (27. Rc6 Bd6! 28. Bc5?? Bh2+! $132 { [%cal Gf6c6] }) 27... h6! 28. Bd4 { Simplification that makes Black's task easier. } (28. Qd2!? Re6 $13 { [%cal Ga8e8] }) 28... Bxd4 29. R5xd4 Rad8 30. Rxd8 Rxd8 31. Re1 { White does not agree to a draw because of a slightly better structure, but she will never get another chance in this game. } (31. Rxd8+ Qxd8 32. Qc6 Qd1+ 33. Kh2 Qe2! 34. Qxc7 Qxf2 35. Qc8+ Kh7 36. Qxa6 Qf4+ 37. Kg1 Qe3+ 38. Kf1 Qf4+ 39. Ke2 Qe4+) 31... Qd6 32. Qc3 Kh7 33. Qc4 Rd7 34. Qe4+ Kg8 35. Qe8+ Kh7 36. Qe4+ Kg8 37. Qe5 (37. Rc1 Qd3!) 37... Qd3! { Just an active defence till the rest of the game! } (37... Qxe5? 38. Rxe5 $14) 38. h4 Kh7 39. Qe8 h5 40. Qe5 Qd5 { Controlling the fifth rank is important. } 41. Qxd5 Rxd5 42. Rc1 (42. Re7 a5 { It would be the same. }) 42... a5! 43. Rxc7 axb4 44. axb4 Rd1+! { Precise till the end. } (44... Rd4 45. b5 Rxh4 46. Rxf7 Rb4 $13 { It is not a loss for sure, but it is leading to a less clear position. }) 45. Kh2 Rd4 46. g3 Rxb4 47. Rxf7 { We are currently in the book draw, and nothing special happened. It was a big miss for Aleksandra in the very first round! } 47... Kh6 48. Kg2 Rb3 49. Rd7 Ra3 50. Rd6+ Kh7 51. Kf1 Ra2 52. Ke1 g6 53. Rd7+ Kh6 54. Rf7 Rb2 55. Kf1 Ra2 56. Kg2 Ra3 57. Re7 Rb3 58. Re3 Rb2 59. Re7 Rb3 60. Rd7 Ra3 61. f3 Ra2+ 62. Kh3 Ra3 63. Rf7 Rb3 64. g4 hxg4+ 65. Kxg4 Rb5 66. Re7 Ra5 67. Re3 Rb5 68. Re4 Ra5 69. f4 Ra1 70. Re6 Rg1+ 71. Kh3 Rf1 72. Kg3 Kg7 73. Re5 { 1/2-1/2  wins. } 1/2-1/2


