{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

After a very bloody 1st round, day number 2 of the Candidates brought us a very peaceful day. All 4 games ended up in draws. But, as we will see in 2 of them, there were still very interesting moments.

Pragg, who had a strong start after beating Giri in round 1, had the difficult task of facing Wei Yi with the black pieces. The 26-year-old former prodigy (whom I faced 10 years ago and he was already a 2700!), didn't manage to create any sort of real chances as White. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:59:54] } 1... e6!? { Although Pragg has played the French before (even in 2026), it was already a bit surprising. } { [%clk 1:58:44] } 2. d4 { [%clk 1:59:45] } 2... d5 { [%clk 1:58:30] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:23] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:57:53] } 4. e5 { [%clk 1:59:04] } 4... Nfd7 { [%clk 1:57:45] } 5. f4 { [%clk 1:58:57] } 5... c5 { [%clk 1:57:38] } 6. Nf3 { [%clk 1:58:46] } 6... Nc6 { [%clk 1:57:27] } 7. Be3 { [%clk 1:58:39] } 7... Be7 { [%clk 1:56:46] } (7... a6 8. Qd2 b5) (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 { These are two different options that Black could also consider while playing this line. }) 8. Qd2 { [%clk 1:55:05] } 8... a6 { [%clk 1:56:15] } 9. Bd3 { [%clk 1:47:33] } 9... O-O { This is already a tricky move order. As we will see, Pragg's strategy will pay off. More common is: } { [%clk 1:55:18] } (9... b5 10. Qf2 b4 11. Na4 c4 12. Be2 Nb6 13. Nc5 $14) 10. O-O?! { After spending more than 10 minutes, Wei Yi goes wrong. This very natural move is already a bit unprecise. In order to fight for an edge, White has to play the following: } { [%clk 1:35:15] } (10. dxc5! Qa5!? { I can imagine this could have been Pragg's idea. } (10... Nxc5 11. Bxc5 Bxc5 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Qd3 Re8 15. Qh7+ { This position was played between Cheparinov-Bluebaum and it feels extremely dangerous for Black, as White ended up winning that game.
Cheparinov, I. - Bluebaum, M., 1-0, Bundesliga 2023-24, lichess.org/fvEnuIIW }) 11. O-O-O!? (11. O-O Nxc5 { This position seems to be a bit more chill. }) 11... Nxc5 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. h4 $36 { White's initiative is already pretty strong. } 13... f5!?) 10... f6! { Playing fast, Pragg is already very happy after this very natural pawn break. From now on, Black will be the one fighting for the advantage. } { [%clk 1:52:29] } 11. exf6 { [%clk 1:13:02] } 11... Nxf6 { Although it feels ok, White's position is already a bit hard to play. As we will see in the line with 12.Rae1 } { [%clk 1:51:30] } 12. Kh1 { [%clk 1:12:20] } (12. Rae1?! c4! 13. Be2 Bb4 $15 { [%cal Gf6e4] }) 12... b6 { [%clk 1:50:04] } (12... c4 { 12..c4 is not as precise as it was with Rae1 because the Q will be able to use that very important square. } 13. Be2 Bb4 14. Qe1 Ne4 15. Ne5 $132) 13. Ne5?! { Very natural but not precise. Wei Yi had better options like: } { [%clk 1:03:38] } (13. Nd1!? { [%cal Gd1f2] } 13... c4 14. Be2 Ne4 15. Qc1 { c2 needs to be protected and with Nf2 coming next, White should be ok. } { [%cal Gd1f2] } (15. Qe1 Nb4! $17)) 13... Qc7 { [%clk 1:40:08] } 14. Rae1 { [%clk 0:54:40] } 14... Bd6?! { Pragg was probably a bit tempted to apply pressure against e5 due to d4 not being very stable, but 14...Bb7 was already simple and very good. } { [%clk 1:38:12] } (14... Bb7! { [%cal Bc6d4,Bc5d4,Ba8e8] } 15. Nxc6 (15. Qf2 { Despite the Q's effort to support d4, Black still gets a very nice position after: } 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Ne2 (17. Qxd4 Bc5 { [%csl Rd4] }) 17... Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Nxd4 Rf6 $15 $36 { Pawn structure is not very good looking, but Black's pair of bishops and the position being open should favour Black. } { [%csl Be7,Bb7][%cal Bb7g2] }) 15... Bxc6 { With c4 and Bb4 coming, Black is simply better. } { [%cal Gc5c4,Ge7b4] }) (14... Nxd4?! { Simply worse, as Black is not ready yet. } 15. Bxd4 cxd4 16. Ne2 $14 { [%cal Be2d4] }) 15. Nxc6?! { [%clk 0:48:45] } (15. dxc5 { Wei Yi misses this resource. It wasn't simple since giving up the control of the center is only justified due to the concrete pressure against c5. } 15... bxc5 16. Na4! $132 { The key move! } 16... Ne7 (16... c4?! 17. Bb6!) 17. c3 { [%csl Re5,Rc5][%cal Bd6e5,Be3c5] }) 15... Qxc6 { [%clk 1:37:18] } 16. Be2 { [%clk 0:48:29] } 16... Ra7 { Creative, but again missing the main opportunity. A better option was probably insisting with: } { [%clk 1:30:24] } (16... c4! $15 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gb6b5,Gb5b4] } 17. Bf3 b5 18. a3 a5 { Black is very solid in the center/K side while he expects to make some solid improvement on the Q side. } { [%cal Gb5b4] }) 17. Bf3 { [%clk 0:46:44] } 17... Raf7?! { Pragg misses his last real chance to seize the initiative. The pattern of releasing the tension with c4 was probably the best way to fight for more. } { [%clk 1:24:39] } (17... c4 18. Nd1 b5 19. c3 a5 20. Nf2 b4 $15 { [%cal Gc6a4,Ga7b7] }) 18. f5! $13 { Wei Yi doesn't miss the chance to get active! } { [%clk 0:33:29] } 18... c4!? { Although it finally happened, Pragg finds this good resource but already late to create chances. } { [%clk 0:48:30] } (18... exf5 19. dxc5 Bxc5 20. Nxd5 Ne4 $13 { It should be around balanced. }) 19. Bg5 { [%csl Re6][%cal Rf3d5] [%clk 0:28:18] } 19... Bb4 $7 { [%clk 0:45:45] } 20. Qe2 { [%clk 0:18:57] } (20. fxe6 Bxe6 21. Qe2 { Was probbaly good enough to equalise. Yet, it probablt makes more sense to keep the tension. } 21... Bxc3 22. Qxe6 Qxe6 23. Rxe6 Ne4!? 24. bxc3 Nxg5 25. Re3 $10 (25. Rxb6 Nxf3 26. gxf3 Rxf3 27. Rxf3 Rxf3 $15 { [%cal Gf3c3] })) 20... Bxc3 { [%clk 0:33:18] } (20... Ne4 21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. f6 h6 (22... gxf6 23. Bh6 $36) 23. Bh4 gxf6 24. Qh5 (24. Nxe4!?)) 21. fxe6 { [%clk 0:18:49] } 21... Re7 { [%clk 0:32:13] } (21... Bxe6 22. Qxe6 Qxe6 23. Rxe6 Ne4!? { Maybe would have been a good try for Pragg. But pretty sure Wei Yi would have found the following to equalise. } 24. bxc3 Nxg5 25. Re3 $10 { Despite being a little bit passive, White should hold this safely due to Black's pawn structure being vulnerable as well. } { [%csl Rd5,Rb6][%cal Gh1g1] }) 22. bxc3 { [%clk 0:18:34] } 22... Rxe6 { [%clk 0:32:07] } 23. Qd2 { [%clk 0:17:11] } 23... Ne4 $10 { The position is simplifying now. } { [%clk 0:28:44] } 24. Bxe4 { [%clk 0:17:04] } 24... Rxf1+ { [%clk 0:28:29] } 25. Rxf1 { [%clk 0:17:00] } 25... Rxe4 { [%clk 0:28:24] } 26. Bf4! { The bishop's right place is e5. } { [%clk 0:13:36] } 26... Re7 { [%clk 0:26:09] } 27. Be5 { [%clk 0:13:14] } 27... Qg6 { [%clk 0:25:35] } 28. Qf4 { [%clk 0:12:37] } 28... Rf7 $10 { [%clk 0:25:12] } 29. Qxf7+ { [%clk 0:12:33] } 29... Qxf7 { [%clk 0:25:10] } 30. Rxf7 { [%clk 0:12:29] } 30... Kxf7 { [%clk 0:25:06] } 31. Kg1 { [%clk 0:12:04] } 31... Bf5 { [%clk 0:24:51] } 32. Kf2 { [%clk 0:11:57] } 32... Bxc2 { Despite winning the pawn, Black knows this is just completely drawn due to the opposite color bishop. } { [%clk 0:24:45] } 33. Bc7 { [%clk 0:11:31] } 33... b5 { [%clk 0:24:40] } 34. a3 { [%clk 0:11:19] } 34... Ke6 { [%clk 0:24:31] } 35. Ke3 { [%clk 0:11:16] } 35... Kf5 { [%clk 0:23:52] } 36. h3 { [%clk 0:07:40] } 36... h5 { [%clk 0:22:43] } 37. g3 { [%clk 0:07:29] } 37... g5 { [%clk 0:22:08] } 38. Bd8 { [%clk 0:07:23] } 38... Bd3 { [%clk 0:21:50] } 39. h4 { [%clk 0:07:15] } 39... Kg4 { [%clk 0:20:53] } 40. Bxg5 { [%clk 0:37:33] } 40... Kxg3 { [%clk 0:51:17] } 41. Bd8 { [%clk 0:37:41] } 41... Be4 { [%clk 0:50:02] } 42. Be7 { [%clk 0:37:56] } 42... Kg2 { [%clk 0:50:24] } 43. Bd8 { [%clk 0:38:09] } 43... Kf1 { [%clk 0:50:32] } 44. Kd2 { [%clk 0:38:37] } 44... Kf2 { [%clk 0:50:58] } 45. Be7 { [%clk 0:39:02] } 45... Kf3 { [%clk 0:51:24] } 46. Bd8 { A very interesting game. Pragg had a very successful opening due to a tricky move order (the importance of innovating, even in very well known positions!) that offered him some great practical chances. On the other hand, Wei Yi failed to create any real chances with white and is still with 50% after 2 draws. } { [%clk 0:39:28] } 1/2-1/2


