{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

The second round finished with Naka playing, again, the longest game of the day against Andrey Esipenko. Despite the difficulty that represents playing 2 games with black in a row in such event, Hikaru is very likely not very happy with how things are going since Esipenko was the one pressing most of the game. }
1. c4 { [%clk 1:59:51] } 1... e6 { [%clk 1:59:49] } 2. g3 { [%clk 1:59:40] } 2... d5 { [%clk 1:59:20] } 3. Bg2 { [%clk 1:59:27] } 3... Nf6!? { [%clk 1:59:13] } (3... d4 { Would have led to a pawn structure similar to how his game against Caruana was. }) 4. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:19] } 4... c5 { [%clk 1:53:34] } 5. cxd5 { [%clk 1:51:51] } 5... Nxd5!? { [%clk 1:51:38] } (5... exd5 6. d4 { This would have led to a very typical Tarrasch structure }) 6. O-O { [%clk 1:47:43] } 6... Be7 { Considering that Hikaru already invested more than 10 minutes to play Be7, it makes me feel that he was not particularly prepared to play this position against Andrey. } { [%clk 1:39:18] } (6... Nc6 7. d4 { Has been played most of the times in this position. }) 7. d4 { [%clk 1:46:12] } 7... cxd4 { [%clk 1:38:52] } (7... O-O 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qc2 Be7 10. Rd1 { This was probably something that Hikaru was trying to avoid. White's position is simply easier to play. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }) 8. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:35:52] } 8... O-O { [%clk 1:38:08] } 9. Qb3 { [%clk 1:32:08] } 9... Nc6 { Black accepts to play with a worse pawn structure but will justify it by playing actively. } { [%clk 1:34:50] } 10. Nxc6 { [%clk 1:27:04] } (10. Rd1 Nxd4 11. Rxd4 Qb6! { After this move, Black should be able to hold without much suffering. } 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. Bxd5 Rd8 $10) 10... bxc6 { [%clk 1:34:33] } 11. e4 { Black's knight is too strong. } { [%clk 1:25:43] } 11... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:46] } (11... Nb6 { This move should be playable as well, with White always holding a slight advantage. } 12. Bf4 (12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Nc3 e5 { Despite the c6 weakness, Black should be ok in this position. } { [%cal Gc8e6] }) 12... Ba6 13. Rd1 (13. Rc1 c5) 13... Qc8 14. a4 Rd8 { [%cal Gb6d7] } 15. Na3 Nd7 { White is slowly better, but Black is definitely in the game. } { [%cal Gd7c5] }) 12. h3 { [%csl Ge3] [%clk 1:24:14] } 12... Ba6 { [%clk 0:58:26] } 13. Rd1 { [%clk 1:23:17] } 13... Qb6 { [%clk 0:55:40] } 14. Be3 { [%clk 1:17:41] } 14... Bc5!? { [%clk 0:53:56] } (14... Qxb3 15. axb3 $36 { [%cal Ga1a6,Ge3a7] }) 15. Bxc5 { [%clk 1:16:11] } 15... Qxc5 { [%clk 0:53:54] } 16. Qc3 { [%clk 1:02:30] } (16. Nc3!? { In my opinion, this would have been a very nice try by Andrey to increase White's advantage. } 16... Rab8?! (16... Rfd8!?) 17. Na4! { Key detail to allow the white Q to get to c2. } 17... Qa5 18. Qc2 $16 { [%cal Ga4c5] }) 16... Qb6! { Black can never allow the Q trade under the current circumstances as it is going to be necessary to create counterplay. } { [%clk 0:43:24] } (16... Qxc3 17. Nxc3 $16 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Ga1c1,Gb2b3,Gc3a4] }) 17. Nd2 { [%clk 0:52:26] } 17... c5! { Hikaru shows the way! Black needs to play active, even at the cost of weakening his position. } { [%clk 0:42:38] } 18. b3 { [%clk 0:38:20] } 18... Rad8 { [%clk 0:33:36] } 19. Nc4 { [%clk 0:36:23] } 19... Bxc4 { [%clk 0:30:17] } (19... Qb4?! 20. Qxb4 cxb4 21. Na5 $16 { Even after fixing the pawn structure, White is just dominating the position with better pieces. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Re4e5,Rg2c6,Ra5c6] }) 20. Qxc4 { [%clk 0:36:16] } 20... e5 { [%clk 0:30:11] } (20... Qa5!? { Always seeking and looking to bother White's pawn structure. } { [%csl Ra2] }) 21. Rac1 { [%clk 0:28:18] } 21... Rxd1+ { [%clk 0:25:14] } (21... Rd4!? { Hikaru probably didn't like the resulting endgame. } 22. Rxd4 (22. Qc2 Rfd8) 22... cxd4 23. Qc7 Re8 $10 { I guess Naka was a bit worried about this endgame, but objectively speaking it should be holdable with precise play } { [%csl Be5,Bd4][%cal Gg8f8,Gf6e4] } 24. Qxb6 axb6 25. Rc6 Kf8 { Although it wasn't simple to assess, Black should have full compensation due to the strength of the d4 pawn and the rook getting active. } { [%cal Ge8a8,Ge8c8] } 26. Rxb6 Rc8 { [%cal Gc8c1,Gd4d3] }) 22. Rxd1 $14 { White's advantage is very stable here. } { [%clk 0:28:16] } 22... a5 { [%clk 0:25:07] } 23. Rc1 $14 { [%clk 0:25:29] } 23... Rc8 { [%clk 0:24:29] } 24. Qc3 { [%csl Re5,Ra5] [%clk 0:25:06] } 24... Qc7 { [%clk 0:23:45] } 25. h4 { [%