{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

We have reached the second round, and surprisingly, all games have ended in a draw. The players are playing very solidly. In this game, there was a significant imbalance, with Jiner dominating early on. Kateryna sacrificed a pawn but did not have sufficient compensation for that move. Although Black had a winning position, both players made several major mistakes in mutual time trouble, ultimately leading to a draw with perpetual check. Once again, Kateryna saved the game. }
1. e4 e6 { In the Open section today, Pragg also played the French Defence. I would say that anyone who chose this opening is ready for a big, complicated battle. } 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 { The Tarrasch variation is typically solid; however, as we will see in the game, White showed a creative and relatively new concept. } 3... c5! { I always thought this was the most critical move: Black needs to fight for control of the center. } 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd6 { Everything has been normal so far, but now let's see the rare and exciting concept of White. } 7. Ne4!? { White immediately attacks the queen and uses the g8 knight, which is not on f6 yet. The problem is that white's c1♗ will be blocked. However, there are numerous interesting lines here. The Russian GM, Mikhail Antipov, has several games with this move. } (7. O-O { This common move has been played in thousands of games. }) 7... Qb4+ 8. Nfd2 Nf6 { After around 10 minutes of thought, Jiner played this natural move. The other option would have been to develop the knight on b8 with ♞c6. } (8... Nc6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 { Just transposes to the game. }) 9. Nxf6+ gxf6 10. O-O Nc6 11. Re1 { Kateryna has thought for about 20 minutes on this move. I would say she tried to recall her analysis. I think she has considered whether to play c2-c3 right now or delay the move. } 11... Bd7 12. c3! { The entire concept is based on this move. White aims to open up the position and gain time, as Black has lost some tempos with the queen. } 12... Qb6 (12... dxc3 13. bxc3 Qa5! (13... Qxc3? { This is surely too much. } 14. Rb1! $18 { [%cal Gc1b2,Gb1b7] }) 14. Bf1!? $44 { Opening up the c4 square for the knight. }) 13. cxd4?! { After 20 minutes of thought, Kateryna played this move. It turns out that the queen on d4 will be quite annoying. From this point on, White started to go downhill in the next few moves. } (13. Bf1! { We have previously encountered this concept. The goal is to occupy the c4 square with White's knight. } 13... dxc3 14. Nc4 Qc7 15. bxc3 $44 { White has reasonable compensation for the pawn. The plan is: b1, f3, and doing some pressure. }) 13... Qxd4! (13... Nxd4 14. Nf3! Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 $44 { [%cal Gf3f6,Gc1e3] }) 14. Ne4?! { It seems like a clever tactical move, but Black can easily defend the weakness on f6. } (14. Bf1!? Be7 15. Qh5 $15) 14... Be7! $17 { Black has a healthy extra pawn and a superior position. } 15. Qe2?! (15. Bf1!? { A more stubborn idea is to overprotect the g2 weakness. } 15... Rg8 $17 (15... f5 16. Nc3 a6 $15)) 15... f5! 16. Nc3 Qg4 (16... Rg8!? { This was another option. Black has a strong domination on the kingside. } 17. Be3 Qh4! { [%cal Gf5f4] } 18. f4 a6! 19. Rad1 Nb4!! 20. a3 Bc6 { And now we see the point of 19...b4. } { [%csl Rg2] } 21. axb4 (21. g3?? Rxg3+ 22. hxg3 Qxg3+ 23. Kf1 Qh3+ 24. Kg1 Qh1+ 25. Kf2 Qg2#) 21... Rxg2+ 22. Qxg2 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Bxb4 $17) 17. f3 (17. Qxg4!? fxg4 18. Bf4 Rc8 19. Rad1 a6 $15) 17... Qg7 $17 18. Bf4? { It is a significant mistake to allow d4 for Black. } (18. Be3 { A more stubborn defense. White must cover the d4 square. } 18... O-O 19. Rad1 Rfd8 $15) 18... Nd4! 19. Qf2 Nxf3+!? { Utilize the fact that the c4 is undefended. } (19... Bc5! $19 { Even more unpleasant for White. } { [%cal Gc5g1] }) 20. Qxf3 Qd4+ 21. Kh1 Qxc4 22. Qg3 (22. b3!? Qc5 23. Na4 Bc6!? 24. Nxc5 Bxf3 25. Nxe6 fxe6 26. gxf3 Kf7 $19) 22... Bc6! { Obviously,the bishop stands wonderfully on c6. } 23. Rad1 Bf6?! (23... Rd8! { The most precise move. Black must be prepared to sacrifice the h8 for the f4. After that, Black's bishop pair and two strong pawns will be much better. } 24. Rxd8+ (24. Qg7 Rxd1 25. Qxh8+ Bf8 26. Rxd1 Qxf4) 24... Kxd8! 25. Qg7 Qxf4 26. Qxh8+ Kc7 27. Qe5+ Qxe5 28. Rxe5 Kd6 29. Re1 a5! $19 { [%cal Gf5f4] }) 24. h3!? { A clever waiting move. } 24... h5?! { A logical move, but objectively it's a mistake. White has a valuable resource: the g6 square in a key variation; that's why the pawn is better placed on h7 than h5. } (24... Rd8?! 25. Bg5! Bxg5 26. Qxg5 Rd7 27. Qg3 $44) (24... a6! { Controlling the b5 square is a useful move, and it turns out to be the most accurate one! } 25. Be5 Bxe5 26. Qxe5 Rg8 27. Rd4 (27. Nd5 Bxd5 28. Rxd5 Qh4!? $17) 27... Bxg2+ 28. Kh2 Qc6 29. Rd6 Bf3!! 30. Qxe6+ (30. Re2 Qc8! 31. Red2 Bc6! $19 { [%cal Ge8e7,Gc8b8] }) 30... fxe6 31. Rexe6+ Kf7 32. Rf6+ Kg7 $19) 25. h4? { Preventing h5-h4 comes with a high cost. The h4 pawn is a major weakness, making White's king much more vulnerable than before. Additionally, the g4 square is greatly weakened. In conclusion, this pawn push is a losing move } (25. Be5! { It's a very smart idea for White to exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 25... Bxe5 (25... h4 26. Qh2! Bxe5 27. Qxe5 Rg8 28. Rd4 Bxg2+ 29. Kh2 Qc6 30. Rd6! Bf3 31. Qxe6+ { Again we have this wonderful draw. } 31... fxe6 32. Rexe6+ Kf7 33. Rf6+) (25... f4 26. Bxf4 h4 27. Qg4! $13) 26. Qxe5 Rg8 { It appears that Black is winning, but White has a defense! } 27. Rd4! Bxg2+ (27... Qa6 28. Rd6!) 28. Kh2 Qc6 29. Rd6! Bf3! { With the idea of ...g2, it seems like White is collapsing! But! } 30. Qxe6+!! { What an incredible save! Now White has a perpetual check! } (30. Rxc6? Rg2+ 31. Kh1 Re2+ 32. Kg1 Rxe5 33. Rxe5 Bxc6 $19) 30... fxe6 31. Rexe6+ Kf7 32. Rf6+ Kg7 33. Rg6+! { Now we see why 24...h5?! was a dubious idea. } 33... Kh7 34. Rh6+) 25... Rd8! 26. Bg5 Bxg5 27. Qxg5 Rc8? (27... Rd7! $19 { Staying on the d-file is the strongest idea. In a mutual time trouble, both players made several serious mistakes. } { [%cal Gc4g4] } 28. Rxd7 Kxd7 29. Rd1+ Kc8 $19) 28. Rd2? { The goal is to double the rooks and overprotect the g2 pawn. However, this provided Black with another opportunity to secure her king and realize her material advantage. } (28. Nb5!! { A fantastic tactical saving move! Black is in different unpleasant motifs. } 28... Bxb5 (28... Qxb5 29. Rxe6+! fxe6 (29... Kf8 30. Qe7+ Kg7 31. Qg5+) 30. Qg6+ Kf8 31. Qf6+ Kg8 32. Qg6+) 29. Rc1! { [%cal Gc1c8] } 29... Qxc1 30. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 31. Qxc1 Bc6 $132 { [%cal Gh8g8,Ge8f8] }) 28... Qb4? { Preparing e7... It's too slow. White can now force a draw. } (28... Kf8! 29. Red1 (29. Rd8+ Rxd8 30. Qxd8+ Be8! $19 { [%cal Gh8g8,Gc4g4] }) 29... Re8!? 30. Rd8 Qg4 $19) (28... Qg4! 29. Qf6 O-O! $19 { [%cal Gg8h7,Gg4g7] }) 29. Rxe6+! fxe6 30. Qg6+ Kf8 31. Qf6+ Kg8 32. Qg6+ Kf8 33. Qf6+ Kg8 34. Qg6+ Kf8 { 1/2-1/2  wins. } 1/2-1/2


