1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 h6!? { This waiting move is quite useful nowadays and is probably more fashionable than 3...a6. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 { White is ready to play the "Carlsbad" pawn structure. } 5... c6 6. e3 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Bd3 Ne7 { From this moment onward, we have a typical Carlsbad issue with the preparation of the ♝f5 move, which is strategically important for Black. } 9. Qc2 { White is fighting against the Black's idea. } 9... O-O (9... Qf6!? { Preparing ...♝f5 seems the most accurate. } 10. Nge2 Bf5 11. O-O O-O $132) 10. Nf3 (10. Nge2!? { Playing against ...♛f6, ♝f5 makes sense too. } 10... Qf6 (10... Nd7 11. O-O Nf6 12. f3!? $14) 11. Ng3! $14) 10... Nd7 { Black decided to transfer her knight to f6, which is also a decent plan. } 11. O-O { This means a calm game is expected. White could gain something sharper, like h3-g4, but it would definitely be riskier as well. } (11. h3!? Nf6 12. g4 Nd7! $132 { [%cal Gc6c5] }) 11... Nf6 12. h3 g6! { The bishop on c8 is one of Black's worst pieces, and they really need to trade it. } 13. Rab1 (13. Nh4!? { We can understand the point - to prevent ...♝f5 - but still, humanly it is not easy to make such a weird-looking move in such a big tournament! } 13... Kg7 14. Rab1 Ne8 $132 { [%cal Gd6f6] }) 13... a5 (13... Bf5!? { The simplest approach. } 14. b4 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Rac8 { It is very close to equal. } { [%cal Ge7f5] }) 14. Na4 (14. Nh4!? $132) 14... Bf5! { Black is usually in a fine position in Carlsbad after this move. } 15. Nc5 Qc7 16. Rfc1 Nd7 (16... Bxd3 { Again, the simplest approach is just to trade. } 17. Qxd3 Nf5 $132 { [%cal Gf5d6] }) 17. Na4 { This is completely harmless. White could try: } (17. b4!? axb4 18. Rxb4 Nxc5 19. dxc5 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 Rxa2 21. Rcb1 Ra7 22. Qb3 Rb8 23. Qb2 $44 { With an interesting compensation for the pawn. }) 17... Rfe8 18. Nc3 Qd6 { Position is equal, and now we see a psychological battle for some initiative. } 19. Ne2 Qf6 20. Nf4 Bxd3 21. Nxd3 Nf5! { Another important pattern in the Carlsbad structure is that the square d6 is an ideal position for the black knight. } 22. b4 Nd6 23. a4 Qe7 24. bxa5 Rxa5 25. Rb4 Rea8 26. Rcb1 R8a7 27. Qb3 Qd8 { With the next few moves, Black clearly shows she is ready for a draw. } (27... h5!?) 28. Nfe5 Kg7 29. Qd1 Qe7 30. Qb3 Qd8 31. Qd1 Qe7 32. Nxd7!? { White correctly felt the moment to continue! } 32... Qxd7 33. Nc5 Qc8 (33... Qc7!? 34. Qf3 b5! 35. axb5 Nxb5 $132) 34. Qf3 Ne4? { Losing patience, and this could cost the game! } (34... b5! 35. axb5 (35. Qf4 Qd8 36. axb5 Nxb5 37. Qe5+ Qf6) 35... Nxb5 { Black should be able to maintain this slightly worse position quite comfortably. }) 35. Rxb7! (35. Nxe4?! dxe4 36. Qxe4 Rxa4 37. d5!? $14) 35... Rxb7 36. Rxb7 Ng5 37. Qg3? { White was seeking a quick tactical solution instead of a technical approach. } (37. Qg4! Qxg4 38. hxg4 { Black is collapsing now. } { [%cal Gb7b6] } 38... Ne4 39. Nxe4 dxe4 40. Rb4 $18 { The endgame should be winning for White. } { [%cal Gb4c4,Gf2f3] }) 37... Rxc5! { That was a great move and calculation; obviously, it saved the game! } 38. Qe5+! (38. dxc5?? Qxb7 $19) 38... Kh7 39. Rb8 { It looks like White is winning, but let's see what happens! } 39... Rc1+! 40. Kh2 { Is it all over now? Not really... } 40... Qxh3+!! { Desperate, but it's working! Black is surviving now. } 41. gxh3 Nf3+ 42. Kg2 Nxe5 43. dxe5 Ra1 44. Ra8 { Draw and big miss for White. } 1/2-1/2


