{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

Day 3 of the Candidates didn't disappoint. We had four interesting games, with 50% of them bringing a decisive result. Fabiano Caruana and Javokhir Sindarov were the two winners of the day and are both in the lead with 2.5/3 (full point ahead of Bluebaum and Pragg) . With many rounds left, 11 to be more precise, there are still plenty of opportunities for all the contenders.

Today, we are going to start with the shortest game of the tournament so far. Just 19 moves were necessary for Caruana to earn a full point against Wei Yi, who started the game strong showing deep prep. But, soon after, he made 2 very significant mistakes that led to lose the game immediately. }
1. Nf3 { At this point and after getting a win vs Nakamura in Round 1, it seems that we will see Fabi playing a lot of Rétis/Catalans in this tourney. } { [%clk 1:59:57] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:49] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:50] } 2... c5 { [%clk 1:59:44] } 3. g3 { [%clk 1:59:44] } 3... g6 { [%clk 1:59:38] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:23] } 4... d5 { Despite not being a very common move order, this move shouldn't change much of the nature in the position. } { [%clk 1:59:07] } (4... Bg7 5. Bg2 d5 { It is more common but, again, it shouldn't change much. }) 5. cxd5 { [%clk 1:59:16] } 5... Nxd5 { [%clk 1:59:00] } 6. Bg2 { White already has a couple of options after Black breaks with d5. Among them is: } { [%clk 1:54:05] } (6. Qb3 Nb4 7. Ne4 Bg7 8. Nxc5 N8c6 9. Bg2 Qa5 10. Qc4 b6 11. Nb3 Qa6 $44 { This position has been played by Pragg a couple of times, with mixed results. Black is down a pawn but very active. }) 6... Bg7 { [%clk 1:58:13] } 7. Qa4+!? { After investing 20 minutes, Caruana decides to go for a sharper variation. Options like 7.h4 or 0-0 would have been calmer. } { [%clk 1:32:12] } (7. h4 { This move is very popular in this structure. White's idea will be to provoke Black to play h5 or h6 or get the opportunity to play for h5. } 7... Nc6 (7... h6 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 { [%cal Gc1h6,Bg7c3,Bd5c3] }) 8. h5 Bf5 9. h6 Bf6 10. O-O { With a balanced position. }) 7... Nc6 { [%clk 1:56:57] } (7... Bd7 8. Qc4 { White's intention is to take advantage of c5, as the pawn is not so easy to defend due to the strong bishop on g2. } { [%csl Rc5][%cal Gg2b7] }) 8. Ng5 { [%clk 1:30:25] } (8. Qc4 { It shouldn't be very good now } 8... Ndb4 9. O-O Qa5 { Black is very comfortable } { [%cal Gc8e6] }) 8... Nb6!? { Playing fast, Wei shows that he is not new to this position. Black improves the 8...e6 that has been played before. He is ready to sac pawns for activity. } { [%clk 1:56:20] } (8... e6 9. Nge4 Nb6 10. Qd1 Qe7 11. d3 { [%csl Rd6,Bf4,Be3,Rc5][%cal Bc1e3,Be3f4,Be3c5,Bf4d6] }) 9. Bxc6+ $7 { Fabi understands that not taking would have led to a simply worse position. As a result, he accepts the challenge.
Following the game closely, I honestly felt that today was going to be a pretty tough day for Fabi. Already down more than 30 mins on the clock and with Wei Yi still in prep, it was hard to imagine that White would win this in less than 10 moves from now. } { [%clk 1:22:17] } (9. Qd1 c4 $15 { Black is just better here due to better development and coordination. } { [%csl Rg5] }) 9... bxc6 { [%clk 1:55:06] } 10. Qxc6+ { [%clk 1:22:14] } 10... Bd7 { [%clk 1:55:00] } 11. Qxc5 { [%clk 1:18:39] } 11... h6 { Simple but good. Wei needs to play fast to show the quality of his compensation. } { [%clk 1:52:43] } (11... O-O 12. O-O Rc8 13. Qa5 $14) 12. Nf3 { [%clk 1:18:18] } (12. Nge4? f5) 12... Rc8 { [%clk 1:52:34] } 13. Qa5 { [%clk 1:18:01] } 13... Bh3 { [%clk 1:51:37] } 14. Qb5+!? { I liked this move. White is forcing Black to put the N on d7, since trading Qs or playing Kf8 is not exactly what Black wants to do. } { [%clk 1:01:31] } (14. Rg1 { Similar to the game, White is always trying to play for g4. } 14... Qd6 15. g4 h5 $132) 14... Nd7 { [%clk 1:47:40] } 15. Rg1! { Caruana correctly understands that going for g4 is more important than grabbing the center or trying to develop the B on c1. } { [%clk 0:55:26] } 15... O-O { Wei Yi was still playing fast. Objectively speaking, 15...Bg4 was very likely forcing White to repeat. } { [%clk 1:45:07] } (15... Bg4!? { White's K doesn't have a good square and the K could be very exposed. With close to an 1-hour gap, I would imagine that Caruana would be happy to accept the draw. } { [%csl Rf3] } 16. Kf1 Bh3+ 17. Ke1 Bg4 $10) 16. g4 { [%clk 0:53:00] } 16... Rc5?! { After deliberating for 30 minutes, Wei Yi makes his first mistake. This natural move actually helps White by letting the Q get to b3. Better was: } { [%clk 1:17:28] } (16... Nf6 { [%csl Rg4] } 17. g5 (17. Qa4 { [%cal Bg1g3,Bg3h3] } 17... Qc7 18. Rg3 h5! 19. gxh5 Bd7 $15 { Very difficult position for both players. }) 17... hxg5 18. Nxg5 Bd7 19. Qb4 $132 { It is extremely hard to predict what would happen, but we can definitely say that Black has compensation for both pawns due to White's lack of development. } { [%cal Gb4h4] }) 17. Qb3! $16 { Very precise. Caruana is already aiming at the B on h3, Black's compensation is already at risk. } { [%cal Gb3h3] [%clk 0:43:22] } (17. Qa4?! Qc7 { [%cal Gc5c4,Gc4g4,Gh3g4] }) 17... Ne5? { The final mistake and game over. Wei needed to hit the g4 pawn in order to keep the fight going. } { [%clk 0:56:08] } (17... Nf6 18. d4! { Another reason why 16..Rc5 was wrong. } 18... Rc8 19. Ne5 { [%cal Gb3g8,Ge5g6,Gg1g3] } 19... Qxd4 20. Nxg6 Nxg4 21. Nd1 { [%cal Gd1f2,Gb3h3] }) 18. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:36:33] } 18... Rxe5 { [%clk 0:48:08] } 19. Nd1! { 1-0 White wins.
A very elegant touch. Black's bishop is lost and, with no chances to complicate, decides to resign.
A very important win for Caruana that keeps him in the lead. On the other hand, first loss for Wei Yi after getting a very interesting position out of the opening. } { [%cal Gb3h3] [%clk 0:36:09] } 1-0


