{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

Finally, in round 3, two games were decided, surprisingly in Black's favor. One of these matches featured a young Chinese Grandmaster playing against a young Kazakh Grandmaster, and it was quite thrilling. White gained the upper hand in the opening and middlegame; however, Bibisara defended tenaciously. Jiner made some bad mistakes, allowing Bibisara to convert her advantage into a winning endgame. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { The Rossolimo variation is a very fashionable line nowadays. In this round, we have seen another game played on this line.  The main point is that White aims to spoil Black's pawn structure, while Black has the compensation of the bishop pair. However, this is just the basics; there are, of course, many complicated variations. } 3... d6 (3... g6 { This has been played in the Goryachkina-Divya game. } 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 Qc7 7. d3 d6 8. e5!! { This is a very nice concept. White effectively disrupts Black's pawn structure while maintaining a strong pawn formation and an advantageous position throughout the game. Aleksandra played a strong positional game and outplayed her opponent; however, she made an unexpected mistake in the rook endgame, which ultimately led to her downfall. } 8... dxe5 9. Na3 Nf6 10. Nxe5 Nd5 11. Nac4 O-O 12. Qe2! $14 f6 13. Nf3 e5 14. Be3 Bg4?! 15. h3 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Rad8 18. Re2 h5 19. Rae1 Kh7 20. h4 Rd5 21. g3 Rf7 22. Qg2 Rd8 23. b3 Rd5 24. Qf3 Rf8 25. Re3 Bh6 26. Re4 Bg7 27. Qg2 $16 { Goryachkina-Divya, 2026 }) 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1! { The rook is usually well-placed on e1, where it overprotects the e4 pawn and prepares e4-e5 in some lines. Additionally, the f1 square becomes available for the white bishop. } 5... Nf6 6. h3!? { I would say that this line has been played about 5 times less frequently in the games, according to the database. It's always beneficial to play a rare line, especially if you know it well, even if it may be less accurate. } (6. c3 { The usual move. } 6... a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 $132 { This is the main move for Black, which White wanted to avoid in the game. }) 6... a6 (6... e6 7. c3 Ne5!? { An interesting alternative variation. } 8. Bf1 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 Be7 10. d4 Bc6! $13) 7. Bf1! Rg8!? { In this position, it's quite uncommon, but we recognize this idea from different openings, such as the Italian, where White plays early h2-h3 and then castles. This allows Black the opportunity to play for the ♜g8, g7-g5 idea. After Bibisara made this exciting move, I was certain we would see a thrilling battle, which indeed happened in the game. :) } (7... e5 { The main move. } 8. c3 Be7 9. d4 $14 { White has a small but stable advantage. }) 8. d3! { Opening up the diagonal is logical. } (8. d4 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 g5) 8... h6! { Yes, it is clear that Black intends to play g7-g5. } 9. b4!? { I love this idea. We are familiar with similar concepts from different openings, such as 1.e4 c5 2.b4 or the Benko Gambit. The aim for White is clearly to open up the bishop, while Black has wasted time focusing on kingside play. } 9... cxb4 10. a3! b3! { Black should aim to maintain a closed position. } (10... bxa3?! 11. d4! g5 12. d5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. g3! g4 15. h4! $16) 11. Nbd2!? (11. c4 g5 12. Qxb3 g4 13. hxg4 Nxg4 14. d4 Rc8! $132 (14... Qa5?! 15. Nc3 Bg7 16. e5 dxe5 17. Bd2 Qd8 18. d5 Nd4 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Ne4 $16 { Tari-Abdusattorov, Stavanger 2023 })) (11. d4!? { It was another straightforward idea. } 11... g5 12. d5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. g3! { Preparing for the g5-g4, where we can easily push h3-h4. } 14... Qc8! 15. cxb3 Bxh3 16. Nd2 Bxf1 17. Nxf1 Qg4 18. Qd3 Nh5 $132) 11... g5 12. d4 g4 13. hxg4 { Black had several options at this point. She could take on c2, capture on g4 with either a knight or a bishop, or play e7-e5. After 10 minutes of thought, Bibisara chose one of the most natural moves, which turned out to be an inaccurate one: recapturing with the bishop to create a pin. } 13... Bxg4?! (13... Nxg4! $132 { Objectively, this is better. } { [%cal Ge7e5] }) (13... bxc2! 14. Qxc2 Nxg4! $132 { [%cal Ga8c8,Ge7e5] }) 14. Bb2 { This is also natural. } (14. c3! $36 { In the interview, Bibisara admitted she would not feel well in the position after this pawn push. The c3 pawn controls the center, and Black is lacking counterplay. }) 14... d5? { Played after 23 minutes. This is a serious mistake, since white has a very strong move that aims to open up the position totally. } (14... bxc2! { This is the most precise, followed by d6-d5, with the idea of preventing the c2-c4 option for White. } 15. Qxc2 d5! 16. Ne5!? Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Qxe4 Rg6!? $132) 15. c4! dxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Rxe4 Bf5!? { Bibisara grabs the best chance to show some counterplay. } 18. Re3 Bc2 19. Qc1?! (19. Qd2! { It would be more natural for White, as she can now connect her rooks with Rae1. Jiner likely aimed to overprotect the b2♗ to prepare for d4-d5, but this loses White's main harmonious setup. } 19... Bg7 20. Bc3! $16 { [%cal Ga1e1,Gd4d5] }) 19... Rc8! { That was a very strong move. The black rook stands very well on c8. } (19... Bg7? 20. d5! $18) 20. d5? { Anyway, Black played for ♞a5, so this is simply provoking it. White still needed to admit her previous queen move misstep and improve her queen to d2. } (20. Bc3 Na5!? 21. c5 Nc6 22. Qb2 h5 $132) (20. Qd2! Bg7 21. Bc3 $16) 20... Na5! 21. Nd2 Rg4!? (21... h5! $132 { A great move that happened in the next turn. } { [%cal Gf8h6] }) 22. Be5?! (22. Bf6!? { A clever, unusual idea. White intends to pin the e7 pawn while also applying pressure to it. } 22... Nxc4 (22... h5 23. Qb2! Bh6) 23. Nxc4 Rgxc4 24. Bxc4 Rxc4 25. Qd2 Qd6! 26. Be5 Qd7 27. Rae1 Rc5! 28. d6 e6 $13) 22... h5!? { It's a clever idea to prepare h6. However, objectively, this is not the best move, as White has a nice escape. } (22... Rgxc4!? { Sacrificing the exchange already here was strong too. } 23. Nxc4 Nxc4 24. Bxc4 Rxc4 25. d6 e6! 26. Qd2 Bxd6! { A nice tactical idea. } 27. Bxd6 (27. Qxd6 Qxd6 28. Bxd6 b2! $19) 27... b2 28. Rae1 b1=Q 29. Rxb1 Bxb1 30. Rg3 Bg6 31. Rb3! b5 32. Rb4! $44) 23. Qb2 Bh6 24. Rae1!? Bxe3 25. Rxe3 Nxc4! { Black is correctly sacrificing some material to pursue a seemingly easy winning position with two extra pawns. However, White has an unexpected and brilliant drawing resource. } 26. Nxc4 Rcxc4 27. Bxc4 Rxc4 28. d6! e6 { It seems that with two extra pawns, Black is winning, but White has a study-like defense. } 29. Bh2? (29. Bg3! h4 30. Rf3!! { A fantastic idea! White's plan applies pressure on the key f7 pawn. With correct play, the position is equal, but I believe these lines are above human understanding. } 30... hxg3 (30... Bg6 31. Be5 $132 { [%cal Gf3b3] }) 31. Qh8+ Kd7 32. Rxf7+ Kc8 33. d7+! (33. Rf8?? gxf2+! 34. Kxf2 (34. Kh2 Rh4+! $19) 34... Rf4+! { What a beautiful geometric concept. } 35. Rxf4 Qxh8 $19) 33... Kc7 34. Qe5+! Kb6 35. Qxe6+ Rc6 36. Qe3+ Rc5 (36... Kc7 37. Qe5+ Kb6) 37. Qd4!! Kc6 38. Rf6+ Qxf6 39. Qxf6+ Kxd7 40. Qg7+ Kc6 41. Qxg3) 29... Qg5! $19 30. Be5 (30. Rg3 Rd4!? $19 { [%cal Gd4d1] }) 30... Be4! { Black has two extra pawns, and the white king is much more vulnerable. We can say that Black is totally winning. } 31. f4 Rc1+ 32. Kh2 Qh4+ 33. Rh3 Rh1+!? 34. Kxh1 Qxh3+ 35. Kg1 Qe3+ 36. Qf2 (36. Kh2 Kd7 $19) 36... Qxf2+ 37. Kxf2 $19 { [%cal Gh5h4,Ge8d7,Gd7c6,Gb7b5] } 37... h4 38. g4 b5 39. Kg1 h3 40. Kh2 Bg2 41. Kg3 a5 42. Kh2 Kd7 43. Kg3 a4! { 0-1 Black wins. } { [%cal Gb5b4] } 0-1


