1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 d6!? { This is quite a clever and provocative variation! Black is giving up control of the center but has some tricks prepared. } (4... Nf6 { This is by far the most common move. }) 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb6 7. Nc3 { It is very natural and can be expected. } (7. Bb5!? { People are unlikely to make a move like this without home preparation. } 7... Bd7 8. Nc3 Nge7 9. h3 O-O 10. O-O $14 { Navara-Schneider, London rapid 2025 }) 7... Nf6 8. Qd3!? { Tan made this move instantly, employing a fascinating strategy to overprotect the center and, in some variations, plan for queenside castling. However, the downside is that Black has a tempo with ♞b4, which was played shortly thereafter. } (8. Be3!? { A natural move, too. } 8... O-O (8... Nxe4? 9. Nxe4 d5 10. Bb3! dxe4 11. Ng5 Be6 { (Wei Yi-Piorun, Goa 2025) } 12. Bxe6! fxe6 13. Nxe6 Qd6 14. Qg4 $18) 9. Bb3!? $14) 8... O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 { White needs to castle to establish a good strategic advantage, but Black is just in time to counterplay. } 10... Nb4! (10... Bg4?! 11. O-O-O! $16) (10... Na5?! 11. Bb5! a6 12. Ba4 $16) (10... g5?! 11. Bg3 $36 { [%cal Ge1c1] }) (10... Re8?! 11. O-O-O!? $16) 11. Qd2 (11. Qe2!? d5 12. a3!? Bxd4!? { Wow! What fascinating tactical lines! } 13. Nxd4 dxc4 14. axb4 Qxd4 15. Rd1 Qe5 $132 { With an unclear position, the engine shows its favorite number: 0.00. However, I believe there are several viable plays in this situation as well. }) 11... d5! { The key move of the 4...d6 system. } 12. exd5 (12. e5? { It was a tempting move, but ultimately a mistake, as Black has a strong counterplay. } 12... dxc4! 13. O-O Bg4! 14. exf6 Bxf3 15. fxg7 Qxh4 16. gxf8=Q+ Rxf8 17. gxf3 Nd3! $17) (12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Bxd5 (13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bg4 $132) 13... Bg4! 14. a3 Bxf3 15. axb4 Bg4 $132) 12... Re8+! (12... Qe8+? { Kateryna has calculated this but found a refutation. } 13. Kd1 $18 (13. Kf1? Nbxd5! 14. Re1! (14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Qb5+ 16. Kg1 Qxd5 $19) 14... Be6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Bxe6 fxe6)) 13. Kf1 (13. Kd1 c6! 14. dxc6 Nxc6! $44) 13... c6! { Another important concept for Black. } 14. dxc6 bxc6! $44 { Black has found many important, principal moves. The compensation is obvious for Black; the white king is on f1. } (14... Nxc6 15. Rd1! $14) 15. Rd1 (15. h3 Be6! 16. Bxe6 Rxe6 17. Kg1 Nbd5 18. Re1 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 c5! 21. Kh2 cxd4 22. cxd4 Bxd4 { White stabilized their coordination of pieces, but Black managed to regain the pawn. }) (15. a3 Nbd5 $132) 15... Ba6? { Going in the wrong direction. The black knight loses valuable time, moving far away from the key d5 square. } (15... Be6! 16. b3 (16. Bxe6 Rxe6 $132 { [%cal Gb4d5] }) 16... Nbd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 $44 { Black is not worse at all. }) 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 17. g4?! { The idea is ambitious, but not very practical. } (17. g3! { White could fix a very clear advantage. The plan is g2, he1. } 17... Nc7 18. Kg2 Ne6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. d5! cxd5 21. Nxd5 Qf5 22. Qd3 Qxd3 23. Rxd3 $16) 17... Nc7 (17... Qd6!? 18. Rg1 Nd5 $14) 18. Rg1 Ncd5 19. g5! Nh5! (19... Ne4? 20. Nxe4 Rxe4 21. gxh6! Rxh4 22. Rxg7+ Kf8 23. Rh7!? { [%cal Gf3h4,Gh7h8] } (23. Nxh4 Qxh4 24. Qg5 Qxg5 25. Rxg5 $18) 23... Kg8 24. Qd3! Rg4 25. Ne5! $18) 20. Rg4?? { White is trying to take full control over Black activities, but it works the opposite way! } (20. gxh6! Qd7 21. Qg5! Ndf4 (21... Qh3+ 22. Qg2! $18) 22. Qg4! Qb7! 23. Ne5! Qa6+ 24. Ne2 Qxe2+ 25. Qxe2 Nxe2 26. Kxe2 Re6! 27. Kf3 Rxh6 28. Rge1 $16) 20... Qd7! 21. h3 Qf5! $19 { Everything has changed now—Black is winning. } 22. Qd3 Ne3+! 23. fxe3 Qxf3+ 24. Bf2 Qxh3+ 25. Rg2 hxg5 $19 { Black has an extra pawn, and the white king is really weak. It looks like the game is over, but they are going to the time trouble zone, and unbelievable events are about to unfold... } 26. Kg1 Bc7 27. Ne4 f6 28. Rc1 Kh8! 29. Nc5 Rad8 (29... g4! $19 { [%cal Gg4g3] }) 30. Qb3 Re7 31. Na6 { White is desperately seeking tactical opportunities. } 31... Qf3 (31... Bd6 32. Rxc6 Kh7!? $19) 32. Nb4 Rd6 { Black is attempting to keep the material advantage. } (32... c5!? 33. Rxc5 (33. dxc5 Re4!? $19 { [%cal Ge4g4] }) 33... Bd6 { It would be practical and strong. } 34. Rc1 Rb7 $19) 33. d5! { White is doing her best to complicate the position. } 33... cxd5 34. Nc6 Rf7? { Black had two winning opportunities, but in both cases, they required sacrificing an exchange! } (34... Rxc6! 35. Rxc6 Bb6 $19 { [%csl Re3] }) (34... Re4! 35. Nd4 Rxd4! 36. exd4 Qxb3 37. axb3 Rd7 $19 { [%cal Gh8h7,Gh7g6,Gh5f4,Gd7e7,Gc7b6] }) 35. Nd4! Qe4?? { This is a huge tactical blunder. } (35... Qh3! { It is necessary to control the c8 square. } 36. Rh2! Qg4+! 37. Rg2 Qd7 38. Qd3! f5 39. Rxg5 Nf6 40. Qxf5 Qe8!? $15) 36. Rxc7! Rxc7 37. Qb8+ Kh7 38. Qxc7 $18 { It is White who is already winning! But let's see what happens next... } 38... Rb6 39. b3 Qb1+ 40. Kh2 f5! { With a very last control move, Black found the best and only practical chance by making White concerned about the ♜h6 idea. } 41. Qf7? { And White firstly missed a simple win after: } (41. Rxg5! Rh6 42. Nxf5! Qb2 43. Kg2 $18) 41... Rf6! 42. Qxd5?? { And now, blundering the whole game! We have a very spectacular puzzle now: Black is starting and winning! } (42. Qxh5+! Rh6 43. Rxg5 g6 44. Qxh6+ Kxh6 45. Bh4 Qxa2+ 46. Rg2 Qb1 47. Bg5+ Kg7 48. Rg1 Qb2+ 49. Kg3 $16 { And White could still make a lot of pressure here. }) 42... Nf4!! { Desperation? Not at all.. } 43. exf4 Rh6+! 44. Kg3 Qd3+! 45. Qf3 (45. Be3 Qxe3+ 46. Qf3 gxf4#) 45... g4!! { That was an incredible shot! We can imagine the emotions of both players in that moment! } 46. Rh2 (46. Qxd3 Rh3# { Giving a checkmate like that is a dream for every chess player! }) 46... gxf3 47. Rxh6+ gxh6 48. Nxf3 a6 { The rest is easy. It's a dramatic and unbelievable game! } 49. Bd4 Qc2 50. b4 Qxa2 51. Bc3 Qb3 52. Be1 Kg6 53. Kg2 Kf7 54. Nh4 Qe3 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


