{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

The fourth round of the Candidates offered the most anticipated match, the clash between the two leaders: Javokhir Sindarov and Fabiano Caruana. And what a game it was! After getting an excellent position out of the opening, Sindarov didn't give Caruana any chance and scored an extremely important win that gives him the sole lead.

The other decisive result came from the encounter between Andrey Esipenko and Anish Giri. After a very interesting opening, Andrey (again) had a very promising position but messed it up with 18.Qxd3 (instead of Rxd3). After that, Anish played extremely accurate to take full advantage of his opponent's mistake. The remaining games between Bluebaum-Pragg and Wei Yi-Naka ended up in draws, with Hikaru missing a huge chance to score his first win in the endgame. }
1. d4 { [%clk 1:59:57] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:59:54] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:50] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:59:50] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:32] } 3... dxc4!? { Not the most common way to play the QGA, but I would assume Fabi was probably trying to avoid some move orders. } { [%clk 1:59:38] } 4. e3 { [%clk 1:59:16] } 4... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:27] } 5. Bxc4 { [%clk 1:59:07] } 5... c5 { [%clk 1:59:19] } 6. O-O { [%clk 1:58:36] } 6... Nc6 { [%clk 1:59:13] } (6... a6 { This is normally the most natural way to play this position. } { [%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] }) 7. Qe2 { [%clk 1:57:17] } 7... a6 { [%clk 1:58:39] } 8. Nc3 { [%clk 1:56:21] } (8. Rd1 { Shouldn't be that challenging for Black. } 8... Qc7 9. Nc3 b5 10. Bb3 (10. Bd3 Bb7) 10... Be7 $10) 8... b5 { [%clk 1:57:13] } 9. Bd3!? { Already a surprise and part of Sindarov's prep. White has played with Bb3 most of the times. } { [%clk 1:55:52] } (9. Bb3 Bb7 10. Rd1 Be7 11. d5 (11. dxc5 Qc7) 11... exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Qb6 $10) 9... Bb7 { [%clk 1:45:37] } (9... cxd4!? { In my opinion, this makes Black's task of getting equality a bit simpler. } 10. exd4 Nb4 11. Be4!? { Considering his style, this was probably what Sindarov had in mind. } (11. Bb1 Be7) 11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nd5 { Vetokhin, Savva - Paravyan, D., 1/2-1/2, Aeroflot Open A 2024, https://lichess.org/Rzf8mdpW } { White still has a tiny advantage due to better development. }) 10. a4!? { Very challenging. After this, Fabi's decisions will get harder and harder. } { [%clk 1:54:58] } 10... b4 { [%clk 1:35:50] } (10... bxa4 11. Bc2 cxd4 12. Nxd4 $36 { White's initiative is strong. } { [%cal Gc2a4,Ga4e8] }) (10... c4 11. Bc2 { Black's pawn structure is vulnerable } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Re2c4,Ra4b5] }) 11. Ne4 { [%clk 1:54:43] } 11... Na5 { [%clk 1:35:11] } 12. Nxf6+ { [%clk 1:54:24] } 12... gxf6 { Caruana chooses right, despite the damage in the pawn structure. } { [%clk 1:27:00] } (12... Qxf6?! 13. e4 $16 { This is already very favourable for White. } { [%cal Gc1g5] }) 13. dxc5 { [%clk 1:54:17] } 13... Nb3 { [%clk 1:09:18] } (13... Bxc5 14. e4 $36) 14. c6! { Very strong move and still the result of prep. Sindarov is still blitzing, while Fabi is trying to find the moves over the board. } { [%clk 1:53:07] } (14. Rb1?! Nxc5 $15) 14... Bxc6 { [%clk 1:07:23] } (14... Nxa1? 15. cxb7 Rb8 16. Bxa6 $18 { [%csl Ra1,Re8] }) 15. Nd4! { [%clk 1:53:01] } 15... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:51:52] } (15... Nxa1 16. Nxc6 Qb6 17. Nd4 $18 { White's position is simply dominant due to the misplacement of the black knight, very poor development and a weak K. } { [%csl Ra1,Re8] }) 16. exd4 { [%clk 1:52:56] } 16... Rg8 { [%clk 0:51:39] } 17. g3 { With an advantage of over an hour on the clock, Sindarov spends some time for the first time in the game. Impressive! } { [%clk 1:26:51] } 17... f5?! { In a difficult position and with pressure on the clock, Caruana plays it wrong. It was better to accept the pawn, despite White's position looking easier to play. } { [%clk 0:34:28] } (17... Qxd4 18. Be3 Qd5 19. f3 f5 $132 { White's compensation is out of question but Black is definitely in the game. } { [%cal Gf6f5] }) 18. Bc4! $16 { Sindarov shows why he is leading this tournament. With great sense of attack, he correctly understands that the black K is struggling in the center of the board. } { [%cal Gd4d5,Gc4e6,Gf1d1] [%clk 1:15:51] } 18... Rg4 { [%clk 0:16:27] } (18... Qxd4 { The engine suggests this as the best option for White. Honestly, it looks pretty hopeless despite getting to trade Qs. } 19. Bxe6 Qe4 20. Qxe4 Bxe4 21. Bb3 $16 { [%csl Rf5,Rf7][%cal Gf2f3,Gf1e1] }) 19. Be3 { Simple and good. As we have said in previous rounds, it seems like Sindarov is never missing his opportunities when it comes to playing with the initiative. } { [%clk 1:11:28] } 19... Bd5 { [%clk 0:11:42] } 20. Rac1! { Great move again. Worse was: } { [%clk 1:06:41] } (20. Bxa6? Bd6 21. Bb5+ Kf8 $13 { Despite being down a pawn, Black looks happier here. } { [%cal Gf5f4] }) 20... Be7 { [%clk 0:06:25] } 21. Bxa6 { [%clk 1:04:55] } 21... Kf8 { [%clk 0:06:21] } 22. Bb5?! { Possibly his only inaccuracy in the whole game. Going back to c4 was good, as the pawn on a4 cannot be captured. } { [%clk 1:01:45] } (22. Bc4 $18 Kg7 (22... Rxa4? 23. Bh6+ Kg8 24. Bxd5) 23. b3) 22... Bf6?! { With less than 10 minutes, Caruana doesn't find the best way to fight here. } { [%clk 0:06:10] } (22... Kg7 23. f3 Rg6 24. Bf4 Bf6 25. Be5 h5 $16 { White is still in the lead, but this is definitely a lot more promising than what occured in the game. } { [%cal Gh5h4] }) 23. Rfd1 { [%clk 0:56:42] } 23... Kg7 { [%clk 0:05:50] } 24. Bc6! { Trading Black's most important piece. The game is over. } { [%clk 0:55:05] } 24... Ra5 { [%clk 0:03:55] } (24... Bxc6 25. Rxc6 Rxa4 26. d5! { This break destroys Black's position. } 26... exd5 27. Qc2 { [%cal Gc2a4,Gc2f5] }) 25. Bxd5 { [%clk 0:52:21] } 25... Rxd5 { [%clk 0:03:53] } 26. Rc5! { [%csl Rg4][%cal Gd4d5] [%clk 0:50:29] } 26... Rd7 { [%clk 0:03:49] } 27. d5 { [%clk 0:47:39] } 27... exd5 { [%clk 0:03:44] } (27... Re4 28. Qh5) 28. Qf3 { [%csl Rd5,Rf5] [%clk 0:45:39] } 28... Bxb2 { Knowing his position is already hopeless, Fabi goes for the good old "since my position is already bad for free, let me at least get some material" } { [%clk 0:03:02] } (28... d4 29. Qxf5 Rg6 30. Bf4 $18 { [%cal Gc5b5,Gb5b4] }) 29. Rcxd5 { [%clk 0:45:25] } 29... Rxd5 { [%clk 0:02:56] } 30. Rxd5 { [%clk 0:45:19] } 30... Qe8 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 31. Rxf5 { [%clk 0:45:11] } 31... Rg6 { [%clk 0:01:59] } 32. h4 { [%clk 0:45:00] } 32... Bc3 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 33. h5 { [%clk 0:44:37] } 33... Ra6 { [%clk 0:01:03] } 34. Qg4+ { [%clk 0:42:45] } 34... Kh8 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 35. Bd4+ { [%clk 0:42:13] } 35... f6 { [%clk 0:00:48] } 36. Rc5 { 1-0 White wins.
A very clear win and another fantastic game played by Sindarov, which gives him a full-point lead over Caruana. He has been getting great positions out of the opening (with the exception of Round 1) and taking full advantage of his opportunities.
On the other hand, tough blow for Fabi, who will have to regroup in the rest day and hope to bounce back, in his aim to catch Sindarov. } { [%cal Gc5c8] [%clk 0:42:02] } 1-0


