ced it is the right decision. White's initiative is going to get pretty strong now. } { [%clk 1:03:40] } (16... Kb8!? 17. b5 axb5 18. cxb5 Nd4 19. Qb2 e5 $132 { This was one of the alternatives, with White's initiative looking strong on the Q-side and Black fighting back in the center. } { [%cal Gd6d5] }) 17. Rab1 { [%clk 1:27:50] } 17... Nxd3 { [%clk 0:55:19] } 18. Qxd3? { Huge mistake that changes everything! Andrey captures with the wrong piece, missing Black's next move and turning the game around. } { [%clk 1:23:02] } (18. Rxd3! Bc6 (18... Kb8 19. Nxd6 Bxd6 20. Rxd6 $18 { [%cal Gd6a6,Gd6b6,Gb1b8] }) 19. c5 $36 { Key move. After this move, Black's K is going to struggle to find a safe square. } { [%csl Rc7] } 19... d5 20. Ng5 { [%cal Ge2e5] } 20... Qf8 (20... Bxg5?? 21. Qe5+ Kd7 22. Qd6+ Ke8 23. Ng7#) 21. Qe5+ Kd7 22. Ne4 $16 { Black's defense task would have been extremely difficult here. }) 18... Ba4! $17 { Great way to defend the d6 pawn and controlling the crucial b3 square. } { [%csl Rb3] [%clk 0:35:19] } 19. Rd2 { [%clk 0:42:28] } (19. Rdc1 Kb8 { Is not any better. }) 19... Kb8 { [%clk 0:34:37] } 20. Rdb2 { Andrey correctly understands that trading Qs is going to be, very likely, hopeless for White } { [%clk 0:28:42] } (20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Qxd6+ Bxd6 22. Rxd6 Rxc4 $19) (20. Qd4 Bc6 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22. Qxd6+ Bxd6 23. Rxd6 Be4 $17 { This is a very sad endgame for White to play. }) 20... Bc6 { [%cal Gd8a5,Gb8a8] [%clk 0:31:48] } 21. c5!? { Trying to complicate things.. } { [%clk 0:21:41] } (21. Nf4 Ka8) 21... dxc5 { [%clk 0:30:33] } 22. Qxa6 { [%clk 0:20:56] } 22... Qd5! $19 { But Anish responds very well. After this move, it will be clear that White's attack is not getting anywhere and the game is close to over. } { [%cal Gd5g2,Gd5b7] [%clk 0:26:03] } 23. f3 { [%clk 0:14:41] } 23... Rc7 { Reinforcing b7 to gain some freedom for the Q } { [%cal Gc7b7] [%clk 0:22:12] } 24. Nhg3 { [%clk 0:09:28] } 24... Rd8 { [%clk 0:21:45] } 25. Nf2 { [%clk 0:09:02] } 25... c4 { [