{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

Before the rest day, we saw the players giving their best efforts, and all of them were engaged in a competitive game. Between the Chinese and Indian stars, we see that from the opening stage onward, the position was quite messy and unbalanced, which led me to believe this would not be a boring game. Indeed, it turned out to be an exciting battle. Zhu played exceptionally well and rightfully won. Divya started the game with 1.c4, a move she had also played previously as White against Vaishali. }
1. c4 e5 { This is one of the most fighting responses. } 2. Nc3 Bb4 { We can see that we are in a reserve color Rossolimo, but White has an extra tempo. } 3. Nd5 { A principal move. } 3... a5!? { Black aims to take control of the b4 square. } (3... Be7 { Another safe reply. }) 4. Nf3 d6 5. a3 Bc5 { We see now that 3...a5 was a useful move. } 6. e3 Nf6!? { A rare move, but it is a very interesting one. Black is ready to pursue an unbalanced and complicated position. } (6... c6 { This is more common. } 7. Nc3 Nd7 8. d4 Ba7 9. Be2 Ngf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 $14) 7. d4 Nxd5! 8. cxd5 exd4 9. exd4 Bb6! { An earlier game was played between Ding and Yu Yangyi. Giri commented on this position and wrote the following sentences: "This position was seen in a couple of recent games. White has the odd looking doubled isolanis in the center, but the b6 bishop is out of play and White can use the momentum to build up an advantage in development." } 10. Bg5!? { A principal move again. Provoking f7-f6 is quite useful. } (10. Be3!? Nd7 $15 { [%cal Gd7f6] }) 10... f6 11. Be3 O-O 12. h4?! { Divya played this move quickly, but based on my analysis, it seems questionable. Black has the opportunity to gain a strong position here. Instead, she should have played ♗d3, ♕c2. It appears that she may have confused the opening lines. } (12. Bd3!? { According to the database, this logical move occurred in all games. } 12... f5 (12... c6? 13. Qc2! f5 14. O-O h6 15. Rfe1 Kh8 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. d5! Bxe3 18. Rxe3 c5 19. Rae1 $18 { Anton Guijarro-Praggnanandhaa, Prague 2019 }) 13. Qc2 Nd7! (13... f4? 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. Bd2 Qe7+ 16. Kf1! Bg4 17. Re1 Qf6 18. h4!? Nd7 19. h5 $18 { Shankland-Yoo, Saint Louis 2022 }) 14. O-O-O!? (14. Bxf5 Nf6! 15. Bd3 h6! 16. Nh4 (16. Bc4 Qe8 17. O-O-O { (Andersen-Ochsner, Svendborg 2020) } 17... Qh5!? $132 { [%cal Gf6d5] }) 16... Nxd5 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Ng6+ Kxh7 19. Nxf8+ Kg8 20. Ng6 Qf6 21. Qe4! Be6 22. O-O Re8 23. Nh4 Bf7 24. Qg4 h5 { (Ding-Yu Yangyi, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019) } 25. Qh3 Re4 26. Nf3 Rg4 $44) 14... Nf6 15. Rhe1 $14) 12... f5! 13. g3 Qe8 14. Bd3?! { The issue with this move is that the pawn on d5 is rather weak, and the bishop would be better positioned on c4 where it can protect it. } (14. Qc2! { Preparing to castle queenside is the most reasonable idea. } 14... Nd7 15. Bc4 Nf6 16. O-O-O $132 { [%cal Gf3g5,Gh4h5] }) 14... Nd7! $15 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gh7h6,Gd7f6] } 15. O-O? { This is clearly a wrong strategy. In a few moves, Divya has lost the d5 pawn. Instead, she needed to go for a dynamic line with h4-h5, ♘h4. } (15. h5! { Preparing ♘h4 still looks like the most harmonious move, with the bishop on d3. } 15... h6! 16. Nh4 Bxd4! 17. Bxf5! { This is a great tactical position. There are many interesting lines here. } 17... Bxb2 (17... Rxf5!? 18. Nxf5 Bxb2 19. Rb1 Bc3+ 20. Kf1 Nf6 21. Nxg7! Qe4! (21... Kxg7 22. Rc1 Be5 23. Rxc7+ Bd7 24. Rh4!? $132) 22. Rh4 Bg4! 23. Qb3 Kxg7 24. Rxg4+ Nxg4 25. Qxc3+ Kg8 26. Rxb7 Nxe3+ 27. Qxe3 Qh1+ 28. Ke2 Qxh5+ 29. g4 Qxg4+ 30. Kd2 $44) 18. Be6+ Rf7 19. Rb1 Bc3+ 20. Kf1 b5! $36 { [%cal Gb5b4] }) 15... h6! { A necessary move. Black controls the important g5 square and is ready to play ♛f7, ♞f6. } 16. Ne1 { The plan is ♘g2-f4, but she doesn't reach f4, as Black is faster to take on d5. } (16. Re1 Qf7! $17 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gd7f6,Gf7d5] }) 16... Nf6! 17. Ng2 Nxd5 { Black has a healthy extra pawn and a clearly better position. } 18. Bc4 (18. Re1!? Be6 19. Bf4 Qf7 20. Rxe6!? Qxe6 21. Bc4 a4! { It is essential to cover the b3 square. } (21... c6?! 22. Qb3! $132) 22. Be3 c6 23. Nf4 Qe4 24. Rc1 { Trying to play for a blockade, but Black has a clearly better position. Needs to be ready to convert his advantage in a long, patient game. } 24... Kh7 $17) 18... Be6! 19. Re1 Qf7?! (19... Qd7! { This is better, as Black can play ♝f7 to solve the problem of the unstable e6 piece. } 20. Bd2 Bf7 $17) 20. Bd2 c6 21. Qb3? (21. Rxe6!! { Divya needed to go for these, where she would get great counterplay. } 21... Qxe6 22. Nf4 Qf7 23. Qf3 Kh7 24. Be3! Rae8 25. Nxd5! cxd5 26. Bxd5 { The bishop is dominating on d5. } 26... Qf6 27. Rd1! $44) 21... Kh7?! (21... Bxd4! { The most accurate. } 22. Rxe6 Qxe6 23. Qxb7 Rac8! 24. Re1 Be5! $17) 22. a4? { Losing the moment. } (22. Rxe6! { This is the final opportunity for the sacrifice. } 22... a4! 23. Rxh6+!! { We see some amusing yet significant intermediate moves from both sides. } 23... gxh6 24. Qd3 Rae8 25. Be3!? $132 { [%cal Gb2b3] }) 22... Bxd4! $19 { Finally, Black takes the important pawn on d4 and is ready to block the e-file with the bishop on e5. } 23. Re2 (23. Rxe6 Qxe6 24. Nf4 Qf6 $19) 23... Be5! 24. Rae1 Nf4!? { A nice move. } 25. gxf4 (25. Bxe6 Nxe6 $19) 25... Bxc4 26. Qg3 Bf6! $19 { With the two extra pawns, Black's position is completely winning. } 27. Re3 d5 28. Qh3 d4 29. Rg3 Qh5 30. b4 axb4 31. Bxb4 Rfe8 32. Rc1 Bd5 33. Ne1 Rxa4 34. Bd6 Kh8 35. Be5 Bxe5 36. fxe5 d3 { 0-1 Black wins. } { [%cal Ga4h4] } 0-1


