1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6!? { This system has become quite popular lately as a way to avoid the Marshall. } 6... dxc6 7. d3 Qd6!? { Not the main move here, but Black's idea to castle long is very logical. } (7... Nd7 { The main move. }) 8. a4!? { I have found only a few games featuring this move, which is a relatively new concept. The point is to develop the knight from a3 to c4. } (8. Nbd2 Be6 9. Ng5 O-O-O 10. Ndf3 Nd7 $132 { Giri-Matlakov, Chess.com 2023 }) 8... Be6 9. Na3 h6?! { Seems like a waste of time. } (9... O-O!? $132 { It is completely fine according to the engine, but as we know, Black is planning the long castle and stopping the g5. }) (9... O-O-O 10. Qe2 Nd7 11. Nd2!? $36 { [%cal Gd2c4] }) 10. Nd2! $14 O-O-O (10... Qd8!? { The engine shows a really strange back-way maneuver. } 11. Ndc4 (11. Nac4 Nd7 $132 { This was definitely not taken into consideration. }) 11... Nd7 12. Ne3 $14) 11. Ndc4 Bxc4 12. Nxc4 { White managed to trade a black bishop and has some statistical advantage here, although the black position is very solid. } 12... Qe6 13. Qe2 (13. Qe1!? { This could be an interesting alternative. } 13... b6 14. Qc3 Nd7 15. f4 $36) 13... Nd7 14. Bd2 b6!? { Black is improving her queenside defending formation. } 15. b4 Kb7 16. Rfb1 { White is preparing a clever queenside play. } 16... Ra8!? 17. Qe1 { White is already planning to sacrifice a piece. } (17. c3!? $36 { Preparing ♗e3, d3-d4 was also a very logical move, leading to a more favorable position. }) 17... h5 (17... g6!? 18. b5 cxb5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Rxb5 Rxa1 21. Qxa1 Ra8 22. Qb2 h5) 18. b5 (18. Qe2!? g6 19. Re1 $14 { Continuing to maneuver was not in the white's plan. }) 18... cxb5 (18... axb5 19. axb5 cxb5 { - 18...cxb5 } (19... Rxa1 20. bxc6+ Qxc6 21. Rxa1 Ra8 $132)) 19. axb5 a5 { A principled move, though somewhat risky, as the piece sacrifice is intriguing for White. } (19... axb5!? { It's a safer option. Anna had anticipated this outcome more than the continuation of the game. } 20. Rxb5 Rxa1 21. Qxa1 Ra8 22. Qb2 $132 { Roughly equal chances. }) 20. Bxa5!? bxa5 21. Nxa5+ Kc8 (21... Rxa5!? 22. Qxa5 Rb8!? $132 { It is a very complicated position with unbalanced material: a rook and two pawns versus a bishop and a knight. The engine shows an evaluation of 0.00, but there is still a lot of life in this position. } { [%cal Gb7c8] }) 22. Nc6 Rxa1! (22... Kb7? { Anna expected this, but it's just losing as the king is very vulnerable. } 23. Rxa8 Rxa8 24. Ra1! Rxa1 25. Qxa1 Nc5 26. h4!? { Black is in a kind of zugzwang position, which is quite amazing. } 26... g6 (26... Bxh4?? 27. Qa7+ $18 { [%cal Ga7c5,Ga7b7] }) 27. g3 Kc8 28. Nxe5 $18) 23. Rxa1 { White got two pawns for the piece, but the black king is weak, and the engine shows it as about equal. } 23... Nb6! 24. Qe3!? { White's plan is now c4-c5. } 24... Bd6! { Kateryna has found a clever way to stop c4-c5. She realized cleverly that she needed to trade the queens. } (24... Kd7?! 25. Ra7! Nc8 26. Ra8 $36) 25. c4 (25. f3?! { Preparing against ...♛h6 with ♕f2, but it's slow, Black can fix her position. } 25... Qh6! 26. Qf2 Kd7! $36 { [%cal Gh8a8] }) 25... Qh6! { The only move - Black is defending well. The point is that if the queen is removed, White can hardly play c4-c5. } 26. Qh3+ Qe6 27. Qe3 Qh6 28. d4!? { White refuses the repetition. } 28... exd4?? { It could be explained by tiredness after the first rounds. Sometimes chess players make the "second move" of a variation they were going to play. Obviously, Black should trade queens first. } (28... Qxe3! 29. fxe3 exd4 30. exd4 Re8! { Black needs to show counterplay and give back the piece for White's strong pawns. } 31. c5 (31. e5 Nxc4 $132) 31... Rxe4! 32. cxd6 cxd6 { The endgame should result in a draw. } 33. g3! $36 { Preventing the rook from accessing the f4 square is clever, as the threat of ♖a7 becomes quite troublesome. Although it is objectively a draw, White still has some practical chances. } (33. Ra7 Rf4!? (33... Nd7 34. b6 Nxb6 35. Rxf7 g5))) 29. Qxd4 $18 { Now suddenly, Black is just lost, with no defense against c4-c5. } 29... Kb7 (29... Qf6 30. e5! $18) 30. c5! { [%cal Gc5b6,Gc5d6] } 30... Ra8 31. cxd6 Qxd6 32. Rxa8 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


