{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

After the first rest day, the players were back in action for the fifth round. Clearly, the most attractive match-up was the one between the current leader, Javokhir Sindarov, and the top seed, Hikaru Nakamura. With the white pieces, Hikaru decided to go for an extremely sharp position out of the opening. Things couldn't go any worse for Hikaru, as Sindarov showed that he was more than prepared and won another very important point in his task to win the event and challenge the current World Champion, Gukesh. }
1. d4 { [%clk 1:59:54] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:59:52] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:40] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:59:43] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:13] } 3... c6!? { After some deliberation, Sindarov decided to play a bit different from his previous game (where he played Be7). } { [%cal Gc7c6] [%clk 1:57:52] } 4. e4!? { In his task to catch the leader, Hikaru decides to go for the most aggressive approach. He probably expected to surprise his opponent with it, since he doesn't have any recent record of playing this move order. } { [%clk 1:58:59] } 4... dxe4 { [%clk 1:57:47] } 5. Nxe4 { [%clk 1:58:54] } 5... Bb4+ { [%clk 1:57:26] } 6. Bd2 { [%clk 1:58:47] } 6... Qxd4 { [%clk 1:57:16] } 7. Bxb4 { [%clk 1:58:43] } 7... Qxe4+ { [%clk 1:57:11] } 8. Be2 { [%clk 1:58:38] } 8... Na6 { [%clk 1:56:38] } 9. Bd6 { [%clk 1:58:30] } (9. Ba5 { This move is also very popular } 9... b6 10. Qd6 Bd7 11. Bc3 f6 12. Nf3 $132 { With compensation for the pawn. }) 9... Qxg2 { Sindarov is not scared of a theoretical fight. A calmer approach would have been: } { [%clk 1:56:00] } (9... e5 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Bd3 { White gets the pawn back and a stable advantage. } { [%cal Gd6e5] }) 10. Bf3 { [%clk 1:58:26] } (10. Qd2 Nf6 (10... Qxh1?? 11. O-O-O) 11. Bf3 Qg6 { This position has been played in the past as well. }) 10... Qg5 { [%clk 1:55:48] } 11. Ne2 { [%clk 1:58:18] } 11... Ne7 { [%clk 1:54:29] } 12. Ng3 { [%clk 1:57:28] } 12... O-O!? { The critical move that will change the course of the game. Sindarov, still playing fast, goes for a side move that has not been played as much. He probably chose a slightly worse move to surprise his opponent, and it ended up working perfectly. } { [%clk 1:52:47] } (12... e5 { This was probably the move that Hikaru was expecting. } 13. Qb3 Ng6 { [%cal Ga1d1,Gh7h5] }) 13. h4?! { After the match, Hikaru admitted that he didn't have 0-0 as a potential move in his prep. Facing such a complex position with no prep is a true nightmare for any player. } { [%clk 0:49:44] } (13. Ne4 { This was the only way to keep the initiative } 13... Qa5+ 14. b4 Qd8 (14... Nxb4 { Very similar to the game, but here we do have the opportunity to castle instead of the unnecessary h4. } 15. O-O Re8 16. Qd2 c5 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Rad1 $36 { [%cal Gd2d8,Gg1h1,Gf1g1] }) 15. Rg1 Nf5 (15... f6 16. Qe2 $36 { [%cal Ge1c1] }) (15... Ng6 16. h4 $36) 16. Be5 $36) 13... Qa5+ $17 { Not only is he down an hour, but White's position is already very bad. } { [%clk 1:50:28] } 14. b4 { [%clk 0:49:41] } (14. Kf1 { Objectively speaking, this was probably a better try. As we will see, White will end up sacrificing the Q but has to be extremely energetic to keep the position alive. } 14... Rd8 15. Bxe7 Rxd1+ 16. Rxd1 f6 17. Bh5! (17. Rd8+ Kf7 $19) 17... g6 18. Bxg6!? (18. Bxf6!? e5 { Black should still be okay, but with a big exposed K. } (18... gxh5 19. Rg1)) 18... hxg6 19. h5) 14... Nxb4 { [%clk 1:38:30] } 15. O-O { [%clk 0:45:33] } 15... Re8 { [%clk 1:37:23] } (15... Rd8?? 16. Bxb4) 16. Qd2 { [%clk 0:42:42] } 16... c5 { [%clk 1:35:17] } 17. Rad1 { [%clk 0:23:07] } 17... Nf5! { It is true that Sindarov's moves are quite natural, but he has been extremely precise throughout the tourney. After this key move, Black will consolidate his advantage. } { [%clk 1:23:26] } 18. Nxf5 { [%clk 0:20:01] } 18... exf5 { [%clk 1:23:20] } 19. Qf4 { [%clk 0:16:49] } 19... Nc6 { [%clk 1:10:04] } 20. Kh1?! { Not the right square for the K, as we will see in the analysis. Better was: } { [%clk 0:16:22] } (20. Kh2 { [%cal Ge8e1,Ge1h1] } 20... Nd4 21. Rxd4 cxd4 22. Rg1 { White needs to make something happen. } { [%cal Gf3d5] }) 20... Nd4 { [%clk 1:02:19] } 21. Rg1 { [%clk 0:16:18] } (21. Rxd4 cxd4 22. Rg1 Re1 $19 { The key detail about the K square. White cannot sac the exchange here. } { [%cal Ge1h1] }) 21... g6 { [%clk 0:55:43] } 22. Bd5 { [%clk 0:14:58] } (22. h5 Nxf3 23. Qxf3 Bd7 $19 { Black, who is up 2 pawns, is consolidating here. } { [%cal Gd7c6] }) 22... Be6 { Keeping things simple. } { [%clk 0:52:27] } (22... Ne2 23. Qh6 Be6) 23. Bxb7 { [%clk 0:14:04] } 23... Ne2 { [%clk 0:50:33] } 24. Qd2 { [%clk 0:11:44] } (24. Qh6 Qc3! $19 { [%cal Gc3g7,Gc3h3] }) 24... Qxd2 { After this, Black is transitioning into a winning endgame. } { [%clk 0:49:59] } 25. Rxd2 { [%clk 0:11:43] } 25... Nxg1 { Already understanding that the endgame is winning, Sindarov is not scared of simplifying despite the opposite-colored bishop endgame. } { [%clk 0:49:52] } 26. Bxa8 { [%clk 0:11:40] } 26... Rxa8 { [%clk 0:48:55] } 27. Kxg1 { [%clk 0:11:32] } 27... Rd8! $19 { The kid never misses. Game over! } { [%clk 0:48:19] } 28. Bf4 { [%clk 0:11:31] } 28... Rxd2 { [%clk 0:48:11] } 29. Bxd2 { [%clk 0:11:25] } 29... Bxc4 { [%clk 0:48:05] } 30. Be3 { [%clk 0:11:24] } 30... Bxa2 { [%clk 0:47:49] } 31. Bxc5 { [%clk 0:11:23] } 31... a5 { [%clk 0:47:41] } 32. f4 { [%clk 0:08:41] } 32... f6 { [%clk 0:47:34] } 33. Kf2 { [%clk 0:08:39] } 33... Kf7 { [%clk 0:47:28] } 34. Ba3 { [%clk 0:08:21] } 34... Ke6 { [%clk 0:46:48] } 35. Bf8 { [%clk 0:07:30] } 35... a4 { [%clk 0:46:27] } 36. Ke3 { [%clk 0:07:28] } 36... Kf7 { [%clk 0:46:22] } 37. Bb4 { [%clk 0:06:21] } 37... h6 { Black is going to be able to create a passed pawn in both sides, which makes White's defense impossible. } { [%clk 0:46:17] } 38. Kf2 { [%clk 0:06:10] } 38... g5 { [%clk 0:45:50] } 39. Kg3 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 39... Bd5 { [%clk 0:45:10] } 40. Ba3 { [%clk 0:36:04] } 40... Be4 { [%clk 1:15:21] } 41. Bc1 { [%clk 0:36:17] } 41... gxh4+ { Sindarov scores another major win to keep his full-point lead. At this point, it is very clear that he is the big favourite to win the event. Esipenko, in round 1, has been the only one who actually put him in trouble. } { [%cal Gf7b3,Ga4a3] [%clk 1:15:32] } 0-1


