{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

After the tough defeat against Sindarov in the previous round, Fabiano Caruana scored a very important win in the fifth round. Fabi, who is alone in the second place, clearly demonstrated that he is ready to fight till the end for the title. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:59:57] } 1... e5 { Bluebaum has officially transitioned from his beloved French to the Petrov. } { [%clk 1:59:52] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:50] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:46] } 3. Nxe5 { [%clk 1:59:46] } 3... d6 { [%clk 1:59:43] } 4. Nc4 { This has been getting more and more popular. } { [%clk 1:59:36] } 4... Nxe4 { [%clk 1:59:34] } 5. Nc3!? { But this is already a bit of a surprise. } { [%clk 1:59:31] } (5. Qe2 { This normally how things go. } 5... Qe7 6. Ne3) 5... Nxc3 { [%clk 1:53:05] } 6. dxc3 { Another surprise, Fabi was willing to bring some fresh ideas as Bluebaum is known for being very well prepared. } { [%clk 1:59:12] } (6. bxc3) 6... d5 { [%clk 1:50:58] } (6... Be7 7. Bf4 O-O 8. Qf3 { Was probably what Fabi had in mind. } { [%cal Ge1c1] }) 7. Ne3 { [%clk 1:59:00] } 7... c6 { [%clk 1:43:37] } (7... Be6!? { Honestly, I do like this move more than what happened in the game. Black keeps a bit more flexibility. } { [%cal Bc7c6,Yc7c5] } 8. Bd3 (8. f4 { This resource, which was played in the game shouldn't work as well. } 8... Bc5) 8... Nc6 { Black position seems to be ok. } { [%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] }) 8. Bd2 { [%clk 1:58:43] } 8... g6 { [%clk 1:38:57] } (8... Bc5 9. Qf3!?) 9. f4 { Bluebaum was already taking his time, while Fabi was still playing fast and showing that he was still in prep. } { [%clk 1:58:28] } 9... Bg7 { [%clk 1:36:10] } 10. Qf3 { [%clk 1:58:09] } 10... Nd7 { [%clk 1:33:46] } 11. O-O-O { [%clk 1:40:10] } (11. h4 { Since Black hasn't 0-0 yet, White was not so motivated to go for h4. } 11... Nc5 12. h5 Bd7 { [%cal Ge8c8,Gd8a5] }) 11... Nc5 { [%clk 1:31:12] } 12. f5 { [%clk 1:16:37] } 12... O-O { [%clk 1:12:28] } 13. g4 { [%clk 1:15:37] } (13. h4) 13... Ne4 { [%clk 1:08:49] } (13... Re8 14. h4 { White's initiative is already very strong. } { [%cal Gg4g5,Gh4h5] }) 14. Bd3 { [%clk 1:11:02] } 14... Re8?! { After this very natural move, Black's position will start getting extremely hard to handle. Better was: } { [%clk 0:49:25] } (14... Nxd2 15. Rxd2 Re8 16. h4 d4! $132 { Despite not looking very active, White's dark squared B was way more important for his king's defense. This position is extremely unclear. } { [%cal Gg7b2,Gd8d4] }) 15. Bxe4! { Fabi goes right and trades the right B. } { [%clk 1:02:29] } 15... Rxe4 { [%clk 0:49:18] } (15... dxe4 16. Qf2 $16 { With the center locked and the Q-side under control, White's attack will run pretty strongly. } { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] }) 16. h4 $36 { [%clk 1:01:56] } 16... Be5 { I'm not sure I like Matthias' move, but it was already hard to find a good move to complicate things. } { [%clk 0:36:44] } (16... Qa5 17. Kb1 Bd7 18. Rdf1 $16 { [%cal Gf1f7] }) 17. c4?! { Probably Caruana's only inaccuracy. Fabi was already focused and applying pressure, but in reality it was better to consolidate his K first. } { [%clk 0:34:23] } (17. Kb1 Qb6 18. Rdf1 Rf4 19. Qh3 $16 { Black's lack of space and opportunities allows White to take his time. }) 17... Qb6! { [%clk 0:29:53] } 18. c3 { [%clk 0:34:05] } 18... Qa5? { Very natural try, but Black desperately needed to bring his pieces to work. The 8th rank is too weak. } { [%clk 0:25:46] } (18... Bd7! 19. Rhf1!? (19. h5 g5 20. cxd5 Ra4! 21. Kb1 h6) (19. Rdf1 Rf4 20. Qh3 d4! $132) 19... Rf4 20. Qg2 Rxf1 21. Rxf1 d4 22. Nc2 $36 { This would not have been easy to find, even for a great player like Caruana. }) 19. h5! $18 { White's attack is overwhelming and, as a result, the game is over! } { [%clk 0:19:04] } 19... g5 { [%clk 0:22:54] } (19... Qxa2 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. Qh3 $18) 20. cxd5 { [%clk 0:11:32] } 20... Rf4 { [%clk 0:18:42] } 21. Qe2 { After this move, Black's back rank will suffer severely. } { [%cal Ge2e8] [%clk 0:11:27] } 21... cxd5 { [%clk 0:13:48] } (21... Qxa2 22. Nc4! Qa1+ 23. Kc2 Qa4+ 24. b3 Qa2+ 25. Nb2 { White's threats are too strong. } { [%cal Gd1a1,Ge2e6] }) 22. Kb1 { [%clk 0:09:11] } 22... Ra4 { [%clk 0:10:16] } 23. c4! { [%clk 0:07:04] } 23... Qa6 { [%clk 0:04:49] } 24. Nxd5 { [%clk 0:06:59] } 24... f6 { [%clk 0:04:48] } 25. Bc3 { [%clk 0:05:42] } 25... Qxc4 { [%clk 0:03:29] } (25... Rxa2 26. Nxf6+ { Similar to the game. }) 26. Nxf6+! { [%clk 0:05:34] } 26... Bxf6 { [%clk 0:03:26] } 27. Qe8+ { [%clk 0:05:29] } 27... Kg7 { [%clk 0:03:24] } 28. h6# { Matthias shows great class and allows his K to get checkmated. With this result, Fabi seems to be the clear contender, while Bluebaum suffers his first defeat. } { [%clk 0:05:27] } 1-0


