1. e4 { Kateryna opens the game with her favorite move. } { [%clk 1:30:57] } 1... c5 { [%clk 1:30:56] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:30:46] } 2... Nc6 { Before the tournament, Bibisara's main weapon in the Sicilian Defence was 2...d6, usually followed by the Najdorf Variation. For this important event, however, she appears to have prepared a new approach with 2...Nc6.
In the first round against Vaishali, she again chose 2...Nc6, when 3.d4 led to the Kalashnikov Variation. In the third round against Zhu Jiner, the Rossolimo Variation appeared. Today, once again, she opts for 2...Nc6. } { [%clk 1:30:48] } 3. Nc3 { Kateryna chooses a different approach. } { [%clk 1:31:28] } 3... g6 { Played instantly! Black goes for the complex Accelerated Dragon, which suits Bibisara's dynamic style very well! } { [%clk 1:31:12] } 4. d4 { [%clk 1:31:33] } 4... cxd4 { [%clk 1:32:05] } 5. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:31:59] } 5... Bg7 { [%clk 1:32:12] } 6. Be3 { [%clk 1:32:08] } 6... Nf6 { [%clk 1:32:22] } 7. Nb3!? { This is not the main line; 7.Bc4 is by far the most popular choice. } { [%clk 1:32:00] } (7. Bc4!?) 7... O-O { [%clk 1:30:31] } 8. Qd2!? { This is an intersting sideline, clearly prepared by Kateryna! White intends to set up a dangerous attacking formation against the Dragon setup with f3, 0-0-0, and h4-h5, opening the h-file and launching an attack against the black king. } { [%cal Gf2f3,Ge1c1,Gh2h5] [%clk 1:31:39] } 8... d6!? { This is the first critical moment of the game. Black can continue with the energetic 8...a5. However, the move played in the game is also a good one. } { [%clk 1:19:44] } (8... a5!? 9. a4 d5! { And complications arise } 10. exd5 Nb4 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gb4d5,Gf6d5] } 11. Rd1 { Suddenly, 11.0-0-0 runs into 11...Bf5! } (11. O-O-O?? Bf5! { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gb4c2,Gf5c2] } 12. Nd4 Ne4! 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 $19 { with a powerful attack for Black }) 11... Ng4!? { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gg4e3] } 12. Bf4 Bf5! { and the position is highly complex. } { [%cal Gb4c2,Gf5c2] }) (8... Ng4 { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gg4e3] } 9. Bg5! $14) 9. f3! { [%clk 1:31:41] } 9... a5 { After 8...d6, it would have been better to continue with the usual development: ...Be6, ...Ne5,...Rc8, with counterplay on the queenside. } { [%clk 1:16:25] } (9... Be6!? { [%cal Gc6e5,Ga8c8] }) 10. a4 { Preventing a4. } { [%clk 1:20:58] } 10... Nb4 { [%clk 1:11:03] } 11. O-O-O! { [%clk 1:19:57] } 11... Bd7 { [%clk 1:08:37] } 12. Kb1 { Quite a useful move in such positions. Before launching an attack on the kingside, White brings its king to a safer place. } { [%clk 1:08:41] } 12... Rc8 { [%cal Gc8c3,Gd7a4] [%clk 1:05:51] } 13. h4 { Kateryna spent a long time on this move. She was likely calculating all possible sacrifices from Black, particularly those involving Rxc3 and Bxa4. } { [%clk 0:44:38] } 13... Nh5?! { Let's take a look at the sacrifices. } { [%clk 0:54:31] } (13... Rxc3? 14. bxc3! Nc6 15. h5! { sacrificing a pawn and opening the h-file! } 15... Nxh5 16. Bh6! $16 { White aims to exchange Black's key defender, the dark-squared bishop. White has a strong attack. }) (13... Bxa4! { This is strong! } 14. h5! { White should most likely ignore the bishop and continue the attack. } (14. Nxa4? Rxc2! 15. Qxc2 (15. Qe1 Qe8! $19 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Ge8a4] }) 15... Nxc2 16. Kxc2 d5! $17 { White's pieces are not well coordinated, and the king is not entirely safe. However, Bibisara opts for a prophylactic move, preventing h5, which is somewhat slow. }) 14... Nxh5 15. Bh6! { The position is very sharp. Both sides are attacking on opposite sides of the board, as is typical in opposite-side castling positions. }) 14. Bd4! { White is aiming to exchange dark-squared bishops! } { [%clk 0:43:23] } 14... e5? { This move is a serious mistake. Black wants to keep the dark-squared bishop at all costs and goes for sacrifices, overlooking White's strong response a few moves later. } { [%clk 0:42:43] } (14... Ng3 { 14...Ng3 would have been better. }) 15. Bf2 { [%clk 0:43:01] } 15... d5 { [%clk 0:34:29] } 16. exd5! { [%clk 0:42:56] } 16... Bf5 { [%clk 0:33:44] } 17. Na1! { This move was most likely underestimated by Bibisara. A square that is usually bad for a knight turns out to be excellent here, defending the key c2 - square. After that, Black's attack gets stuck, and White can improve its position. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gg2g4] [%clk 0:36:03] } 17... Nf6 { [%clk 0:28:39] } 18. g4 { [%clk 0:35:46] } 18... Rxc3 { Black tries to complicate the position with an exchange sacrifice. } { [%clk 0:17:03] } (18... Bd7 19. g5 Nh5 20. d6 $18) 19. Qxc3 { [%clk 0:31:00] } 19... Nfxd5 { [%clk 0:14:39] } 20. Qd2! { White should be careful not to allow a tactical shot with ...Nc3. } { [%clk 0:30:27] } (20. Qc5?? Nc3+! $19) 20... Be6 { [%clk 0:12:52] } 21. Nb3 { The knight returns to the game! } { [%clk 0:23:00] } 21... Qf6 { [%clk 0:10:25] } 22. Be2 { [%clk 0:15:50] } 22... Rc8 { [%clk 0:09:52] } 23. c3 { [%clk 0:11:59] } 23... Nc6?! { [%clk 0:06:30] } (23... Nxc3+! { Black should have tried 23...Nc3 as a last chance. } 24. bxc3 Bxb3 25. cxb4 Bc2+! 26. Qxc2 Rxc2 27. Kxc2 e4! { [%cal Gf6b2] } 28. Bd4! { White maintains a significant advantage, but its king is exposed, and Black can hope for a draw. }) 24. Nc5! { Now White's plan is simple: trade pieces and win the endgame with an extra exchange. } { [%clk 0:11:57] } 24... Nf4 { [%clk 0:05:38] } 25. Nxe6 { [%clk 0:12:02] } 25... Nxe2 { [%clk 0:01:51] } 26. Qxe2 { [%clk 0:10:22] } 26... Qxe6 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 27. Qe4 { [%clk 0:10:26] } 27... Qb3 { [%clk 0:01:05] } 28. Rd7 { [%clk 0:09:32] } 28... b5 { [%clk 0:00:37] } 29. axb5 { [%clk 0:09:50] } 29... Qxb5 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 30. Qd5 { [%clk 0:09:55] } 30... Qxd5 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 31. Rxd5 { Kateryna converts her advantage smoothly, giving her opponent no chances. } { [%clk 0:10:23] } 31... f5 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 32. gxf5 { [%clk 0:10:26] } 32... Ne7 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 33. Rd7 { [%clk 0:09:36] } 33... Nxf5 { [%clk 0:01:18] } 34. h5 { [%clk 0:09:48] } 34... a4 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 35. hxg6 { [%clk 0:09:39] } 35... hxg6 { [%clk 0:01:52] } 36. Rg1 { [%clk 0:07:34] } 36... a3 { [%clk 0:00:56] } 37. Rxg6 { [%clk 0:07:44] } 37... axb2 { [%clk 0:01:25] } 38. Kxb2 { [%clk 0:05:31] } 38... Kh7 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 39. Rf6 { [%clk 0:03:55] } 39... Nh6 { [%clk 0:01:51] } 40. Be3 { 1-0 White wins.
