1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:56] } 1... e5 { Vaishali usually plays either 1...c5 or 1...e5. In this game, she opts for 1...e5. } { [%clk 1:30:39] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:17] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:31:01] } 3. Bc4 { Zhu Jiner has both 3.Bc4 and 3.Bb5 in her repertoire. } { [%clk 1:31:09] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:19] } 4. d3 { Interestingly, Vaishali has already had this position twice in this tournament, but with the White pieces: in the third round against Muzychuk and the fourth round against Goryachkina. } { [%clk 1:32:01] } 4... h6 { Goryachkina also played 4...h6 against Vaishali. 4...Bc5 is the main line here, and Vaishali has played it many times before this game. } { [%clk 1:30:59] } (4... Bc5) 5. O-O { [%clk 1:26:31] } (5. a4!? { This was Vaishali's choice in her game against Goryachkina in round four. }) 5... d6 { The idea of this setup is to fianchetto the bishop later with ...g6 and ...Bg7. } { [%clk 1:31:27] } 6. a4!? { I like this move. White plans to advance the pawn and gain space, while keeping the development of the knight on b1 flexible. } { [%clk 1:26:41] } 6... g6 { [%clk 1:31:21] } 7. a5!? { This is an important moment in the game. Should Black allow White's a pawn to advance further, or stop it with 7...a6? } { [%clk 1:26:23] } 7... Bg7 { Vaishali responds instantly with 7...Bg7. In fact, both options are possible. } { [%clk 1:31:29] } (7... a6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. h3 O-O 10. Re1 { with a complex position. }) 8. a6 { [%clk 1:20:45] } 8... b6 { [%clk 1:28:02] } 9. Bb5 { [%clk 1:20:32] } 9... Bd7 { [%clk 1:28:08] } 10. c4!? { An interesting idea. White wants to develop the knight to c3, but only after playing c4 - gaining more space and further controlling the d5 square. } { [%clk 1:20:38] } 10... O-O { [%clk 1:26:42] } 11. Nc3 { In general, I like Zhu Jiner's opening preparation. She has shown creative ideas in almost all her games in this tournament. } { [%clk 1:20:53] } 11... Nd4 { Vaishali took her time before playing this move. It seems her preparation ended here. Both 11...Nb4 and 11...Ne7 have been played in several games. } { [%clk 1:01:50] } (11... Nb4) (11... Ne7) 12. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:15:07] } 12... exd4 { [%clk 1:01:48] } 13. Bxd7 { [%clk 1:15:30] } 13... Nxd7 { [%clk 1:02:41] } 14. Ne2 { White's knight is under attack, and the question is where to move it. Zhu chooses the most natural move. The engine suggests 14.Nb5 and it appears that the knight cannot be easily driven away from b5. } { [%clk 1:15:29] } (14. Nb5!? { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc7c6,Gb5d6] }) 14... c6 { [%clk 0:51:42] } 15. f4 { Another important moment in the game. White intends to improve its position on both sides: with b4 on the queenside and, at some moment, with f5 on the kingside. But what can Black do to generate counterplay? } { [%clk 0:56:09] } 15... f5? { Vaishali aims to prevent White from playing f5. However, this advance weakens the kingside and gives White additional chances there. } { [%clk 0:51:24] } (15... Rb8! { 15...Rb8, with the idea of ...b5 and later recapturing on b5 with the rook, would have given Black sufficient counterplay. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb6b5,Gb8b5] }) 16. Ng3?! { 16.exf5 was stronger! } { [%clk 0:55:59] } (16. exf5! Rxf5 (16... gxf5 17. Ng3! $16 { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gg3h5] }) 17. Ng3! Rf8 18. Qg4 $16 { bringing pieces to the kingside, making White's attack very dangerous. } 18... Kh7 19. Bd2 Nf6 20. Qh3 Qd7 21. f5!) 16... Nc5?! { Black should have taken on e4. } { [%clk 0:48:50] } (16... fxe4! 17. Nxe4 (17. dxe4 Qe7 18. f5 h5! $13) 17... Nf6! $14) 17. b4! { [%clk 0:55:11] } 17... Ne6 { [%clk 0:49:00] } 18. Bd2 $16 { White improves its position on both sides. It is difficult for Black to find good counterplay. } { [%clk 0:45:15] } 18... Qd7 { [%clk 0:47:42] } 19. h4 { [%clk 0:43:28] } 19... d5 { Black tries to break in the centre. } { [%clk 0:36:34] } 20. cxd5! { [%clk 0:41:26] } 20... cxd5 { [%clk 0:36:59] } 21. e5 { White decides to close Black's dark-squared bishop and make the d4-pawn weak. 21.exf5 is also quite good. } { [%csl Bd4] [%clk 0:41:48] } (21. exf5!? gxf5 22. Nh5! $16 { [%csl Bg8] }) 21... h5 { [%clk 0:29:09] } 22. Ne2 { White's plan is simple now: to attack the weak pawn on d4. } { [%csl Gd4] [%clk 0:37:46] } 22... Qb5 { [%clk 0:27:41] } 23. Ra3 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Ga3d3] [%clk 0:28:50] } 23... Rfc8 { [%clk 0:18:44] } 24. Qa1 { White simply targets the weak pawn. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ga1d4,Ge2d4] [%clk 0:28:40] } 24... Rc2 { [%clk 0:18:38] } 25. Rd1 { [%cal Gc2d2,Gd1d2] [%clk 0:29:05] } 25... Kf7 { [%clk 0:14:41] } 26. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:28:00] } 26... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:15:09] } 27. Qxd4 { [%clk 0:28:24] } 27... Ke6 { White has won a pawn, but it is not so easy to convert the advantage, as the positon is quite closed. It is instructive to follow how Zhu gradually improves her position. First, she exchanges Black's active rook on c2. } { [%clk 0:15:13] } 28. Rc3! { [%clk 0:18:56] } 28... Rc8 { [%clk 0:15:25] } 29. Rxc8 { [%clk 0:18:57] } 29... Rxc8 { [%clk 0:15:23] } 30. Qe3 { Then she further improves her pieces. } { [%clk 0:19:21] } 30... Bf8 { [%clk 0:15:24] } 31. Qg3 { [%clk 0:18:37] } 31... Qe8 { [%clk 0:13:21] } 32. b5! { [%clk 0:17:27] } 32... Be7 { [%clk 0:12:00] } 33. Rb1 { [%clk 0:12:40] } 33... Rc2 { [%clk 0:10:33] } 34. Be3 { [%clk 0:12:16] } 34... Rc3 { [%clk 0:09:28] } 35. Bd4 { [%clk 0:12:18] } 35... Rc2 { [%clk 0:09:09] } 36. Kh2 { [%clk 0:11:47] } 36... Bd8 { [%clk 0:07:57] } 37. Ra1 { [%clk 0:07:08] } 37... Qf7 { [%clk 0:06:20] } 38. Be3 { [%clk 0:03:38] } 38... Qe8 { [%clk 0:05:08] } 39. Kh3 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 39... Qf7 { [%clk 0:03:27] } 40. Bc1! { Now the bishop comes to the a3-f8 diagonal. } { [%clk 0:02:44] } 40... Be7 { [%clk 0:00:59] } 41. Ba3! { After exchanging the dark-squared bishops, White's queen can also make use of the dark squares. } { [%clk 0:24:53] } 41... Bxa3 { [%clk 0:06:03] } 42. Rxa3 { [%clk 0:25:18] } 42... Rc8 { [%clk 0:06:17] } 43. Qg5 { [%clk 0:22:15] } 43... Kd7 { [%clk 0:06:22] } 44. d4! { [%csl Gg3][%cal Ga3g3] [%clk 0:15:31] } 44... Rg8 { [%clk 0:05:32] } 45. Rc3! { Now the rook gains the open c-file. } { [%clk 0:15:13] } 45... Re8 { [%clk 0:04:16] } 46. Kh2 { [%clk 0:12:54] } 46... Re6 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 47. Qg3 { The queen also shifts to the c-file. } { [%clk 0:13:18] } 47... Kd8 { [%clk 0:01:16] } 48. Qe1 { [%clk 0:12:52] } 48... Qe7 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 49. Kh3 { [%clk 0:12:49] } 49... Qe8 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 50. Qc1 { The c-file is decisive now. } { [%clk 0:12:58] } 50... Qd7 { [%clk 0:01:11] } 51. Qc2 { [%clk 0:11:43] } 51... Re7 { [%clk 0:01:12] } 52. Qb3 { [%clk 0:11:53] } 52... Re6 { [%clk 0:01:21] } 53. Qb4 { [%clk 0:11:56] } 53... Ke8 { [%clk 0:01:26] } 54. Rc2 { [%clk 0:10:45] } 54... Qd8 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 55. Qc3 { [%clk 0:11:01] } 55... Kd7 { [%clk 0:00:49] } 56. Rc1 { [%clk 0:11:06] } 56... Qb8 { [%clk 0:00:45] } 57. Qb3 { [%clk 0:11:31] } 57... Qa8 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 58. Kg3 { [%clk 0:11:09] } 58... Ke8 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 59. Rc7 { [%clk 0:11:19] } 59... Re7 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 60. Rc6 { [%clk 0:11:39] } 60... Rd7 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 61. Qc2 { [%clk 0:11:44] } 61... Rd8 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 62. Rxg6 { 1-0 White wins.
