{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

The sixth round of the Candidates continued with the same trend as before: Sindarov beating his opponent, this time Wei Yi, in a very clear and convincing way. Even better news for the Uzbek prodigy were that all the remaining games ended up in draws, meaning that his advantage goes from 1 to 1.5 points.

After Sindarov's difficult first round against Esipenko, his dominance has been unquestionable in every single game (which includes a draw against Bluebaum, where the German had to defend a difficult position). Wei Yi, on the other hand, has not been able to perform as well as we had expected. His potential is out of the question, but it seems that he is a bit off in this tournament, not being able to create any serious winning chances in any of his 5 previous games. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:59:54] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:59:50] } 2. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:35] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:59:36] } 3. Bc4!? { Wei Yi plays the Vienna, an opening that has been growing in popularity lately. It is true that solid openings like the Petrov or the Berlin had contributed. } { [%clk 1:59:12] } 3... Nf6 { [%cal Gd1g4] [%clk 1:59:01] } (3... Bc5 4. Qg4! { White already creates some difficulties in this variation. } 4... g6 5. Qf3 Nf6 6. Nge2) 4. d3 { [%clk 1:59:00] } 4... Na5 { [%clk 1:58:54] } 5. a3 { Wei Yi goes for a side line, forcing Black to capture on c5. The main move here is normally: } { [%cal Gc4a2] [%clk 1:58:41] } (5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 7. O-O d6 8. Qd3 { This is the typical setup that might result in this variation. Black gets the B pair, but in response White gets more space to maneuver a very good control over the d5 square. } { [%cal Gb2b3,Ga2a4,Ge2g3,Gc1e3,Ga1d1] }) 5... Nxc4 { [%clk 1:54:47] } 6. dxc4 { [%clk 1:58:10] } 6... Bc5 { Sindarov decides to play with the B out, instead of the solid Be7. } { [%clk 1:51:46] } (6... d6 7. Nge2 Be7 8. Qd3 O-O 9. Ng3 { [%cal Ge1g1,Gf2f4] }) 7. Nf3 { [%clk 1:57:49] } 7... d6 { [%clk 1:50:48] } 8. Qd3 { [%clk 1:57:30] } 8... Be6 { [%clk 1:41:17] } 9. Bg5 { [%clk 1:56:12] } 9... a5! { Very good move. Black doesn't allow White to find the best version to 0-0-0. This is a waiting move that doesn't weaken d6 and also keeps the black K a little bit longer in the center. } { [%clk 1:36:38] } (9... c6 10. O-O-O $36 { [%cal Gg5e3,Gd3d6] }) 10. Nd5 { [%clk 1:54:01] } (10. O-O-O h6 11. Be3 Nd7 { Black's position seems to be fine. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rd7c5] }) 10... c6!? { This shows a very good understanding by Sindarov. Intead of trading on d5, he allows White to capture on f6 to use the g-file with his R. Worst was: } { [%clk 1:32:39] } (10... Bxd5?! 11. cxd5 { [%cal Gd3b5,Gg5d8] } 11... h6 (11... c6 12. O-O-O { White holds a very comfortable position. }) (11... Qd7? 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nh4 $16) 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qb5+) 11. Nxf6+ { [%clk 1:53:40] } (11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Ne3 Bxe3 13. fxe3 (13. Qxe3 Bxc4) 13... Qb6 { Black should have a very decent position as well. } { [%cal Gh8g8,Ge8c8] }) 11... gxf6 { [%clk 1:32:35] } 12. Bh4 { Understandably, Wei tries to keep his pressure against the f6 pawn. } { [%clk 1:53:27] } (12. Be3 Qb6 { Again, Black is just planning to occupy the g file and, if needed, castle Q-side }) 12... Rg8 { [%clk 1:31:08] } 13. O-O { [%clk 1:52:44] } 13... a4 { An interesting move that will offer White the possibility to break on b4 for a price.. } { [%clk 1:28:24] } (13... Rg6!? { This move was an option to offer some freedom for the Q. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Gg6f6] }) 14. b4 { Wei Yi understands that he needs to } { [%clk 1:17:56] } 14... axb3 { [%clk 1:17:49] } 15. cxb3 { [%clk 1:17:13] } 15... Bg4!? { And now it's very clear what Sindarov's intention was. Black is planning to trade on f3 to occupy the d4 square. } { [%clk 1:15:00] } (15... Rxa3!? 16. Rxa3 Bxa3 17. Ra1 Bc5 18. Bxf6 { This was probably Wei Yi's intention. } 18... Rxg2+ $7 { Black needs to play this. } (18... Qc8 19. Nh4 $16) 19. Kxg2 Qxf6 { Despite being down an exchange, black's position should be ok due to the power of the B pair and the exposure of the white's K. } { [%cal Gc5f2,Ge6g4,Gf6f2,Gf6g6] }) 16. b4 { [%clk 1:12:51] } (16. Kh1!? { The engine suggests that this would have been a good try to fight for an advantage. } 16... Bxf3 (16... Rg6 17. a4 $14 { This is a bit anti-intuitive, but White's structure will be easier to defend (compared to the game). That will allow better possibilities to apply pressure on the center/K side. } { [%cal Ga1d1,Gf3d2,Gf2f4] }) 17. Qxf3 Rg6 18. a4! { The idea is to play with a4 instead of b4, keeping the Q-side structure easier to defend. } { [%cal Ga1d1] }) 16... Bxf3 { [%clk 1:14:01] } 17. Qxf3 { [%clk 1:12:42] } 17... Bd4 { [%clk 1:13:58] } 18. Bxf6 { Hard to evaluate as innacurate, but this capture doesn't represent any danger for Black. Wei Yi spent more than half of his time on this move. } { [%clk 0:26:08] } (18. Ra2 { [%csl Ga3] } 18... Rg6 19. h3 Ra4 20. Rb1 { White should be slightly better in this position. }) 18... Qd7 { [%clk 1:13:10] } 19. Rad1 { [%clk 0:21:55] } 19... Qe6! { The most dangerous move for Black. Black applies pressure against c4 and the B on f6. } { [%cal Gg8g6,Ge6c4] [%clk 1:09:21] } (19... Qg4 20. Rd3 (20. Qxg4?! Rxg4 { [%cal Gg4e4,Ga8a3] })) 20. h3 { [%clk 0:17:14] } (20. h4! { Objectively, this is probably white's most accurate move (very difficult for us humans though). } { [%cal Gf6g5] } 20... Rg6 21. Bg5 Qxc4 22. Be3 $132 { [%cal Gh4h5,Gf3f5,Ga8a3] }) 20... Qxc4 { [%clk 1:07:13] } (20... Rg6 21. Bh4 Qxc4 $15 { Was probably a promising option, leaving the white B badly placed on h4. } { [%csl Rh4] }) 21. Rd3 { [%clk 0:15:09] } (21. Rxd4!? { The kind of move that we would expect for the brilliant Wei Yi. White tries to show why Black's K is not completely safe on e8. } 21... Qxd4 (21... exd4 22. Rd1 Qe6 23. Rxd4 Rg6 24. e5 $36 { [%cal Gf6e5,Gd4h4,Gd4e4,Ge4e8,Gh4h7] }) 22. Rd1 Rxa3 23. Rxd4 Rxf3 24. Rxd6 Rxf6 $10 { This was probably Sindarov's best option, keeping a balanced endgame. }) 21... Qe6 { [%clk 1:01:13] } 22. Rfd1 { [%clk 0:15:01] } (22. Rxd4! { Again the active option, White needs to keep his pieces active. But Wei was already low on time. } 22... exd4 23. Bxd4 $132 { [%cal Gf1e1,Ge4e5] }) 22... Rg6 { [%clk 0:59:40] } 23. Bh4 { [%clk 0:14:59] } 23... Kf8 { [%clk 0:57:34] } (23... c5!?) 24. Qh5 { [%clk 0:12:17] } 24... Kg8 { [%clk 0:55:14] } 25. Kh1 { [%clk 0:10:02] } 25... c5! $17 { After putting his K on a safer square, Sindarov is finally ready to take advantage of his possibilities. } { [%clk 0:54:21] } 26. f4?! { Wei Yi tries his best to stay active, but not at the right moment. } { [%clk 0:07:50] } (26. bxc5 dxc5 27. Qe2 c4 { Honestly, this doesn't look any better } { [%cal Gc5c4] }) 26... exf4 { [%clk 0:53:27] } 27. Qf3 { [%clk 0:06:29] } 27... Re8?! { Trying to take advantage of Wei's clock issues, Sindarov plays fast and allows White to get back into the game. } { [%clk 0:51:36] } (27... Be5 $19 { Keeping good defense of the pawn, Black will play c4 next. } { [%cal Gc5c4] }) 28. Bf2! { Good move by Wei Yi! } { [%clk 0:06:13] } 28... Bxf2 { [%clk 0:49:30] } (28... Be5 { Is not longer possible due to } 29. bxc5 dxc5 30. Bxc5) 29. Qxf2 { [%clk 0:06:12] } 29... Qxe4 { [%clk 0:49:23] } 30. Rxd6?? { With time trouble approaching, Wei Yi chooses the wrong pawn. White had very good chances to defend after: } { [%clk 0:05:09] } (30. bxc5 dxc5 31. Rf3! { The key move! } { [%cal Gf3f4,Gf2c5] } 31... b6 32. Rxf4 Qe6 33. Rf1 $13 { Despite being down a pawn, White's chances to hold are extremely high due to his active pieces and the vulnerable K. }) 30... Rxd6 { [%clk 0:48:24] } 31. Rxd6 { [%clk 0:05:07] } 31... Qe3! { And again: the kid never misses! Sindarov takes full advantage of his chances. The game is over. } { [%clk 0:48:14] } 32. Qf3 { [%clk 0:01:38] } (32. Qh4 Qg3 $19 { [%csl Rh1] }) (32. Kg1 Qc1+ 33. Kh2 Re1 $19 { [%cal Ge1h1] }) (32. Rd2 c4 $19 { Were not any better. }) 32... c4 { [%clk 0:46:45] } (32... Qxf3 33. gxf3 c4 { This is also winning. }) 33. Qg4+ { [%clk 0:01:37] } 33... Kf8 { [%clk 0:45:47] } 34. Rd1 { [%clk 0:01:13] } 34... c3 { [%clk 0:44:54] } 35. Qg5 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 35... f3 { [%clk 0:44:07] } 36. Qxe3 { [%clk 0:00:54] } 36... Rxe3 { Another great demonstration by Javokhir Sindarov, this time in a more positional way, who scores another massive win as Black. He has been showing a lot of consistency and pretty much no flaws. On the other hand, another bad day for Wei Yi who gets his second loss in the tournament. } { [%clk 0:44:04] } 0-1


