{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

Hikaru Nakamura and Praggnanandhaa played a very balanced game that ended in a 3-fold repetition. Hikaru has not been able to bring his A-game yet. Furthermore, Pragg had a strong start in the event (great win vs Giri in Round 1) but, soon after, suffered a critical defeat in Round 3 vs Sindarov. }
1. d4 { [%clk 1:59:56] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:21] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:45] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:59:07] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:21] } 3... Bb4 { [%clk 1:58:59] } 4. e3 { [%clk 1:59:17] } 4... b6 { [%clk 1:58:36] } 5. Ne2 { [%clk 1:58:59] } 5... c5 { [%clk 1:57:39] } 6. a3 { [%clk 1:57:13] } 6... Ba5 { [%clk 1:57:33] } 7. Bd2 { Played after a brief deliberation. White also had the alternative of playing: } { [%clk 1:51:22] } (7. Rb1 Na6 8. g3 Bb7 9. d5 b5 $132) 7... O-O { [%clk 1:56:21] } 8. d5 { [%clk 1:47:56] } 8... exd5 { [%clk 1:55:37] } 9. Nxd5?! { In this event, Hikaru has not been very impressive with his opening choices. As a result of this, he has not been able to put his opponents in any sort of difficulty. In my opinion, a better option was to capture with the pawn: } { [%clk 1:41:55] } (9. cxd5 d6 (9... Ba6 10. Ng3 Bxf1 11. Kxf1 { Similar to the game, but with more pieces on the board (and a bad looking B on a5)! } { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] }) (9... Bb7 10. Nf4 Qe7 11. Bd3 $36) 10. Ng3 Bb7 11. e4 $36) 9... Nxd5 { [%clk 1:51:40] } 10. cxd5 { [%clk 1:41:13] } 10... Bxd2+ { This is the big difference. After trading this B, Black has solved most of his problems. } { [%cal Ga5d2] [%clk 1:51:04] } 11. Qxd2 { [%clk 1:41:09] } 11... Ba6 { [%clk 1:47:24] } 12. Ng3 { [%clk 1:32:01] } 12... Bxf1 { [%clk 1:46:17] } 13. Kxf1 { Compared to the other position mentioned in the line with 9.cxd5. } { [%clk 1:31:59] } 13... d6 { [%clk 1:36:29] } 14. h4!? { Naka goes for the right plan. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gd8h4] [%clk 1:24:02] } (14. e4 Qh4 15. f3 g6 $15 { Black is definitely happier here. } { [%cal Gf7f5,Gb8d7,Ga8e8] }) 14... Nd7 { [%clk 1:32:59] } 15. e4 { [%clk 1:23:41] } (15. h5 Qg5) 15... Qf6 { [%clk 1:25:39] } 16. Re1 { [%clk 1:09:46] } (16. Rh3!?) 16... g6 { [%clk 1:13:16] } 17. h5 { White doesn't want to allow black to play h5. } { [%clk 1:08:42] } 17... Ne5 { [%clk 1:12:28] } 18. Rh3 { [%clk 1:01:56] } (18. Qh6 Qg7) 18... b5!? { Pragg correctly understands that his opportunities will mostly come on the Q-side. } { [%clk 1:06:40] } (18... c4 { Was prob ok as well. }) 19. Kg1 { [%clk 0:54:35] } 19... c4 { [%clk 0:56:17] } 20. Qh6 { Making a draw offer. Hikaru probably understood that Black had more chances of improving on the Q-side than he had on the K-side. } { [%clk 0:50:59] } (20. Rf1 Nd3 { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gf6b2] } 21. Qh6 Qg7 22. Qg5 { This was probably a good alternative to keep the game going. } { [%cal Gf2f4] }) 20... Ng4 { [%cal Gf6f2] [%clk 0:52:36] } (20... Qxf2+?? { Despite looking good, this move doesn't work. } 21. Kxf2 Ng4+ 22. Ke2 Nxh6 23. hxg6) (20... Qg7 21. Qg5 $132 { Similar to the previous line. } { [%cal Gf2f4] }) 21. Qd2 { [%clk 0:50:39] } 21... Ne5 { [%clk 0:50:12] } 22. Qh6 { [%clk 0:50:29] } 22... Ng4 { [%clk 0:47:01] } 23. Qd2 { [%clk 0:50:27] } 23... Ne5 { After analyzing his chances, Pragg accepts the draw offer. Despite being a short game, the game definitely offered some interesting alternatives for both players.
The other two remaining games of the round, Caruana- Esipenko and Giri-Bluebaum, ended up in draws with no real chances for any of the four players. } { [%clk 0:27:09] } 1/2-1/2


