{ Annotated by IM / WGM Lilit Mkrtchian - https://lichess.org/@/Lilit-Mkrtchian

Round 6 featured a clash between the tournament leaders, Zhu and Muzychuk. A tense and balanced struggle was expected. Zhu had won her last two games and was in good form, while Muzychuk had been playing strong chess and remained undefeated. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:55] } 1... e5 { Anna has two main weapons against 1.e4: either 1...c5, leading to the Sicilian, or 1...e5. In this tournament, she chose 1...e5 against Divya and Vaishali, and the Sicilian against Goryachkina. Today: 1...e5 again. } { [%clk 1:30:53] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:30:46] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:31:15] } 3. Bc4 { For the third time in this tournament, Zhu opts for 3.Bc4, although 3.Bb5 is also part of her repertoure. It seems she has prepared some interesting ideas especially in the 3.Bc4 lines. } { [%clk 1:31:39] } 3... Bc5 { Zhu faced 3...Nf6 in her previous games against Tan (Round 1) and Vaishali (Round 5). She demonstrated good preparation and creative ideas in those games. } { [%clk 1:31:38] } (3... Nf6 4. d3) 4. d3 { [%clk 1:31:58] } 4... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:44] } 5. Be3!? { Another relatively new idea from Zhu. White aims to exchange Black's strong dark-squared bishop at once. The main continatuions are 5.c3 and 5.0-0. } { [%clk 1:32:18] } (5. c3) (5. O-O) 5... Bxe3 { Anna spent some time here to decide whether to exchange on e3 or retreat the bishop to b6 and exchange it there. Both options are perfectly playable. } { [%clk 1:27:33] } (5... Bb6) 6. fxe3 { [%clk 1:32:11] } 6... d6 { [%clk 1:27:46] } 7. Qd2!? { White prevents 7...Na5, which would lead to the exchange of the strong bishop. } { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gc6a5] [%clk 1:32:58] } (7. O-O Na5!? { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga5c4] }) 7... a6 { A standard move in such positions. } { [%clk 1:24:00] } 8. Bb3 { White can also consider castling. However, Zhu plays these moves quickly, suggesting that she is still following her preparation. } { [%clk 1:32:18] } (8. O-O b5 9. Bb3 O-O 10. a4 Bd7 { with a playable position for both sides. }) 8... Be6!? { Faced with a new idea, Anna remains calm and makes solid and accurate moves. She aims to exchange White's strong bishop in a similar way. } { [%clk 1:16:25] } 9. Nc3 { [%clk 1:31:26] } 9... Bxb3 { [%clk 1:12:30] } 10. axb3 { [%clk 1:30:49] } 10... d5!? { A typical break in the centre. } { [%clk 1:09:16] } 11. exd5 { [%clk 1:30:31] } 11... Nxd5 { Only now does Zhu take her time. } { [%clk 1:09:39] } 12. O-O { [%clk 1:20:52] } 12... O-O { All the pieces are developed and both sides have castled. What should both sides do next? With no obvious weaknesses or clear plans, both sides will try to improve their positions gradually. A slow manoeuvring phase begins, which is typical of such positions. } { [%clk 1:08:21] } 13. Ne4 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ge4c5] [%clk 1:18:45] } 13... Qe7 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7c5] [%clk 1:02:43] } 14. Ng3 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gg3f5] [%clk 1:17:12] } 14... g6 { [%clk 1:01:51] } (14... f5!? { 14...f5 is a more active option and is also perfectly playable. }) 15. e4 { [%clk 1:00:46] } 15... Nf6 { [%clk 0:55:24] } (15... Nf4!? { 15...Nf4 can lead to a comlex position after } 16. Nxe5!? Qxe5 17. Qxf4 Qxb2 { [%csl Gc2] } 18. Rac1 a5!? $13 { However, 15...Nf6 is the more solid option. }) 16. Kh1 { A useful move, so that there are no future checks along the a1-g7 diagonal. } { [%clk 1:00:41] } 16... Nd7 { From this point on, the game becomes more dynamic. Black aims to regroup the knight via f6-d7-e6, where it will control the important squares d4 and f4. } { [%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Gc5e6] [%clk 0:52:35] } 17. Ne2!? { White also wants to improve the knight from g3, where it does little, to a better square. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ge2c3,Gc3d5] [%clk 0:56:38] } 17... Rad8 { [%clk 0:50:15] } (17... Nc5 { After the immediate 17...Nc5, interesting variations can arise. } 18. Nc3 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] } 18... Nb4 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gb4d5] } 19. Nd1!? { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gd2b4] } 19... a5 20. Ne3!? { A nice idea! The knight is well placed on e3, eyeing d5, defending c2, and being closer to the kingside. }) 18. Rf2 { [%clk 0:55:08] } (18. Nc3!? { The idea of bringing the knight to e3 is so appealing! } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] } 18... Nb4 (18... Nf6 { The engine suggests 18...Nf8 to prevent Nd5. However, psychologically it is not easy to bring the knight back to f6 when the initial plan was to regroup it via c5-e6. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gf6d5] }) 19. Nd1!? { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gd1e3] }) 18... Nc5 { [%csl Ge6,Ge4][%cal Gc5e6,Gc5e4] [%clk 0:45:40] } 19. Nc3 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] [%clk 0:48:48] } 19... Nb4 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gb4d5] [%clk 0:36:49] } 20. Raf1 { However, White has another idea in mind: doubling the rooks on the f-file and then pushing the h-pawn to create threats on the kingside. } { [%clk 0:42:06] } (20. Nd1?? { Now 20.Nd1 runs into 20...Ne4! } 20... Nxe4! $19) 20... f6 { Black defends the e5-pawn, preparing to play Ne6. } { [%clk 0:33:25] } 21. h4 { [%clk 0:41:41] } 21... Ne6 { [%clk 0:31:56] } 22. Nh2? { White aims to bring the knight to g4 to put pressure on Black's position, but in doing so removes the knight controlling d4, allowing ...Nd4, attacking the c2-pawn. } { [%csl Gg4,Gf6,Gh6][%cal Gh2g4] [%clk 0:37:50] } (22. h5! { Instead, 22.h5 is stronger. }) 22... Nd4! { A strong reply by Anna! The counterplay begins, and Black seizes the initiative. } { [%cal Gb4c2,Gd4c2] [%clk 0:27:36] } 23. Qd1 { [%clk 0:28:38] } (23. Ng4 { 23.Ng4 runs into } 23... f5! 24. Nh6+ Kg7 $17 { [%csl Gh4][%cal Ge7h4] }) 23... f5! { [%csl Gh4][%cal Ge7h4] [%clk 0:21:51] } 24. g3 { [%clk 0:23:34] } (24. exf5 Rxf5! 25. g3 Rdf8! 26. Rxf5 gxf5 27. Rf2 Qe6 $17) 24... f4! { Anna plays very energetically, and suddenly White's position begins to collapse. } { [%csl Gh4,Gc2] [%clk 0:20:28] } 25. gxf4 { [%clk 0:23:40] } 25... Rxf4! { [%csl Gh4] [%clk 0:16:21] } 26. h5 { [%clk 0:14:09] } (26. Rxf4 exf4 27. Rxf4 Ndxc2! $19 { [%csl Gd3] }) 26... Ndxc2! { Another strong decision by Anna. She gives up her two excellent knights for a rook and some pawns, obtaining a decisive advantage. } { [%clk 0:15:07] } 27. Rxc2 { [%clk 0:13:36] } 27... Rxf1+ { [%clk 0:13:32] } 28. Nxf1 { [%clk 0:14:00] } 28... Nxc2 { [%clk 0:09:48] } 29. Qxc2 { [%clk 0:14:24] } 29... Qh4+ { [%clk 0:09:56] } 30. Nh2 { [%clk 0:07:08] } (30. Q