1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:55] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:30:37] } 2. Bc4 { Kateryna usually plays 2.Nf3, and after 2...Nc6 she has 3.Bb5, 3.Bc4, and 3.Nc3 in her repertoire. It seems she has prepared a different move order for this game. } { [%clk 1:31:03] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:52] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 1:31:27] } 3... Nc6 { [%clk 1:30:59] } 4. d3 { [%clk 1:31:34] } 4... Bb4 { This variation was seen in Vaishali's game against Fatalieva last year in Samarkand, where White played 5.a3. Interestingly, this exact position also appeared today in the Men's Candidates game between Wei and Sindarov, where Black played 4...Na5. } { [%clk 1:31:06] } 5. Nf3 { Kateryna opts for 5.Nf3, transposing into the Four Knights Game. } { [%clk 1:31:15] } 5... h6 { Preventing Bg5. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gc1g5] [%clk 1:30:31] } 6. O-O { [%clk 1:30:50] } 6... Bxc3!? { [%clk 1:30:12] } (6... O-O { In case of 6.0-0, White can respond with7.Nd5. } 7. Nd5!? Bc5 8. c3!? { Vaishali chooses a more common approach after ...Bb4, exchanging on c3, doubling White's pawn and avoiding positions with Nd5. }) 7. bxc3 { [%clk 1:31:15] } 7... O-O { [%clk 1:30:29] } 8. Re1 { A standard move in such positions. } { [%clk 1:28:26] } 8... d6 { [%clk 1:30:35] } 9. h3 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gc8g4] [%clk 1:26:26] } 9... Na5!? { Attacking the bishop on c4 and preparing ...c5. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga5c4] [%clk 1:30:29] } 10. Bb3 { [%clk 1:26:36] } 10... c5!? { From her use of time, it is clear that Vaishali is still in her preparation and is very familiar with these positions. She plays such positions with both colours and has clearly studied them thoroughly. Overall, her opening preparation is impressive. After 10...c5, she aims to advance the c-pawn further and weaken White's queenside pawns. It is also instructive that Black refrains from exchanging the bishop on b3, thus avoiding improving White's queenside pawn structure. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc5c4] [%clk 1:30:19] } 11. c4 { After spending some time, Kateryna decided to prevent Black's ...c4 by playing 11.c4 herself. If } { [%clk 1:16:18] } (11. Nd2 Be6 { ...c4 is again a threat. It seems White has no choice but to prevent it with c4. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc5c4] }) 11... Nh7! { After 11.c4, the bishop on b3 is locked in, and Black can immediately prepare ...f5, opening the f-file and activating the pieces. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf7f5] [%clk 1:26:52] } 12. c3 { Preparing the d4 break in the centre. Another option was to leave the queenside pawn structure as it is and regroup the knight. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd3d4] [%clk 1:04:21] } (12. Nh2!? { [%cal Gh2f1,Gf1g3,Gf1e3] } 12... f5 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Nf1 b6 15. Ng3 { [%cal Gg3f5,Gg3e4] } 15... Bd7 16. Be3 $13) 12... f5 { [%clk 1:13:46] } 13. exf5 { In case of 13.d4, } { [%clk 0:57:20] } (13. d4 fxe4 14. Rxe4 Bf5 15. Re1 { it transposes into the game continuation. }) 13... Bxf5 { [%clk 1:14:10] } 14. d4 { [%clk 0:44:16] } 14... e4 { Avoiding the exchange on d4, which would undouble the c-pawns. } { [%clk 1:13:27] } 15. Nh2! { [%clk 0:44:41] } (15. Nd2? { This would allow 15...Qh4, when the White king is no longer entirely safe. } 15... Qh4! { [%csl Bg1] }) 15... b6 { Now 15...Qh4 runs into... } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gd8h4] [%clk 1:02:10] } (15... Qh4 16. dxc5! dxc5 17. Qd5+ Kh8 18. Qxc5 b6 19. Qe3 $14 { Vaishali defends the c5-pawn, preparing ...Qh4. }) 16. Qh5 { This prevents ...Qh4 and activates the queen. } { [%clk 0:23:22] } 16... Qf6 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf6d4] [%clk 0:48:25] } 17. Be3 { [%clk 0:23:37] } 17... Rae8 { Bringing the rook into the centre. } { [%clk 0:48:17] } 18. Rad1 { White does the same. } { [%clk 0:19:09] } 18... Be6 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga5c4,Ge6c4] [%clk 0:47:10] } 19. Qe2? { An important moment in the game. White's c4-pawn is under attack, and it seems natural to defend it with the queen. However, this allows ...Qf7, increasing the pressure on c4 and forcing d5, after which the position becomes more closed - something that does not favour the side with the bishop pair. White is left with weak 