{ Annotated by GM Axel Bachmann - https://lichess.org/@/ABachmann

The seventh round of the Candidates was played this Sunday, with only one game being decisive: Wei Yi's win as Black over Esipenko.

Today we were able to see Wei Yi's best version, grabbing the initiative after a serious opening mistake by Esipenko and not letting him escape. The remaining 3 matches ended up in draws: Sindarov - Giri (where Giri fought hard to hold), Bluebaum-Naka, and Pragg-Caruana, whose games were pretty balanced throughout. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:59:55] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:59:54] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:49] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:45] } 3. d4 { [%clk 1:59:41] } 3... Nxe4 { [%clk 1:59:30] } 4. Qe2!? { Esipenko comes with another tricky move order. This tournament has shown us that classical is far from over, with players showing up very creative move orders to create practical problems. } { [%clk 1:59:29] } 4... d5 { [%clk 1:55:34] } 5. Nxe5 { [%clk 1:58:56] } 5... Be7 { [%clk 1:43:42] } 6. f3 { [%clk 1:58:15] } 6... Nd6 { [%clk 1:41:17] } (6... Nf6 { Normally the N prefers d6 to avoid getting attacked with g4-g5 easily. } { [%cal Gg2g4] }) 7. Nc3 { [%clk 1:58:05] } 7... Nf5 { [%clk 1:33:10] } (7... c6 8. Bf4 O-O 9. O-O-O { This was probably what Andrey had in mind. The position will get very complicated with both sides attacking their opponent's K. } { [%cal Gh2h4,Gg2g4,Bb7b5,Ba7a5] }) 8. Qf2 { [%clk 1:57:05] } 8... O-O { [%clk 1:28:20] } 9. Bf4 { [%clk 1:56:28] } 9... f6 { [%clk 1:21:22] } 10. Nd3 { [%clk 1:49:44] } 10... Nc6 { Wei Yi understands that he needs to act fast in order to avoid being under heavy pressure. Worse was: } { [%clk 1:20:15] } (10... c6 11. g4 Nd6 12. O-O-O b5 13. h4 $16 { White's initiative seems to be a lot more dangerous due to the piece being better placed. } { [%cal Gf2g3,Gb5b4,Gc3a4,Gc1b1] }) 11. Ne2 { [%clk 1:45:53] } 11... Nb4! { Another good one! } { [%clk 1:20:00] } 12. Nxb4 { [%clk 1:44:34] } 12... Bxb4+ { [%clk 1:19:55] } 13. c3 { [%clk 1:44:27] } 13... Bd6 { [%clk 1:19:51] } 14. Bd2? { Very serious mistake. Looking at how fast Esipenko was still playing, makes me believe that he probably saw a similar position where the trade had to be avoided. And indeed, he was right! But he needed to castle first, as we will see: } { [%clk 1:42:44] } (14. O-O-O Re8 (14... Qe8 15. Re1 $14) (14... Bxf4+ 15. Nxf4 { [%cal Gf1d3,Gg2g4,Gf2d2] }) 15. Bd2 $36 { And this is the right version that he was probably trying to get. } { [%cal Gg2g4] }) 14... Qe8! $17 { After this great move, White's position becomes a complete nightmare. } { [%cal Ge8e2,Ge8a4] [%clk 1:16:27] } 15. Kd1 { Sad, sad necessity. } { [%clk 1:06:32] } (15. O-O-O Qa4! $19 { This was probably what Esipenko missed. } { [%cal Ra4a2,Ra4d1] } 16. a3 Bxa3 17. bxa3 Qxa3+ 18. Kc2 (18. Kb1 Ne3 $19 { [%cal Gc8f5] }) 18... Qa2+ 19. Kc1 Bd7 { Black is winning } { [%cal Gd7a4] }) (15. g4 Ne7 { With the K unable to go anywhere, this expansion might make White's position even worse. } { [%cal Gf6f5] }) 15... Qa4+ { [%clk 1:10:54] } 16. Kc1 { [%clk 1:05:40] } (16. b3 Qa3 17. Bc1 Qa5 { Black will create threats continuosly.. } { [%cal Gc7c5] }) 16... b5?! { [%clk 0:52:45] } (16... Bd7 { Black simply needs to bring his pieces out to take advantage of White's lack of coordination. } { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc7c5] } 17. Nf4 c5 { [%cal Ga4f4,Gd6f4] }) 17. Nf4 { Right idea, wrong move order: the story of Esipenko in this Candidates! } { [%clk 0:54:34] } (17. g4! { This was a great opportunity for white to complicate things. } 17... Ne7 18. Nf4 c5 19. Bd3 c4 (19... cxd4 20. Qxd4 Qxd4 21. cxd4 $132) 20. Bc2 Qa6 21. Qh4 $15 { Despite black's advantage, we can definitely feel white is still in the game! }) 17... c5! { This time, Wei doesn't miss the opportunity. } { [%clk 0:46:39] } 18. Bd3 { [%clk 0:47:18] } (18. g4?! cxd4 19. gxf5 dxc3 { The same resource doesn't work now. } { [%cal Gd6f4] }) 18... cxd4 { [%clk 0:44:13] } 19. Bc2 { [%clk 0:46:00] } 19... Qa6 { [%clk 0:44:00] } 20. cxd4 { [%clk 0:45:26] } 20... Bd7 $17 { With simple moves, Black got a very promising position. } { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c1] [%clk 0:41:53] } 21. Kb1 { [%clk 0:34:27] } 21... Rac8 { [%clk 0:38:54] } 22. Bd3 { [%clk 0:33:49] } 22... Rc4!? { This is the Wei Yi we know! } { [%clk 0:30:39] } (22... Rfe8 { Was also fine, but less spectacular. } 23. g4 Ne7 24. h4 Qb6 { [%cal Ge7c6,Gc6d4] }) 23. Ne2 { [%clk 0:32:15] } (23. Bxc4 dxc4 { Black's initiative is overwhelming. } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Gf5b1,Gf5e7,Gd7f5,Gb5b4,Gc4c3] } 24. g4 b4! { [%cal Gc4c3] }) (23. b3 Rxd4) 23... Ne7 { [%clk 0:19:41] } (23... Ba3! { This would have been too much. The engine suggests this brilliant idea, taking advantage of White's K and also creating the d6 square for the black N. } { [%cal Gf5d6] } 24. bxa3 (24. Bxc4 bxc4 { [%cal Gf8b8,Gb8b2] }) (24. g4 Nd6 $36) 24... Qxa3 25. Nc1 Rxc1+ { [%cal Ga3d3] }) 24. g4 { [%clk 0:31:33] } (24. a3!? { This is a great defensive idea: White stops b4 (which is one of the main ideas for Black, as we will see in the next few moves). }) 24... Rfc8 { [%clk 0:16:46] } (24... f5! { Playing in the whole board: Black can exploit opportunities on both sides of the board. } 25. Qg2 (25. g5 f4 { [%cal Gd7f5] }) 25... b4 $19 { [%csl Rb1,Rg2][%cal Gd7b5] }) 25. h4? { [%clk 0:29:45] } (25. a3! { Again, white needed to stop b4! } 25... Qb6 26. Ra2 b4 27. Bxc4 dxc4 28. axb4 $132 { [%csl Ge2][%cal Ga2b2,Gd2b4,Ge2c3] }) 25... b4! { Wei Yi shows goes for the best idea. } { [%clk 0:14:42] } 26. b3 { [%clk 0:20:37] } (26. h5 Bb5 { This is the main idea of the b4 resource. } { [%cal Gc4c1] }) 26... Bb5! { [%clk 0:14:40] } 27. bxc4 { [%clk 0:16:08] } (27. Nf4 Bxf4 28. Bxf4 Rc1+ { White is either losing a lot of material or getting checkmated. } { [%cal Gb5d3,Ga6a3] }) 27... Bxc4! { [%clk 0:13:57] } (27... dxc4? 28. Bc2 c3 29. Bc1 { White should still be lost, but it is far more complicated than the line played by Wei Yi. }) 28. Bc2 { [%clk 0:09:43] } (28. Bxc4 Qxc4 { The Q enters the attack and finishes the game. } 29. Rc1 Qd3+ 30. Kb2 Qxd2+ { [%cal Gd2f2] } 31. Kb3 Rc3+! { [%cal Gc8c3,Gd2f2] } 32. Rxc3 (32. Nxc3 Qxf2) 32... bxc3 { [%cal Ge7c6,Gc6a5,Gd2b2] }) 28... Bd3 { [%clk 0:13:51] } 29. Bc3 { [%clk 0:08:59] } 29... bxc3 { [%clk 0:06:16] } 30. Nc1 { [%clk 0:04:51] } 30... Rb8+ { 0-1 Black wins.
With Qa3 & R*b3-Bf4 getting in, Esipenko resigned.
Great game played Wei Yi, who now gets a little bit closer to the 50% mark. In contrast, this result closes Esipenko's first half with a very disappointing 2/7. A little bit unfair to the Russian talent, who has played some really good chess at moments and has been the only one who got a very good advantage vs Sindarov. } { [%cal Ga6a3,Ga3b2] [%clk 0:06:13] } 0-1


