This position has been played multiple times by the very good Hungarian GM, Robert Ruck (with two wins). But objectively speaking, the position should be around equal. }) 18. Qxe7 { [%clk 1:56:38] } 18... Nxe7 { [%clk 1:30:48] } 19. Nxb7 { [%clk 1:56:09] } 19... Rdb8 { [%clk 1:08:52] } 20. Nxa5 { [%clk 1:54:36] } (20. Ba6 Bb6 21. Nd6 $14 { This also looks a bit unpleasant. Looking at Sindarov's pace, it makes me feel that he knew both possibilities and preferred the one that was played in the game. } { [%cal Ga6c8,Gf3e5] }) 20... Rxb5 { [%clk 1:08:06] } 21. Nb3 { [%clk 1:54:27] } 21... a5 { [%clk 1:07:12] } 22. Rd2 { [%clk 1:46:10] } 22... a4 { [%clk 1:03:43] } (22... Rab8!? { This move order forces White to play with Rcc2 or Rb1. } 23. Rcc2 Nc6 24. Nbd4 R5b6 25. b3 a4 $10 { Very similar to the game: I do prefer to trade one of the white Ns. }) 23. Nbd4 { [%clk 1:45:47] } 23... Rb7 { [%clk 1:03:33] } 24. h3 { [%clk 1:44:38] } (24. Ne1!? { [%cal Ge1d3] }) 24... Rab8 { [%clk 1:02:39] } 25. b3 { [%clk 1:44:29] } 25... axb3 { [%clk 1:01:36] } 26. axb3 { [%clk 1:44:24] } 26... f6 { [%clk 0:52:15] } (26... Ng6 { Despite White's position being more pleasant, I have a feeling that relocating the N to e6 would have offered Black an easier way to hold. } { [%cal Gg6f8,Gf8e6,Gg6f4,Gf4e6,Rb7b3] }) 27. g4 { [%clk 1:32:17] } 27... h5 { [%clk 0:49:34] } 28. Ne1 { [%clk 1:31:17] } 28... hxg4 { [%clk 0:41:32] } 29. hxg4 { [%clk 1:30:42] } 29... Ng6 { [%clk 0:27:53] } 30. f3 { [%clk 1:26:00] } 30... Ne5 { [%clk 0:27:04] } 31. Kf2 { [%clk 1:25:37] } (31. Nd3 { This move was played a move later, but I do feel that this is a good case of "the sooner, the better". } { [%cal Gd3c5,Gd3f4,Gc1c5] }) 31... g5 { [%clk 0:25:40] } 32. Nd3 { [%clk 1:23:46] } 32... Bd7 { [%clk 0:24:07] } 33. Kg3 { [%clk 1:17:23] } (33. Rc5! Kf7 34. Rxd5 Nxd3+ 35. Rxd3 $14 { Black's K and the current situation with the rooks, don't allow Black to play Be6 so easily: } { [%csl Rb7,Rb8,Rf7] } 35... Be6 36. Rd6 Bxb3 3