 moves, or play f4. Vaishali opts for the aggresive f4 push, which is quite double-edged. Other options also lead to complex play. } { [%clk 1:18:14] } 9. f4 { [%clk 0:59:27] } (9. d5!?) (9. Re1!? O-O 10. Ng3 $13) 9... O-O { Black could have played the cunning 9...Qe7, keeping both castling options in reserve. } { [%clk 1:18:16] } (9... Qe7!? { For instance, 10.Ng3 would be a mistake due to } 10. Ng3? h5! { [%csl Gc8][%cal Ge8c8,Ge8g8,Gh5h4] } 11. Ne2 O-O-O! $17) 10. Ng3 { Now it is time for Black to decide how to proceed in the centre: whether to maintain the tension or to resolve it. In general, the position is very complex, and both options are perfectly playable. } { [%clk 0:47:10] } 10... Ba6 { Tan first decides to attack White's rook. } { [%clk 1:09:59] } (10... exd4!? 11. cxd4 c5!? $13) (10... Qe7!?) 11. Rf3 { [%clk 0:42:14] } (11. fxe5!? dxe5 12. Re1 { ... is a good alternative to the move played in the game. }) 11... exd4!? { After some thought, Tan decides to change the central structure. The game now becomes very dynamic, requiring move-by-move calculation. } { [%clk 0:54:19] } 12. cxd4 { [%clk 0:42:38] } 12... c5!? { [%clk 0:54:18] } 13. e5! { This is the best move in the position. After the inaccurate 13.d5, Black can seize the initiative. } { [%clk 0:36:03] } (13. d5?! Ng4! { [%cal Gg7d4,Gd4g1] } 14. Nb3 Bc4! { [%cal Gc4b3,Gg7d4] } 15. h3! Bxb3 16. Rxb3 Bd4+ 17. Kf1 Nh2+ 18. Ke2 Qh4 $36) 13... Ne8! { After, } { [%clk 0:53:27] } (13... dxe5 14. dxe5 Ng4 15. Nde4! { ... White's chances are preferable. }) 14. Be4! { After a long think, Vaishali finds an interesting idea. } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Ge4a8] [%clk 0:16:40] } 14... Rc8 { [%clk 0:53:22] } 15. Ra3! { [%csl Ga7][%cal Ga3a7] [%clk 0:15:04] } 15... Nb8 { [%cal Gb8a6] [%clk 0:53:21] } 16. Rxa6 { Creativly played. However, there is a quieter continuation in this sharp position. } { [%clk 0:12:43] } (16. Nf3 cxd4 17. Qxd4 (17. Nh5!?) 17... dxe5 18. Qxd8 Rxd8 19. fxe5 Rd1+ 20. Kf2 Nc7 21. Bc2 $13) 16... Nxa6 