] }) 28. Qxe2! { [%clk 0:01:21] } 28... dxe2 { [%clk 0:18:50] } 29. Ng3! { After exchanging queens, Black's powerful pawn falls, and White gets good drawing chances. } { [%clk 0:01:42] } 29... Re8 { [%clk 0:19:05] } 30. Nxe4! { [%clk 0:00:54] } 30... Rxe4 { [%clk 0:19:22] } 31. Kf2! { [%csl Ge2] [%clk 0:01:18] } 31... Bxb2 { [%clk 0:19:26] } 32. Re1 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 32... Rxa4 { [%clk 0:16:31] } 33. Rxe2 { [%clk 0:01:11] } 33... Bf6 { After all these more or less forced moves, Black is still pawn up. However, White can activate the rook, placing it behind the passed a-pawn and making its advance difficult. } { [%clk 0:16:53] } 34. Rc2 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 34... h5 { [%clk 0:16:54] } 35. Kf3 { [%clk 0:00:57] } 35... a5 { [%clk 0:17:14] } 36. Rc6 { [%clk 0:00:34] } 36... Kg7 { [%clk 0:17:26] } 37. Ra6! { White got what she wanted: the rook is behind the passed a-pawn. With accurate play, White should hold this position. } { [%clk 0:00:42] } 37... Ra1?? { But now comes a shocking blunder... } { [%clk 0:16:33] } 38. Rxf6! { Black simply blunders a piece... } { [%clk 0:01:04] } 38... Rf1+ { [%clk 0:11:43] } (38... Kxf6 39. Bd4+ $18 { [%cal Gd4a1,Gd4f6] }) 39. Ke2! $18 { [%clk 0:01:31] } 39... Kxf6 { [%clk 0:10:50] } 40. Kxf1 { White is a piece up in this endgame, and the winning plan is as follows: the bishop keeps Black's a-pawn under control, the king is gradually improved, and at some point Black will be forced to retreat, fall into zugzwang, and lose the pawns. } { [%clk 0:01:57] } 40... Kf5 { [%clk 0:11:14] } 41. Ke2 { [%clk 0:01:32] } 41... Ke4 { [%clk 0:11:38] } 42. g3 { Defending the f4-pawn and freeing the bishop. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gg3f4] [%clk 0:01:40] } 42... a4 { [%clk 0:11:56] } 43. Bc5 { Controlling the a-pawn. } { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gc5a3] [%clk 0:00:51] } 43... h4 { [%clk 0:11:25] } 44. Be7 { [%clk 0:00:46] } 44... hxg3 { Black tries to exchange one pair of pawns, but White still has two, and this will be decisive. } { [%clk 0:11:31] } 45. hxg3 { [%clk 0:0