{ Annotated by IM / WGM Lilit Mkrtchian - https://lichess.org/@/Lilit-Mkrtchian

In Round 7, before the second rest day and the end of the first half of the tournament, two strong tacticians faced each other in a hard-fought battle, as expected.

The tournament leader, Anna Muzychuk, has White against Bibisara Assaubaeva, who comes into the game after two consecutive losses. The two met in the final of the last World Blitz Championship in Doha, where the young Kazakh player defeated Anna to claim the title and secure a place in the Candidates. Anna, in good form here, will certainly be looking for revenge. }
1. e4 { 1.e4 is definitely Anna's preferred opening move. } { [%clk 1:30:57] } 1... c5 { So far in this tournament, Bibisara has relied on the Sicilian, although 1...e5 is also a part of her repertoire. } { [%clk 1:30:56] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:21] } 2... Nc6 { Bibisara once again avoids her usual Najdorf and opts for 2...Nc6. This is the fourth time she has faced 1.e4 in this tournament, and she has chosen 2...Nc6 on every occasion. } { [%clk 1:31:22] } 3. Bb5 { The Rossolimo Variation, Anna's main weapon against 2...Nc6, is on the board. } { [%clk 1:31:41] } 3... Nf6 { In the third round, Bibisara faced the Rossolimo against Zhu and played 3...d6. In this game, however, she opts for a new approach. } { [%clk 1:31:45] } 4. Bxc6 { After some thought, Anna chooses one of the main lines. Other serious options include 4.Nc3 and 4.e5. } { [%clk 1:25:36] } (4. Nc3!?) (4. e5!?) 4... dxc6 { This is the main continuation. After another capture, } { [%clk 1:31:55] } (4... bxc6 5. e5 Nd5 6. O-O g6 7. c4 Nc7 8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 Bg7 10. Qh4 { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gc1h6] } 10... h6 11. Nc3 Ne6 12. Re1 { ...White enjoys better chances. }) 5. d3 { [%clk 1:26:01] } 5... Bg4 { Again the main continuation. Another option is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and castle, postponing the development of the light-squared bishop. } { [%clk 1:32:20] } (5... g6 { [%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] }) 6. h3 { Immediately posing the question of what to do with the bishop. } { [%clk 1:16:33] } 6... Bh5 { Bibisara plays quickly, still following her preparation. In case of, } { [%clk 1:31:49] } (6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. a4!? O-O 10. Be3 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ge3c5] } 10... Nd7 11. Nd2!? { ... White has the better chances. }) 7. g4 { It seems that sooner or later this move will have to be played to get rid of the pin. } { [%clk 1:10:41] } (7. Nbd2 Nd7!? { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e5] } 8. g4) 7... Bg6 { [%clk 1:32:14] } 8. Bf4 { This move allows Black to play ...c4, undoubling the pawns. 8.b3 would have prevented it and developed the bishop to b2. } { [%clk 1:11:06] } (8. b3!? { [%csl Gc4] } 8... Nd7! { A typical idea in such positions: Black aims to play ...e5. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 9. Bb2 h5!? 10. g5 e5 { [%cal Gd8g5] } 11. Nbd2 h4!? { ...leading to a complex position. Nevertheless, White has the better chances in this complex position. }) 8... c4! { Undoubling the c-pawns. } { [%clk 1:29:55] } 9. Nc3 { [%clk 1:09:35] } 9... cxd3! { [%clk 1:26:55] } 10. Qxd3 { 10.cxd5 is also playable, keeping the queens on the board. Most likely, Anna aims to simplify and reach an endgame against her young opponent, who excels in dynamic positions. } { [%clk 1:06:49] } (10. cxd3!?) 10... Qxd3 { [%clk 1:23:51] } 11. cxd3 { [%clk 1:03:59] } 11... Nd7! { A correct idea, preparing ...f6 and ...e5. } { [%cal Gf7f6,Ge7e5] [%clk 1:22:53] } 12. Nh4 { The game can become more complex after 12.h4. } { [%cal Gh4g6,Gh4f5] [%clk 0:51:11] } (12. h4!? { [%cal Gh4h5] } 12... f6 13. h5 Bf7 { [%cal Ge7e5] } 14. e5!? g5!? $13 { Anna chooses a simpler approach. }) 12... e5 { [%clk 1:20:44] } 13. Be3 { The bishop is better placed on this diagonal. } { [%cal Ge3a7] [%clk 0:51:37] } 13... Be7 { Bibisara immediately forces the knight on h4 to decide. Another option is 13...0-0-0. } { [%clk 1:09:23] } (13... O-O-O 14. Ke2 f6 { [%cal Gg6f7] } 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. h4 $10) 14. Nf5! { After 14.Nxg6, } { [%csl Gg7,Ge7][%cal Gf5g7,Gf5e7] [%clk 0:48:34] } (14. Nxg6 hxg6 { ... the pawn on h3 may become a target for Black's rooks. } { [%csl Gh3][%cal Gh8h3] }) 14... Bxf5 { [%clk 1:06:50] } 15. exf5! { Securing a good square for the knight. } { [%csl Ge4] [%clk 0:48:58] } 15... O-O-O { [%clk 1:00:21] } 16. Ne4 { [%clk 0:41:22] } (16. Bxa7?? b6! { [%csl Ba7] }) 16... Kb8 { [%csl Ga7][%cal Gb8a7] [%clk 0:57:43] } (16... h6!? { [%csl Gg5] } 17. Ke2 Nb6 18. h4 Nd5 { is also perfectly playable. }) 17. Ke2 { The king is best placed on this square. } { [%cal Ge2d3] [%clk 0:38:58] } 17... Nf6 { Black aims to exchange White's strong knight. } { [%cal Gf6e4] [%clk 0:54:28] } 18. Nxf6 { Anna continues with further simplifications. She could put some pressure on Black's position with 18.g5, gaining space on the kingside. } { [%clk 0:30:11] } (18. g5!? { In this case, 18...Nxe4 would have been a mistake. } 18... Nxe4? (18... Nd5 19. h4 $14) 19. dxe4 Rd7 20. Rad1 Rhd8 21. Rxd7 Rxd7 22. h4 $16 { White's advanced kingside pawns are very dangerous. } { [%cal Gh4h5] }) 18... Bxf6 { [%clk 0:53:47] } 19. Rac1 { The position is equal. Both sides can slightly improve their pieces, but there is not much to play for. } { [%clk 0:28:21] } 19... Rd5 { [%clk 0:52:57] } 20. b3 { [%clk 0:27:15] } 20... Rhd8 { Black attacks White's d3-pawn, but it is easily defended. } { [%clk 0:52:14] } 21. Rhd1 { [%csl Gd3] [%clk 0:27:40] } 21... h6 { [%clk 0:51:36] } 22. Rc4 { [%clk 0:27:23] } 22... R8d7 { [%clk 0:50:04] } 23. Rd2 { [%clk 0:27:26] } 23... Rd8 { [%clk 0:48:33] } 24. Rd1 { [%clk 0:27:50] } 24... R8d7 { [%clk 0:48:59] } 25. Rd2 { [%clk 0:28:14] } 25... Rd8 { [%clk 0:49:25] } 26. Rd1 { [%clk 0:28:40] } 26... R8d7 { 1/2-1/2 wins.
