I expected to see a big fight in this game, given the result of the first round. Since Anish is a well-known "white-colour player" and Pragg is ready to offer a tough game with any pieces, this had to be a curious spectacle. }
1. d4 { [%clk 1:59:58] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:19] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:52] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:59:14] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:49] } 3... d5 { [%clk 1:59:05] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:45] } 4... dxc4 { [%clk 1:58:32] } 5. e4 { [%clk 1:59:37] } 5... b5!? { Expectable. This line is very popular now, and Black's results are often impressive. } { [%clk 1:58:26] } (5... Bb4 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O { There is a lot of theory in this line. }) 6. e5 { [%clk 1:59:10] } 6... Nd5 { [%clk 1:58:06] } 7. Nxb5 { [%clk 1:59:04] } 7... Nb6 { [%clk 1:58:02] } 8. Be2 { [%clk 1:58:46] } 8... Be7!? { A flexible move. Black wants to castle kingside and reserves the opportunity to place the knight on d7 rather than on c6, as usual. } { [%clk 1:57:45] } (8... Nc6 { The most popular move, but Pragg tries to get away from the mainstream as early as possible. } 9. O-O Be7 10. Be3 O-O) 9. O-O { [%clk 1:58:18] } 9... O-O { [%clk 1:57:20] } 10. a4! { Great move! Giri highlights the absence of a knight on c6. } { [%clk 1:54:40] } 10... Ba6 { [%clk 1:40:05] } 11. Na3 { [%clk 1:51:45] } 11... c5?! { An inaccuracy. White made the strongest moves, and at that moment it was necessary to remember the development of the pieces. } { [%clk 1:35:26] } (11... Nc6! 12. a5 Nd5 13. Bxc4 Bxc4 14. Nxc4 Ndb4 15. Be3 Rb8 $44 { Black has an excellent compensation. It is likely that the pawn on a5 will be taken back in the nearest future, and the position is equal. }) 12. a5 { [%clk 1:40:41] } 12... Nd5 { [%clk 1:33:52] } 13. Bxc4 { [%clk 1:23:01] } 13... Qxa5? { This natural move is a mistake, after which the Dutchman provides for a solid advantage. } { [%clk 1:20:05] } (13... Bxc4! { Black needed to complete the development on the queenside: } 14. Nxc4 Nc6! 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Qe2 Rb8 17. Bd2 h6 18. Rfd1 Qc7 $44 { Black still has a good compensation for the pawn. }) 14. Nc2! { [%clk 1:21:53] } 14... Qb6 { [%clk 1:19:15] } 15. Bxd5 { [%clk 1:11:33] } 15... exd5 { [%clk 1:19:01] } 16. Re1 { [%clk 1:10:36] } (16. dxc5!? { Maybe this move was stronger, but I also like the choice made in the game. } 16... Bxc5 17. b4! Be7 18. Re1 $16 { The threat of Ne3 is very unpleasant, as the knight can reach both d5 and f5. }) 16... Bb7 { [%clk 0:50:13] } 17. Bg5! { It's a very deep positional idea. White exchanges bishops and occupies the d4 square with a knight, restricting the b7 bishop. } { [%clk 1:07:39] } 17... Bxg5 { [%clk 0:42:20] } 18. Nxg5 { [%clk 1:07:14] } 18... h6 { [%clk 0:42:15] } 19. dxc5 { [%clk 0:53:15] } 19... Qxc5 { [%clk 0:42:07] } 20. Nf3 { [%clk 0:51:42] } 20... Nc6 { [%clk 0:41:35] } 21. Ncd4 { [%clk 0:50:00] } 21... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:40:48] } 22. Nxd4 $14 { The computer does not consider Black's position too dangerous, but from a human point of view it is very difficult to play. I'm not surprised that Pragg couldn't handle the defending challenge himself. White has a clear attacking plan: h3, Kh2, f4-f5 and so on, and Black must play very carefully. } { [%clk 0:49:54] } 22... Bc8 { [%clk 0:40:17] } 23. Qd2 { [%clk 0:40:40] } 23... Rb8 { [%clk 0:36:41] } 24. Rec1 { [%clk 0:33:13] } 24... Qb6 { [%clk 0:34:46] } 25. b3 { [%clk 0:30:11] } 25... Bd7 { [%clk 0:33:09] } 26. h3 { [%clk 0:29:02] } 26... Rfc8 { [%clk 0:30:17] } 27. Rd1 { [%clk 0:25:52] } 27... Rc5 { [%clk 0:29:11] } 28. Kh2 { [%clk 0:25:33] } 28... a5 { [%clk 0:26:57] } 29. f4 { White has made all the planned moves and now Black needs to design his defense. } { [%clk 0:25:22] } 29... f6? { A weird decision. Black weakens the king, but gets nothing in return. } { [%clk 0:22:49] } (29... Qc7 30. Re1 Rc3! 31. Rac1 (31. f5 f6!) 31... Rxc1 32. Rxc1 Qb6 $13 { After the trade of rooks, White's attack is not as effective, and Black has a good chance of equalizing. }) 30. Re1! { Of course, Giri does not miss the opportunity to double the rooks and make the e5 pawn even more dangerous. } { [%clk 0:22:29] } 30... Re8? { The rook on e8 occupies the square needed for the bishop. } { [%clk 0:14:38] } (30... Qb4! 31. Rad1 Qxd2 32. Rxd2 fxe5 33. fxe5 $36 { Of course, White's position is better, but Black's position is still defendable. }) 31. Re2?! { [%clk 0:19:31] } (31. Re3! { was much stronger. The rook on e3 is better placed, as it can go to g3 and white is able to impose threats to the black king. } 31... fxe5 32. fxe5 Qc7 33. Rae1 a4 34. bxa4 Bxa4 35. Rg3! { White has too many opportunities, Black has no defense. } 35... Rxe5 36. Ne6 $18) 31... fxe5 { [%clk 0:12:36] } 32. fxe5 { [%clk 0:19:26] } 32... Qc7 { [%clk 0:07:32] } 33. Rae1 { [%clk 0:18:41] } 33... a4 { [%clk 0:07:16] } 34. bxa4 { [%clk 0:17:58] } 34... Bxa4 { [%clk 0:07:06] } 35. Kh1 { [%clk 0:17:52] } 35... Qf7? { A crucial mistake, after which Black's position can no longer be saved. } { [%clk 0:05:08] } (35... Bb5! 36. Re3 Ba4!! { It's hard to believe, but Black's idea is to play Bc2. Black is ready to give up a pawn on d5 and to trade the White's active knight and get a counterplay. } 37. e6 Bc2! 38. e7 (38. Nxc2 Rxc2 39. Qxd5 Qc6) 38... Be4 39. Ne6 Qxe7 40. Nxc5 Qxc5 $14 { Black has a good chance for a draw. }) 36. e6 { [%clk 0:15:16] } 36... Qg6 { [%clk 0:05:01] } 37. Rf2 { [%clk 0:12:18] } 37... Rc4 { [%clk 0:03:19] } 38. Rf4! { [%clk 0:09:57] } 38... h5? { [%clk 0:01:38] } 39. Qf2! { e7 and Rf8 are threatening, and Black doesn't have a good defense. The rest of the game does not require any comments. } { [%clk 0:07:59] } 39... Bc2?! { [%clk 0:00:47] } (39... Rc7 40. Qf3 $18) 40. e7 { [%clk 0:35:05] } 40... Be4 { [%clk 0:30:33] } 41. Rf8+ { [%clk 0:25:17] } 41... Kh7 { [%clk 0:30:54] } 42. Rxe8 { [%clk 0:25:41] } 42... Qxe8 { [%clk 0:31:08] } 43. Rxe4 { [%clk 0:22:30] } 43... dxe4 { [%clk 0:28:28] } 44. Qf5+ { A great revenge from Giri for losing in the first round! } { [%clk 0:19:26] } 1-0


