Welcome to the second half of the tournament and I want to start my annotations with the most dramatic game of the 8th round! }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:56] } 1... c5 { [%clk 1:30:52] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:20] } 2... g6 { White is obviously heading towards the Maróczy Bind, an opening which is associated with a very specific pawn structure. } { [%clk 1:31:17] } 3. c4 { [%clk 1:28:34] } 3... Nc6 { [%clk 1:31:19] } 4. d4 { [%clk 1:28:48] } 4... cxd4 { [%clk 1:31:33] } 5. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:29:12] } 5... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:45] } 6. Nc3 { [%clk 1:29:29] } 6... d6 { As you see, in this pawn structure White usually has a stronger center which guarantees them a space advantage and better chances in the game. } { [%clk 1:31:08] } 7. Be2 { [%clk 1:25:18] } 7... Nxd4 { [%clk 1:31:10] } 8. Qxd4 { [%clk 1:25:42] } 8... Bg7 { [%clk 1:31:35] } 9. Be3 { [%clk 1:24:35] } 9... O-O { Now, Black is threatening to play Ng4 and exchange the dark-squared bishop. } { [%clk 1:30:30] } 10. Qd3 { [%clk 1:23:29] } 10... Ng4 { [%clk 1:09:19] } 11. Bxg4 { [%clk 1:23:17] } 11... Bxg4 { Black has managed to get a pair of bishops, but since White's central pawns are located on the light squares, White can easily afford it. } { [%clk 1:09:43] } 12. O-O { [%clk 1:22:48] } 12... Be6 { [%clk 1:04:04] } 13. Bd4 { The best way to fight against the bishop pair is simple, just exchange one of them! } { [%clk 1:17:58] } 13... Bxd4 { [%clk 0:53:15] } 14. Qxd4 { [%clk 1:18:01] } 14... Qc7 { The best counterplay Black can get is on the c-file. The typical plan includes doubling over the file and then trying to open it by pushing b7-b5. } { [%clk 0:53:42] } 15. b3 { [%clk 1:17:39] } 15... Qc5 { [%clk 0:53:39] } 16. Qd3 { Avoiding the exchange is the best, as Black lacks space and White may need her queen to start a kingside attack. } { [%clk 1:16:44] } 16... Rfc8 { [%clk 0:52:15] } 17. Rfe1 { [%clk 1:07:29] } 17... a6 { [%clk 0:49:33] } 18. a4 { It is a very important move as White had to stop b7-b5. } { [%clk 0:59:00] } 18... Rc7 { [%clk 0:48:26] } 19. Re3 { This is a smart rook lift, as White's plan may include starting the attack on the kingside or play Nc3-d5 and, after the exchange, taking on d5 with the e pawn, which will allow White to open the e-file, so both rooks should be ready for that! } { [%clk 0:53:51] } 19... Rac8 { [%clk 0:36:47] } 20. Rae1 { [%clk 0:50:21] } 20... Qe5 { [%clk 0:25:58] } 21. h3 { [%clk 0:45:01] } 21... b6 { [%clk 0:24:05] } 22. Nd5 { White goes for the typical idea. } { [%clk 0:39:21] } 22... Bxd5 { [%clk 0:22:51] } 23. exd5 { [%clk 0:39:44] } 23... Qf6 { [%clk 0:22:57] } 24. Rf3 { Starting from this moment, White will try to open up the kingside and create attacking chances. } { [%clk 0:33:18] } 24... Qg7 { [%clk 0:22:18] } 25. h4 { [%clk 0:26:10] } 25... f6? { [%clk 0:16:55] } (25... b5 26. cxb5 axb5 27. axb5 (27. Qxb5 Qd4 { comes with a tempo since the h4 pawn is under attack }) 27... Qb2 { All of a sudden, all black pieces are active! }) 26. Qd4 { [%clk 0:21:24] } 26... Rb8 { [%clk 0:16:38] } 27. Rfe3 { [%clk 0:19:17] } 27... Rbb7 { [%clk 0:15:56] } 28. Re6 { [%clk 0:18:16] } 28... Qh6 { [%clk 0:11:59] } 29. g3 { [%clk 0:12:48] } 29... Qf8 { [%clk 0:08:04] } 30. h5 { [%clk 0:11:27] } 30... g5 { [%clk 0:07:01] } (30... gxh5 31. Kg2 Qf7 32. R1e4 { Does not look so easy for Black as the h5 pawn will eventually fall. }) 31. Kg2 { [%clk 0:05:43] } 31... Qa8 { [%clk 0:05:12] } 32. Ra1 { [%clk 0:05:29] } (32. h6 { as Black does not have time to play b6-b5. } 32... b5 33. axb5 axb5 34. cxb5 Rxb5 35. Rxe7 Rxe7 36. Rxe7 Rxd5 37. Qe4 $18) 32... Qc8 { [%clk 0:05:03] } 33. Rae1 { [%clk 0:03:32] } 33... Qa8 { [%clk 0:05:24] } 34. f4 { Trying to weaken the Black king even more by opening the g-file. } { [%clk 0:02:27] } 34... gxf4 { [%clk 0:05:36] } 35. Qxf4 { [%clk 0:02:46] } 35... b5 { Finally, Black decided to play it, but now it is too late as White's attack is too strong. } { [%clk 0:04:08] } 36. h6 { [%clk 0:01:48] } 36... Qf8 { [%clk 0:04:14] } 37. cxb5 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 37... axb5 { [%clk 0:04:44] } 38. a5 { Creating a strong passer. } { [%clk 0:01:03] } 38... Rc5 { [%clk 0:03:49] } 39. Qg4+ { [%clk 0:00:42] } 39... Kh8 { [%clk 0:04:16] } 40. b4? { [%clk 0:00:40] } (40. Qg7+! Qxg7 41. hxg7+ Kxg7 42. a6 Rb8 43. Rxe7+ Kg6 44. a7 Ra8 45. Rb7 $18 { allows White to enter into a winning endgame due to a strong passed pawn and very active rooks. }) 40... Rc4 { [%clk 0:00:36] } 41. R6e4 { [%clk 0:17:56] } (41. Qh5 { with a threat of Rxf6! }) 41... Rxe4 { [%clk 0:09:08] } 42. Rxe4 { [%clk 0:15:39] } 42... Rc7 { [%clk 0:08:46] } 43. Qe2 { I guess White has missed an important idea for Black in her calculations. } { [%clk 0:12:15] } 43... Qxh6 { [%clk 0:04:14] } 44. Qxb5 { [%clk 0:03:34] } 44... Rc2+ { [%clk 0:03:56] } 45. Re2 { [%clk 0:03:58] } 45... Qg6! { I think Anna has missed this move! Queen is coming back to the game and already threatening Qe4 which looks very unpleasant for White. } { [%clk 0:04:23] } 46. Rxc2 { [%clk 0:03:39] } 46... Qxc2+ { [%clk 0:04:52] } 47. Kf3 { [%clk 0:03:54] } 47... Qd1+ { [%clk 0:03:23] } 48. Kf2 { [%clk 0:02:26] } 48... Qd2+ { [%clk 0:03:37] } 49. Kf3 { [%clk 0:01:34] } 49... Qd1+ { [%clk 0:04:06] } 50. Kf2 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 50... Qd2+ { [%clk 0:04:30] } 51. Qe2 { Avoiding the repetition at any cost is probably the start of a wrong approach. I guess White is overestimating her chances. Although it is quite understandable, after having such a big advantage it is very difficult to accept the equality! } { [%clk 0:00:55] } 51... Qxb4 { [%clk 0:04:06] } 52. a6 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 52... Qb6+ { [%clk 0:03:09] } 53. Kg2 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 53... Qa7 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 54. Qb5 { [%clk 0:01:16] } 54... Kg7 { [%clk 0:01:54] } 55. Qa4 { [%clk 0:00:51] } (55. Qb7 Qe3 { Black can activate her queen and go for perpetual. }) 55... h5 { [%clk 0:01:36] } 56. Qa2 { [%clk 0:00:57] } 56... Kf7 { [%clk 0:01:51] } 57. Qe2 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 57... Kf8 { [%clk 0:01:26] } 58. Kh3 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 58... Qg1 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 59. a7 { [%clk 0:00:48] } (59. Qxh5 Qf1+ 60. Kh2 Qxa6 61. Qh8+ Kf7 62. Qh7+ Ke8 63. Qg8+ Kd7 64. Qe6+ Kd8 65. Qg8+ Kc7 66. Qe6 { Although Black has an extra pawn she cannot avoid perpetual as the e7 pawn can be defended only by the king. }) 59... Qxa7 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 60. Qxh5 { [%clk 0:01:17] } 60... Qe3 { Queen comes in time, so White has no chances for perpetual anymore. } { [%clk 0:00:54] } 61. Qh8+ { [%clk 0:00:57] } 61... Kf7 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 62. Qh5+? { [%clk 0:01:13] } (62. Qh7+ Ke8 63. Qg8+ Kd7 64. Qa8 { and now White has much better chances for perpetual on the queenside. }) 62... Kg7 { [%clk 0:01:42] } 63. Qe8 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 63... Qe4 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 64. Kh2 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 64... Qe2+ { [%clk 0:00:58] } 65. Kg1 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 65... Qe1+ { [%clk 0:01:11] } 66. Kg2 { [%clk 0:01:19] } 66... Qd2+ { [%clk 0:01:40] } 67. Kh3 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 67... Qe2 { [%clk 0:02:08] } 68. g4 { [%clk 0:01:33] } 68... Qf3+ { [%clk 0:02:06] } 69. Kh2 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 69... Qe4 { [%clk 0:01:31] } 70. Kg3 { [%clk 0:01:56] } 70... Qe5+ { [%clk 0:01:39] } 71. Kh3 { [%clk 0:02:05] } 71... f5 { [%clk 0:01:51] } 72. gxf5 { [%clk 0:01:43] } 72... Qxf5+ { [%clk 0:02:13] } 73. Kg3 { [%clk 0:01:56] } 73... Qg5+ { [%clk 0:02:17] } (73... Qg6+ 74. Qxg6+ Kxg6 75. Kg4 Kf6 76. Kf4 { looks like a draw as White holds the opposition and does not allow Black to activate her king. }) 74. Kf2 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 74... Kf6 { King is coming towards the d5 pawn. } { [%clk 0:01:28] } 75. Qh8+ { [%clk 0:01:05] } 75... Kf5 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 76. Qc8+ { [%clk 0:01:11] } 76... Kf6 { [%clk 0:01:00] } (76... Ke5 77. Qc3+ Kxd5 78. Qa5+ $18 { White still has some tricks. }) 77. Qh8+ { [%clk 0:01:36] } 77... Kg6 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 78. Qg8+ { [%clk 0:01:36] } 78... Kh6 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 79. Qh8+ { [%clk 0:01:42] } 79... Kg6 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 80. Qg8+ { [%clk 0:02:07] } 80... Kh5 { [%clk 0:01:38] } 81. Qf7+ { [%clk 0:01:01] } 81... Kh4 { [%clk 0:02:05] } 82. Qh7+ { [%clk 0:00:48] } 82... Kg4 { [%clk 0:02:33] } 83. Kf1 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 83... Qf5+ { Exchanging the queens in the correct situation sends the game into a completely winning pawn endgame for Black. This game has cost Anna her sole lead and allowed Divya to join the group of the leaders in the tournament. } { [%clk 0:02:58] } 0-1


