... f4 { Black is trying to create some counterplay on the kingside, but is it sufficient? } { [%clk 0:33:31] } 25. Kg2 { [%clk 0:30:25] } 25... Qf6 { [%clk 0:27:47] } 26. Bc1 { Very good move as White threatens to take the pawn on f4, rook on e8, and eventually the knight on b6. } { [%clk 0:26:16] } 26... Rf8 { Threatening fxg3, but White has a simple defence. } { [%clk 0:21:01] } 27. Rf1 { [%clk 0:17:29] } 27... d5 { Very good try for counter chances! } { [%clk 0:18:45] } 28. cxd5 { It is better to keep the light-squared bishop on the board. } { [%clk 0:14:44] } (28. Bxd5+? Nxd5 29. cxd5 Qf5 $13 { giving some headache to White }) 28... Ra8 { [%clk 0:13:36] } 29. Qb7 { [%clk 0:15:10] } 29... Rxa2 { [%clk 0:13:51] } 30. Rd2 { [%clk 0:14:54] } (30. d6 fxg3 31. hxg3 Bxd6 32. Bh6 Rf7 33. Qc6 $18 { Going for attack is the best defence! }) 30... Raa8 { [%clk 0:05:23] } 31. d6 { [%clk 0:13:45] } 31... Rab8 { [%clk 0:04:55] } 32. Qe7 { By exchanging the queens, White tries to avoid any kind of complications. } { [%clk 0:12:46] } 32... Rbd8 { [%clk 0:04:45] } 33. Re2 { [%clk 0:09:07] } 33... Bxd6 { [%clk 0:03:51] } 34. Qxf6 { [%clk 0:04:12] } 34... Rxf6 { [%clk 0:04:20] } 35. Rd1 $18 { Although there is a material equality on the board, it is still lost for Black, as White has a tremendous initiative due to the bishop pair. } { [%clk 0:04:27] } 35... Rff8 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 36. Re6 { [%clk 0:04:12] } 36... Nc8 { [%clk 0:01:46] } 37. Bb2 { [%clk 0:04:32] } 37... Rf7 { [%clk 0:00:52] } 38. Bd5 { [%clk 0:02:15] } 38... Kf8 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 39. Bc4 { [%clk 0:01:53] } 39... Bc7 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 40. Rxd8+ { [%clk 0:01:30] } 40... Bxd8 { [%clk 0:01:29] } 41. Re5 { [%clk 0:22:51] } 41... Rc7 { [%clk 0:27:09] } 42. Re4 { [%clk 0:21:38] } 42... g5 { [%clk 0:25:54] } (42... fxg3 43. Rf4+ Ke8 44. Bb5+ Ke7 45. Bf6+ $18 { One more example where we can appreciate the strength of the bishop pair. }) 43. Be5 { [%clk 0:19:20] } 43... Re7 { [%clk 0:23:47] } 44. gxf4 { [%clk 0:13:18] } 44.