lk 0:40:16] } 19... Nxc4 { [%clk 1:14:46] } 20. Qxc4 { [%clk 0:40:10] } 20... Rfb8 { [%clk 1:08:34] } 21. Qd4? { [%clk 0:35:00] } (21. b3 { was necessary } 21... Ba6 22. Qd4 a4 23. Nxa4 Nxa4 24. bxa4 c5 { but Black has a strong attack. }) 21... Bc6! { [%clk 1:07:03] } 22. b3 { [%clk 0:31:22] } 22... a4 { [%clk 0:58:57] } 23. Nxa4 { [%clk 0:31:02] } 23... Nxa4 { [%clk 0:55:03] } 24. bxa4 { The critical moment. White's position is lost, but it's not any easy to find the right way. } { [%clk 0:30:59] } 24... Bxa4?? { It is really surprising that such a brilliant tactical player as Sindarov immediately went to trading queens. } { [%clk 0:54:52] } (24... Qb7! 25. Rhe1 Bxa4! 26. Bxa4 c5! { White loses because the queen is overloaded and cannot defend the a4 bishop and the b2 square simultaneously. } { [%csl Ra4,Rb2,Rc1][%cal Gb7b2,Ga8a4] }) 25. Qxb6 { [%clk 0:27:58] } 25... cxb6 { [%clk 0:54:20] } 26. Bb3! { Perhaps Javokhir missed this defensive idea? } { [%clk 0:26:18] } (26. Rd2 Rc8 27. Kb1 Rxc2 28. Rxc2 Bxc2+ 29. Kxc2 Rxa2+ $15 { and Black keeps chances to win. }) 26... Bxb3 { [%clk 0:54:11] } 27. axb3 { [%clk 0:26:16] } 27... Ra2 { [%clk 0:54:03] } 28. Kb1 { [%clk 0:26:13] } 28... Rba8 { [%clk 0:52:57] } 29. f5 { [%clk 0:23:11] } (29. Rd8+ Rxd8 30. Kxa2) 29... exf5 { [%clk 0:41:28] } 30. exf5 { [%clk 0:22:32] } 30... R2a5 { [%clk 0:41:24] } 31. Rhf1 { White finished the development of the pieces and completely equalized the position. Draw is coming. } { [%clk 0:21:35] } 31... g6 { [%clk 0:41:10] } 32. fxg6 { [%clk 0:20:41] } 32... hxg6 { [%clk 0:40:37] } 33. h4 { [%clk 0:20:35] } 33... Ra2 { [%clk 0:40:31] } 34. Rd8+ { [%clk 0:15:36] } 34... Rxd8 { [%clk 0:40:24] } 35. Kxa2 { [%clk 0:15:33] } 35... Rd4 { [%clk 0:40:19] } 36. Rh1 { [%clk 0:15:26] } 36... b5 { [%clk 0:40:14] } 37. Kb2 { [%clk 0:07:58] } 37... b4 { [%clk 0:39:31] } 38. Kc2 { [%clk 0:07:53] } 38... Kg7 { [%clk 0:38:59] } 39. Rh2 { [%clk 0:07:21] } 39... f5 { [%clk 0:37:38] } 40. gxf6+ { [%clk 0:34:07] } 