1. Nf3 { [%clk 1:30:38] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:30:18] } 2. b3 { This opening is known as the Nimzowitsch-Larsen or Nimzo-Larsen Attack after Larsen and the Latvian-Danish GM Aron Nimzowitsch. White is going for the fianchetto with Bb2 while delaying the fight for the center. } { [%clk 1:30:58] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 1:28:12] } 3. Bb2 { [%clk 1:31:21] } 3... e6 { [%clk 1:28:35] } 4. c4 { [%clk 1:31:36] } 4... Bd6 { [%clk 1:27:41] } 5. g3 { [%clk 1:31:37] } 5... O-O { [%clk 1:20:58] } 6. Bg2 { [%clk 1:32:02] } 6... c6 { This move looks a bit modest. Another option was to push: } { [%clk 1:21:10] } (6... c5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. d4 Nc6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 { Eventually leading to the position with an isolated pawn for Black. }) 7. O-O { [%clk 1:32:07] } 7... Nbd7 { [%clk 1:21:14] } 8. d4 { [%clk 1:32:22] } 8... a5 { Since Black can’t do much in the center, she goes for a flank pawn attack, hoping the advance will weaken White’s pawn chain on a2–b3–c4. } { [%clk 1:19:45] } 9. Nc3 { [%clk 1:31:54] } 9... Ne4 { [%clk 1:18:56] } 10. Nxe4 { Not allowing Black to reinforce the central knight by playing f5 or Ndf6. } { [%clk 1:19:14] } 10... dxe4 { [%clk 1:19:23] } 11. Ne5 { [%clk 1:19:04] } 11... f5 { [%clk 1:19:40] } (11... Bxe5? 12. dxe5 Nc5 13. Qc2 $18 { and White wins a very important central pawn. }) 12. f4 { [%clk 1:14:37] } 12... Nf6 { [%clk 0:53:44] } 13. e3 { The center has settled, so it’s time to finish developing the pieces. } { [%clk 1:10:39] } 13... Qe8 { [%clk 0:50:49] } (13... Bd7 { Was, probably, a better way to improve the pieces. }) 14. h3 { Getting ready for g3-g4, which will let White grab more space on the board. } { [%clk 1:04:55] } 14... b5? { [%clk 0:48:00] } (14... Nd7 15. g4 Nxe5 16. fxe5 Be7) 15. Rf2 { White is planning to improve the bishop by playing Bg2-f1. } { [%clk 0:58:28] } 15... Ba6 { [%clk 0:39:15] } 16. Rc1 { [%clk 0:54:20] } 16... bxc4 { If Black just waits, White has a nice plan to improve the position with Bf1, Rg2, g4, and Qe1. } { [%clk 0:34:36] } 17. bxc4 { [%clk 0:52:18] } 17... Nd7 { Black doesn’t want to stay passive, so she tries to create counterplay by sacrificing a pawn. } { [%clk 0:33:27] } 18. Nxc6 { [%clk 0:38:48] } 18... Rc8 { [%clk 0:13:39] } 19. d5 { [%clk 0:26:54] } 19... Nc5 { With an immediate threat of Nd3 which will allow Black to exchange the strong dark square bishop. } { [%clk 0:13:28] } 20. Qd4 { [%clk 0:24:46] } 20... Rf6 { [%clk 0:06:10] } 21. Rd2 { [%clk 0:21:36] } 21... Rg6? { This mistake gives White an even bigger advantage. Black should have stuck to her original plan of exchanging the bishop. } { [%clk 0:04:45] } (21... exd5 22. cxd5 Nd3 23. Qb6 Nxb2 24. Qxa6 Ra8 25. Qe2 Nd3 $16 { Even though White is still better in the final position, it’s far from a guaranteed win. }) 22. Kh2 { [%clk 0:20:58] } 22... Nd3? { This leads to a brilliant exchange sacrifice, giving White the chance to create two incredibly strong connected passed pawns in the center. It was better just to wait by playing 22...Rf6 or even 22...Kh8. } { [%clk 0:04:01] } 23. Rxd3! { [%clk 0:20:39] } 23... exd3 { [%clk 0:04:30] } 24. c5 { [%clk 0:20:39] } 24... Rxc6 { [%clk 0:01:54] } (24... Bf8 25. d6 Rxc6 26. d7 Qd8 27. Bxc6 $18) 25. dxc6 { [%clk 0:20:42] } 25... Bc7 { [%clk 0:02:24] } 26. Qd7! { [%clk 0:19:19] } 26... Qb8 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 27. Be5 { Excellent idea! White just needs to trade off the blocking bishop. } { [%clk 0:16:42] } 27... Bxe5 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 28. Rb1 { Winning an important tempo! } { [%clk 0:16:39] } 28... Qf8 { [%clk 0:00:36] } (28... Qxb1? 29. Qe8#) 29. fxe5 { [%clk 0:17:00] } 29... h5 { [%clk 0:00:43] } 30. Qd6 { With a threat of Rb8. } { [%clk 0:16:37] } 30... Qf7 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 31. Rb7! { This sacrifice lets White undouble the pawns, making them unstoppable. } { [%clk 0:13:28] } 1-0


