This game was also crucial for the tournament standings, as both players were among the leaders with 4.5 points. }
1. Nf3 { [%clk 1:30:54] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:30:48] } 2. e3 { [%clk 1:31:14] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:52] } 3. b3 { [%clk 1:31:36] } 3... c5 { [%clk 1:30:12] } 4. Bb2 { We’re seeing a Nimzo-Indian opening—but with the colors reversed. } { [%clk 1:31:18] } 4... e6 { [%clk 1:30:24] } 5. Be2 { [%clk 1:31:27] } 5... Nc6 { [%clk 1:30:31] } 6. O-O { [%clk 1:30:45] } 6... Bd6 { [%clk 1:29:50] } 7. d4 { [%clk 1:30:45] } 7... b6 { [%clk 1:25:21] } 8. c4 { [%clk 1:16:40] } 8... Bb7 { The position is almost symmetrical, and soon one player will have to decide the pawn structure, as the central tension can’t last much longer. } { [%clk 1:23:11] } 9. cxd5 { [%clk 1:13:24] } 9... exd5 { [%clk 1:23:31] } 10. Nc3 { [%clk 1:12:41] } 10... O-O { [%clk 1:22:43] } 11. Rc1 { As a result of the opening, the pawn structure could end up giving Black either isolated (if Black takes the d4 pawn) or hanging pawns. } { [%clk 1:12:34] } 11... Re8 { The main issue with hanging pawns is that they can be hard to defend. Black can’t allow the dark-squared bishop to be exchanged, as it would weaken the c5 pawn. On the other hand, Nf6 is crucial because it protects the d5 pawn. This move, however, gives White the chance to secure a very favorable exchange. } { [%clk 1:17:16] } 12. Nb5 { [%clk 1:09:26] } 12... Bf8 { [%clk 1:11:03] } 13. dxc5 { [%clk 1:08:31] } 13... bxc5 { [%clk 1:11:24] } 14. Bxf6 { [%clk 1:08:49] } 14... gxf6 { Black cannot take back with the queen as she will lose an exchange. } { [%clk 1:11:30] } (14... Qxf6 15. Nc7! $16) 15. Bd3 { [%clk 1:04:58] } 15... Ne5?! { This is probably not the best move; it would have been better to sacrifice a pawn to centralize the pieces. } { [%clk 0:39:04] } (15... f5 16. Bxf5 Qf6 17. Bb1 Rad8) 16. Re1 { [%clk 0:51:17] } 16... Qd7 { [%clk 0:34:08] } 17. Nc3 { [%clk 0:48:12] } 17... Qg4 { [%clk 0:22:31] } 18. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:29:07] } 18... Qxd1 { [%clk 0:22:56] } 19. Rexd1 { [%clk 0:29:32] } 19... fxe5 { [%clk 0:21:00] } 20. e4 { White is aiming to dominate the light squares. } { [%clk 0:29:51] } 20... dxe4?! { This looks like a big inaccuracy, as White manages to reach a very favorable endgame with a good knight against a bad bishop. } { [%clk 0:18:17] } (20... d4 21. Nb5 Red8 22. Na3 a5 23. Nc4 f6) 21. Bxe4 { [%clk 0:28:57] } 21... Bxe4 { [%clk 0:18:30] } 22. Nxe4 { [%clk 0:29:22] } 22... Red8 { [%clk 0:18:55] } 23. Kf1 { [%clk 0:12:19] } 23... Rxd1+ { [%clk 0:15:26] } 24. Rxd1 $16 { Black’s position is already tough, with weak pawns on c5, e5 and a7, White having the control of the d-file and the central knight being more active than Black’s bishop. } { [%clk 0:12:44] } 24... a5 { [%clk 0:15:54] } 25. Rd5 { Leads to a material gain for White. } { [%clk 0:07:58] } 25... a4 { [%clk 0:16:05] } 26. Rxe5 { [%clk 0:08:10] } 26... axb3 { [%clk 0:15:58] } 27. axb3 { [%clk 0:08:36] } 27... Rb8 { [%clk 0:11:15] } 28. Rg5+ { [%clk 0:08:42] } 28... Kh8 { [%clk 0:11:35] } 29. Rg3 { [%clk 0:09:07] } 29... h6 { [%clk 0:10:12] } 30. Ke2 { White has managed to win a pawn, and Black is completely stuck on defense, with all the pawns separated. } { [%clk 0:08:32] } 30... Rb4 { [%clk 0:09:34] } 31. Nd2 { [%clk 0:08:21] } 31... Bd6 { [%clk 0:09:11] } 32. Rd3 { [%clk 0:05:32] } 32... Be5 { [%clk 0:09:03] } 33. Nc4 { [%clk 0:05:32] } 33... Bg7? { [%clk 0:05:35] } (33... Bd4 34. Rf3 f6 $16) 34. Nd6 { [%clk 0:05:07] } 34... Kg8 { [%clk 0:05:34] } 35. Rg3 { With a deadly threat Nf5. } { [%clk 0:04:05] } 35... Kh7 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 36. Nxf7 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 36... Rb6 { [%clk 0:03:28] } 37. f4 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 37... Re6+ { [%clk 0:01:51] } 38. Re3 { [%clk 0:01:10] } 38... Rf6 { [%clk 0:02:15] } 39. Nd8 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 39... Rxf4 { [%clk 0:02:11] } 40. Re7 { Black has managed to win back a pawn but has fallen into a deadly pin. After Ne6, exchanging pieces would lead to a completely lost pawn endgame. } { [%clk 0:01:30] } 40... Rb4 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 41. Ne6 { [%clk 0:27:35] } 41... Kg6 { [%clk 0:29:40] } 42. Nxg7 { [%clk 0:27:36] }