Even though this game looked pretty calm and not very action-packed, I think it was really important psychologically for both players. The Indian GM came in with a half-point lead as a co-leader of the tournament, while the Ukrainian GM was right behind and putting on the pressure. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:57] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:30:36] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:21] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:31:01] } 3. Bc4 { White goes for the Italian game. } { [%clk 1:31:44] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:23] } 4. d3 { [%clk 1:32:07] } 4... h6 { [%clk 1:31:42] } 5. O-O { [%clk 1:32:21] } 5... d6 { [%clk 1:31:47] } 6. Re1 { [%clk 1:32:20] } 6... g6 { Both options for developing the bishop are playable, but nowadays many players go for the fianchetto. } { [%clk 1:25:26] } 7. d4 { [%clk 1:32:27] } (7. c3 Bg7 8. d4 O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. Qb3) 7... Bg4 { Since White hasn’t played h3 yet, Bg4 is usually a good move, pinning the knight and putting pressure on the d4 pawn. } { [%clk 1:19:31] } 8. dxe5 { [%clk 1:32:42] } 8... Nxe5 { [%clk 1:08:59] } 9. Be2 { [%clk 1:33:03] } 9... Qd7 { [%clk 1:03:03] } 10. Nc3 { [%clk 1:30:59] } 10... Bg7 { [%clk 0:58:07] } 11. Be3 { [%clk 1:24:28] } 11... Bxf3! { The right time to relieve some tension. } { [%clk 0:47:58] } (11... O-O? 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Nd5 Bxe2 (13... Be6 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxd7 Bxd7 16. Bxh6 $16) 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxd7 $18) 12. Bxf3 { [%clk 1:24:56] } 12... Nxf3+ { [%clk 0:47:02] } 13. Qxf3 { [%clk 1:25:23] } 13... Ng4 { Black is looking to improve the knight’s position. } { [%clk 0:47:21] } 14. Bd2 { [%clk 1:18:08] } 14... O-O { [%clk 0:45:17] } 15. h3 { [%clk 1:13:19] } 15... Ne5 { [%clk 0:45:36] } 16. Qe2 { [%clk 1:13:29] } 16... Nc6 { The players come out of the opening with an equal position. } { [%clk 0:42:32] } 17. Nd5 { [%clk 1:07:32] } 17... f5?! { This feels a bit premature and gives White a chance to seize an advantage. It was probably better to play 17...Ne7 and try to exchange the central knight. } { [%clk 0:36:20] } 18. Qc4 { [%clk 1:00:15] } 18... Kh7 { [%clk 0:36:36] } 19. c3?! { [%clk 0:59:55] } (19. f4 Rae8 20. exf5 Qxf5 (20... Rxf5 21. g4 Rff8 22. Bc3 $16 { Suddenly, Black’s king doesn’t look so safe, and Black would have needed to be very careful. }) 21. Nxc7 $14 { Even though the engine shows a slight advantage for White, I feel this position is a lot more difficult for Black to handle. }) 19... Rae8 { [%clk 0:30:44] } 20. f4 { Same plan here, but it’s slower, as Black has already placed the rook on the open file. } { [%clk 0:55:56] } 20... fxe4 { [%clk 0:27:29] } 21. Rxe4 { [%clk 0:56:18] } 21... b5 { By pushing the pawn with a tempo, Black gains extra space on the side where she has a pawn majority. } { [%clk 0:26:47] } 22. Qe2 { [%clk 0:49:53] } 22... Rxe4 { [%clk 0:27:04] } 23. Qxe4 { [%clk 0:50:20] } 23... Re8 { [%clk 0:27:16] } 24. Qd3 { [%clk 0:48:41] } 24... Ne7 { This defends the b5 pawn in the best way, since the knight on d5 is better than the one on c6. } { [%clk 0:26:28] } 25. Nxe7 { [%clk 0:39:58] } 25... Rxe7 { [%clk 0:26:52] } 26. Re1 { [%clk 0:40:02] } 26... Rxe1+ { [%clk 0:25:52] } 27. Bxe1 { [%clk 0:40:31] } 27... a6 { It’s an equal-looking endgame, and both players go for further exchanges. } { [%clk 0:17:42] } 28. b3 { [%clk 0:37:59] } 28... Qf5 { [%clk 0:15:29] } 29. Qxf5 { [%clk 0:38:09] } 29... gxf5 { [%clk 0:15:56] } 30. c4 { [%clk 0:36:01] } 30... bxc4 { [%clk 0:15:36] } 31. bxc4 { [%clk 0:36:30] } 31... h5 { [%clk 0:15:44] } 32. Kf2 { [%clk 0:36:31] } 32... Kg6 { [%clk 0:16:06] } 33. Kf3 { [%clk 0:36:33] } 33... Bd4 { [%clk 0:14:38] } 34. g4 { [%clk 0:35:54] } 34... hxg4+ { [%clk 0:15:03] } 35. hxg4 { [%clk 0:36:20] } 35... fxg4+ { [%clk 0:15:26] } 36. Kxg4 { [%clk 0:36:46] } 36... c6 { [%clk 0:15:39] } 37. f5+ { [%clk 0:36:31] } 37... Kf7 { [%clk 0:16:02] } 38. Kf4 { [%clk 0:36:15] } 38... d5 { [%clk 0:16:16] } 39. cxd5 { [%clk 0:36:41] } 39... cxd5 { [%clk 0:16:43] } 40. Ba5 { [%clk 0:36:41] } 40... Kf6 { [%clk 0:16:52] } 41. Bd8+ { [%clk 0:36:31] } 41... Kf7 { [%clk 0:17:16] } 42. Bc7 { [%clk 0:36:34] } 42... Kf6 { A draw might not be ideal for both players, because it allowed the Indian Grandmaster to move into sole first place, while the Ukrainian Grandmaster remained third. } { [%clk 0:17:41] } 1/2-1/2


