{ Annotated by IM / WGM Ekaterina Atalik: https://lichess.org/@/EkaterinaAtalik

What a dramatic game! The Chinese Grandmaster came in sharing the lead, but probably overestimated her chances. She could have gone for a threefold repetition, and a few miscalculations cost her a very important point. }
1. d4 { [%clk 1:30:56] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:53] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:31:21] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:31:18] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:46] } 3... d5 { [%clk 1:31:40] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 1:32:10] } 4... c6 { [%clk 1:31:53] } 5. Bg5 { This move in the Semi-Slav opening leads to sharp, tactical positions, where Black can choose to play the Botvinnik variation 5...dxc4 or the Moscow or Anti-Moscow. } { [%clk 1:32:33] } 5... h6 { [%clk 1:32:11] } 6. Bxf6 { 6.Bh4 would have led to an Anti-Moscow Gambit. } { [%clk 1:32:57] } 6... Qxf6 { [%clk 1:32:37] } 7. a3 { [%clk 1:31:26] } (7. e3 { It’s a more popular line, although the move chosen in the game has also been played by many top grandmasters. }) 7... dxc4 { [%clk 1:30:24] } 8. e3 { [%clk 1:31:14] } 8... g6?! { [%clk 1:15:57] } (8... b5 9. Ne5 Bd6 10. f4 $13 { leads to a different type of positions where Black has an extra pawn, but the position is balanced thanks to White’s excellent central knight and Black’s undeveloped queenside. }) 9. Bxc4 { [%clk 1:29:59] } 9... Bg7 { [%clk 1:16:21] } 10. O-O { [%clk 1:25:53] } 10... O-O { [%clk 1:16:43] } 11. Ne5!? { [%clk 1:23:35] } (11. e4) 11... c5! { A perfect moment to put pressure in the center and clear the c6 square for the knight. } { [%clk 1:16:07] } 12. Ne4 { [%clk 1:15:09] } 12... Qe7 { [%clk 1:15:55] } 13. Qf3 { [%clk 1:11:56] } 13... cxd4 { [%clk 1:09:30] } 14. exd4 { [%clk 1:12:20] } 14... Nc6 { Black is starting to solve the problems with the queenside pieces. } { [%clk 1:07:57] } 15. Nxc6 { [%clk 1:11:01] } 15... bxc6 { [%clk 1:08:21] } 16. Rad1 { Once again, the position is balanced. Both the d4 and c6 pawns are weak, so both players have roughly equal chances. } { [%clk 1:09:58] } 16... Rd8 { [%clk 1:07:40] } 17. Qe3 { [%clk 1:09:54] } 17... a5 { This move prepares to put the bishop on the best possible spot. } { [%clk 1:07:47] } 18. Nc5 { [%clk 0:59:56] } 18... Qd6 { [%clk 1:06:51] } 19. Ne4 { [%clk 0:59:25] } 19... Qe7 { [%clk 1:07:12] } 20. Nc5 { [%clk 0:55:09] } 20... Qd6 { [%clk 1:07:35] } 21. Ne4 { [%clk 0:51:29] } 21... Qb8 { What a pricey decision! } { [%clk 0:59:24] } (21... Qe7 { It would have led to a threefold repetition and wouldn’t have affected the current tournament standings. }) 22. Rd2?! { [%clk 0:51:32] } (22. b3 { Was better, to play } 22... Ba6 23. Nc5 Bxc4 24. bxc4 { And later White can use the rook on the b-file. }) 22... Ba6 { [%clk 0:59:25] } 23. Rc1 { [%clk 0:51:00] } 23... Bxc4 { [%clk 0:56:59] } 24. Rxc4 { [%clk 0:51:28] } 24... Ra6 { [%clk 0:53:53] } 25. g3 { [%clk 0:48:20] } 25... Rb6 { [%clk 0:51:42] } 26. Qc3 { [%clk 0:43:10] } 26... Rd5 { The balance remains: if White tries to take the c6 pawn, Black can recapture the d4 pawn. } { [%clk 0:48:59] } 27. Nc5 { [%clk 0:30:30] } (27. Rxc6 Rxc6 28. Qxc6 Rxd4) 27... h5 { [%clk 0:38:43] } 28. h4 { [%clk 0:27:15] } (28. Qxa5? Rxb2 $15 { giving Black better chances. }) 28... e5 { A good moment to open up the bishop. } { [%clk 0:30:12] } 29. Qxa5 { [%clk 0:23:02] } 29... exd4 { [%clk 0:18:03] } 30. b4 { This is probably the start of a sequence of mistakes, as Black won’t achieve much on the next moves, while White will significantly improve her position. } { [%clk 0:20:00] } 30... Rb5 { [%clk 0:11:58] } (30... g5 31. hxg5 h4 32. gxh4 Qf4 $13) 31. Qa4 { [%clk 0:19:47] } 31... Qe8 { [%clk 0:12:03] } 32. Qd1! { The queen has returned to the game, and the a-file is ready for the passed pawn. } { [%clk 0:19:38] } 32... Re5 { [%clk 0:11:56] } 33. Kg2 { [%clk 0:15:58] } 33... Re1 { [%clk 0:08:14] } 34. Qf3 { [%clk 0:16:16] } 34... Rb8 { [%clk 0:08:23] } 35. a4 { [%clk 0:12:55] } 35... Rd8 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 36. a5 { [%clk 0:09:30] } 36... Rd5 { [%clk 0:03:14] } 37. Nd3 { [%clk 0:09:04] } 37... Ra1 { [%clk 0:03:32] } 38. Re2 { We can see big improvements for White: the queen is on a much stronger square, the knight is blocking Black’s passed pawn, White has taken control of the open e-file, and on top of that, the a-pawn has started to march. } { [%clk 0:07:33] } 38... Qd7 { [%clk 0:03:51] } 39. Rec2 { [%clk 0:05:29] } 39... Ra3 { Black does not have a good defence anymore. } { [%clk 0:01:47] } (39... Rd6 40. Rxc6 $18) 40. Rxc6 { [%clk 0:04:06] } 40... Rc3 { [%clk 0:02:09] } 41. R6xc3 { [%clk 0:02:44] } 41... dxc3 { [%clk 0:02:32] } 42. Nc5 { As we know, two connected passed pawns are stronger than a single pawn, so White’s next task is simple: push them forward. } { [%clk 0:02:20] } 42... Qd8 { [%clk 0:27:15] } 43. a6 { [%clk 0:29:42] } 43... Rd1 { [%clk 0:27:33] } 44. Nb3!? { [%clk 0:15:58] } (44. b5 Ra1 45. Ne4 Bd4 46. Nxc3 $18 { White wins 1 more pawn and leaves no chances to her opponent. }) 44... Rd3 { [%clk 0:24:34] } 45. Qe4 { [%clk 0:15:58] } 45... f5 { [%clk 0:24:43] } 46. Qb7 { [%clk 0:11:36] } 46... Rd7 { [%clk 0:25:01] } 47. Qc6 { [%clk 0:12:00] } 47... Rd6 { [%clk 0:25:19] } 48. Qc4+ { [%clk 0:11:45] } 48... Kh7 { [%clk 0:25:41] } 49. b5 { [%clk 0:11:48] } 49... Qa8+ { With the pawns marching, Black’s only chance is to create counterplay on the kingside. } { [%clk 0:25:13] } 50. Kh2 { [%clk 0:10:11] } 50... Rd1 { Theatening chackmate in 1! } { [%clk 0:24:44] } 51. Qc6 { [%clk 0:10:20] } 51... Qa7 { [%clk 0:21:31] } 52. Ra2 { Letting some of the advantage slip away. } { [%clk 0:08:35] } (52. Qb7 Qxb7 53. axb7 Rd8 54. Na5 Rb8 55. f4 Bf6 56. Kg2 Kg7 57. Kf3 Kf7 58. Ke2 Ke6 59. Kd3 Kd7 60. Kc4 Kc7 61. Re2 Rf8 62. Re6 c2 63. Rc6+ Kd7 64. Kd3 $18) 52... f4 { [%clk 0:18:08] } 53. b6 { [%clk 0:08:25] } 53... Qe7 { [%clk 0:10:42] } 54. a7 { [%clk 0:08:16] } 54... fxg3+ { [%clk 0:10:48] } 55. fxg3 { [%clk 0:08:40] } 55... Be5 { [%clk 0:09:54] } 56. Kg2!! { Avoiding the last trick! } { [%clk 0:06:59] } (56. a8=Q?? Qxh4+ 57. Kg2 Qh1+ 58. Kf2 Qf1+ 59. Ke3 Re1+ 60. Re2 Qxe2#) 56... Rd3 { [%clk 0:09:45] } 57. a8=Q { [%clk 0:07:01] } 57... Rxg3+ { [%clk 0:10:10] } 58. Kf1 { [%clk 0:07:26] } 58... Qf7+ { [%clk 0:10:11] } 59. Rf2 { [%clk 0:07:41] } 59... Qxb3 { [%clk 0:10:31] } 60. Qd7+ { Black resigned as 60...Bg7 loses after 61. Qxg7 K