4] } (23... Qxc5+ 24. Rxc5 Rc8 25. Ke3 f5 26. Rxc8+ Bxc8 27. Nc5 Kf7) 24. Qxd5 { [%clk 1:10:48] } 24... Bxd5 { [%clk 0:59:04] } 25. Nc3 { [%clk 1:10:43] } 25... Be6 { [%clk 0:58:55] } 26. Rc5 { [%clk 1:06:27] } 26... f6 { [%clk 0:57:03] } 27. Rc6 { [%clk 1:06:14] } 27... Kf7 { [%clk 0:56:57] } 28. Rxa6 { [%clk 1:06:09] } 28... Rb8 { [%clk 0:56:52] } 29. Ra7+ { [%clk 1:05:44] } 29... Kg6?! { [%clk 0:43:49] } (29... Kf8! { Was quite important to keep the g pawn free, in order to be able to trade it. } 30. h4 h5 31. Ke1 Bf7 32. Rc7 g5 $14) 30. Re7 { [%clk 1:03:27] } 30... Rb6 { [%clk 0:41:25] } 31. g4?! { An odd decision by Fabi. He let Black trade a pair of pawns that had a decisive role in Black's counterplay, as the black king would have a path to reach the kingside pawns. } { [%clk 0:58:13] } (31. h4! { Preparing a fence for Black's king } 31... h5 32. Ke1 $16) 31... h5! { [%clk 0:39:25] } 32. gxh5+ { [%clk 0:57:09] } 32... Kh6 { [%clk 0:39:19] } 33. Ke1 { [%clk 0:57:05] } 33... Bf5 { [%clk 0:29:45] } 34. Rc7 { [%clk 0:50:42] } 34... Be6 { [%clk 0:17:29] } (34... Ra6 { It was possible to give the c4 pawn up in order to activate the bishop } 35. a4 Bc2 36. Rxc4 Kxh5 37. Kd2 Bb3 38. Rb4 Bf7 $14) 35. Kd2 { [%clk 0:46:57] } 35... Rd6+ { [%clk 0:16:37] } 36. Kc2 { [%clk 0:42:53] } 36... Rd7 { [%clk 0:15:08] } 37. Rc6 { [%clk 0:38:56] } 37... Bf7 { [%clk 0:14:45] } 38. a4 { [%clk 0:27:05] } 38... Ra7 { [%clk 0:14:30] } 39. Kb2 { [%clk 0:22:04] } 39... Kxh5 { [%clk 0:06:13] } 40. Ka3 { [%clk 0:52:15] } 40... Rb7 { [%clk 0:34:00] } 41. Nb5 { [%clk 0:52:31] } 41... Kg5! { Once Black gets counterplay, the rest is simple. } { [%cal Gg5f4,Gf4e3] [%clk 0:29:15] } 42. Rc5 { [%clk 0:14:04] } 42... Kf4 { [%clk 0:27:07] } 43. a5 { [%clk 0:14:28] } 43... Ke3 { [%clk 0:26:06] } 44. a6 { [%clk 0:12:04] } 44... Rb6 { [%clk 0:26:19] } 45. a7 { [%clk 0:12:32] } 45... Ra6+ { [%clk 0:26:43] } 46. Kb4 { [%clk 0:13:00] } 46... Be8 { [%clk 0:27:04] } 47. Rc7 { [%clk 0:12:36] } 47... Kxe2 { [%