{ Annotated by WGM Petra Papp - https://lichess.org/@/cukus

The battle was crucial for Aleksandra, as a win would bring her closer to first place. She opted for a very fighting opening, but Vaishali was well-prepared and secured a nice position after the early moves. The Indian superstar played exceptionally well and won the game convincingly. As a result, she is now leading by one point. }
1. d4 { [%clk 1:30:53] } 1... d5 { [%clk 1:30:38] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:04] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:02] } 3. c3!? { White plans to transpose into the London System with 3.c3, which limits some of Black's options. However, there are several lines where we do not lose time by playing c2-c3. So it's questionable who wins more with this move order. :) } { [%clk 1:31:23] } 3... e6 { [%clk 1:31:21] } (3... Bf5 4. Qb3!?) 4. Bf4 { [%clk 1:30:41] } 4... c5 { [%clk 1:31:25] } 5. e3 { [%clk 1:30:19] } 5... Qb6!? { [%clk 1:29:44] } (5... Nc6 6. Nbd2 { This could lead to one of the main lines. }) 6. Qb3 { [%clk 1:28:11] } 6... Bd7!? { Vaishali has taken a very interesting approach with her preparation. She is delaying the move to ...♞c6 for a while to maintain flexibility in her position. She has two main options: she can play ♜c8 to utilize the c-file with her rook, or she can opt for ♝c6 and set up with ♞bd7. This overall strategy is quite smart. } { [%clk 1:15:55] } 7. Nbd2 { [%clk 1:24:01] } 7... Be7 { [%clk 1:09:07] } 8. Be2 { Not going into the c5-c4 tempo is rather obvious. } { [%clk 1:21:37] } (8. Bd3 c4 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Bc2 b5 $132 { It is perfectly fine for Black. }) 8... O-O { [%clk 1:07:49] } (8... c4?! 9. Qc2! $14 { [%cal Gb2b3] }) (8... Bc6!? { This would be a very interesting alternative idea as well. } 9. g4 (9. O-O Nbd7 $132) 9... h6! 10. Ne5 g5 11. Bg3 h5!? $132) 9. O-O { This is, I believe, one of the important moments of the game. White made a castle without a doubt, but after that, her attacking prospects are minimal, and soon, we will get an equal endgame. } { [%clk 1:12:38] } (9. Ne5!? { White could try to build a more aggressive setup with this knight's jump. } 9... Be8 (9... Bc6 10. g4! $14) 10. g4!? $132) 9... Rc8 { [%clk 1:02:30] } 10. Ne5 { [%clk 1:07:29] } 10... Be8 { The black pieces are now perfectly coordinated and have nothing to worry about. } { [%clk 1:02:00] } 11. Bg5 { White wants to play f2-f4, but this setup is not ideal here, as Black can trade queens. Additionally, Black's pieces are prepared for this. } { [%clk 0:53:50] } (11. g4 Nfd7! $132) (11. Qxb6!? { This trade, followed by a kingside pawn push, would give a slight edge to White. } 11... axb6 12. g4!? h6 13. h4 Nh7 14. h5 $36) 11... Nc6 { [%clk 0:59:54] } 12. f4 { [%clk 0:51:49] } 12... Na5 { Forcing an endgame. } { [%clk 0:32:11] } (12... h6!? { This is also a fine option. } 13. Bh4 cxd4!? 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. exd4 Ne4!? $132) 13. Qxb6 { [%clk 0:50:38] } 13... axb6 { [%clk 0:31:52] } 14. f5 { According to the tournament situation, White is trying to show some ambition, but Black's position is very solid. } { [%clk 0:50:45] } 14... h6 { [%clk 0:31:01] } 15. Bh4 { [%clk 0:49:26] } 15... exf5!? { [%clk 0:30:05] } 16. Rxf5 { [%clk 0:47:29] } 16... Nc6!? { [%clk 0:25:23] } 17. a3 { [%clk 0:44:45] } 17... Bd8!? { Keeping everything well-protected. } { [%clk 0:19:15] } 18. Raf1 { [%clk 0:29:20] } (18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Rxf6? { It is not a correct line, but we need to check this exchange sacrifice every time. Also, Black's refutation is quite nice and instructive. } 19... gxf6 20. Ng4 Kg7 21. Rf1 cxd4 22. exd4 Nxd4! 23. cxd4 Rc2 24. Rd1 Rxb2 $17 { [%cal Ge8a4] }) (18. Bg3 Nh7!? $132 { [%cal Gd8g5] }) 18... Nxe5! { Black needs to trade White's annoying knight. } { [%clk 0:15:54] } 19. Rxe5 { [%clk 0:27:07] } (19. dxe5 Nh7!? $132) 19... Bc6! { Overprotecting the d5 pawn is rather obvious. } { [%clk 0:15:24] } 20. Ref5 { At that moment, White realized that e5 is a tactically dangerous place for the rook, but it will come back, as we will see. } { [%clk 0:24:17] } 20... Rc7! { [%clk 0:15:05] } 21. h3 { [%clk 0:18:28] } 21... Rd7 { [%clk 0:13:38] } (21... Ne8!? 22. Bg3 Rd7 $132 { [%cal Ge8d6] }) 22. Bg3 { [%clk 0:15:42] } 22... Bc7 { Black is keeping the game as solid as possible. } { [%clk 0:11:52] } (22... Ne8 $132 { [%cal Ge8d6] }) 23. Bxc7 { [%clk 0:13:40] } 23... Rxc7 { [%clk 0:12:20] } 24. Re5 { [%clk 0:12:45] } 24... Re8 { [%clk 0:11:52] } (24... Rd8 $132 { [%cal Gf6e8,Gf7f6] }) 25. Rff5?! { And this is another key moment of the game. White is trying to bring complications into the battle, but it works exactly to the black side's advantage. } { [%clk 0:12:47] } (25. Rxe8+ Nxe8 26. Bf3 { The game is likely to finish in a draw. }) 25... Rxe5 { [%clk 0:09:01] } 26. Rxe5 { [%clk 0:12:08] } 26... g6! { It's a great feeling of momentum! With a few precise moves, Black put the opponent in a really unpleasant situation! } { [%clk 0:09:20] } 27. dxc5 { [%clk 0:09:15] } 27... bxc5 { [%clk 0:09:46] } 28. c4! { [%clk 0:09:23] } 28... Kf8! { Maintaining the tension around the white rook. } { [%cal Gf6d7] [%clk 0:08:25] } 29. cxd5! { [%clk 0:09:06] } 29... Bxd5! { Again, the best option. } { [%clk 0:08:22] } (29... Nxd5 30. Bf3 Rd7 31. Nc4 f6 32. Re6 Kf7 33. Rd6) 30. Bc4?? { White became nervous while trying to solve the rook problem quickly, which led to disaster. } { [%clk 0:06:43] } (30. a4!? { The engine is holding it. } 30... Be6 (30... Bc6 31. Rxc5!) 31. a5 Ke7 32. Nc4 g5!? $15 { but Black is still pressuring. }) 30... Bc6! $19 { The move is calm yet incredibly strong! There are no escape routes left for the white rook. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Gf6d7] [%clk 0:07:48] } 31. Rxc5 { [%clk 0:03:16] } 31... b6! { This small shot could significantly impact the entire tournament! The rook cannot retreat due to the poor move 30.♗c4, and the bishop now blocks the c-file. } { [%clk 0:08:16] } 32. Rxc6 { [%clk 0:02:43] } (32. Re5 Nd7 $19) 32... Rxc6 { [%clk 0:08:44] } 33. Bb5 { [%clk 0:02:19] } 33... Rc2 { The position is obviously winning for Black, and she converted it very confidently. } { [%clk 0:06:53] } 34. Nc4 { [%clk 0:02:40] } 34... Nd5 { [%clk 0:06:48] } 35. b3 { [%clk 0:02:22] } 35... Rc3 { [%clk 0:05:54] } 36. Ba4 { [%clk 0:02:14] } 36... Nxe3!? { Showing the power. } { [%clk 0:02:53] } (36... b5 37. Bxb5 Rxb3 38. a4 Nxe3 $19) 37. Nxb6 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 37... Rc2 { [%clk 0:03:18] } 38. Bb5 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 38... Rxg2+ { [%clk 0:03:45] } 39. Kh1 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 39... Rb2! { [%clk 0:02:55] } 40. Nd7+ { [%clk 0:01:21] } (40. b4 Nc2 $19) 40... Ke7 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 41. Nc5 { [%clk 0:01:40] } 41... Kd6 { [%clk 0:01:53] } 42. Nb7+ { [%clk 0:23:55] } 42... Kd5 { Full domination. } { [%clk 0:28:31] } 43. b4 { [%clk 0:24:01] } 43... Ke4 { [%clk 0:26:36] } 44. Nc5+ { [%clk 0:17:17] } 44... Kf3! { [%clk 0:26:50] } 45. Bd3 { [%clk 0:17:18] } 45... f5 { Taking away the crucial e4 square, so Black is ready to play ♚g3. The position is totally winning for Black, and not surprisingly, Aleksandra resigned. A very important point for Black! } { [%clk 0:24:55] } 0-1


