Zhu was in second place before and after this round, so she still has a chance to catch up to Vaishali. The game was relatively balanced, with White applying very little pressure, but Divya had played the whole game very solidly, and in the end, it was a rather peaceful draw. }
1. e4 { Zhu has played most of her games in the Candidates Tournament using the King's Pawn opening, so this was an expected first move. } { [%clk 1:30:53] } 1... c5 { Divya enjoys playing the Sicilian Defense. } { [%clk 1:30:54] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:16] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:31:17] } (2... g6 { Divya attempted this move in round 8 against Anna Muzychuk, likely aiming to avoid the Rossolimo variation. It turned out to be a dramatic game. Anna nicely outplayed her, and Divya found herself in a difficult position for quite some time. However, around the 40th move, Anna made some critical mistakes, lost control of the game, and ultimately blundered, leading to her loss. I didn’t expect Divya to try the Maroczy opening again! :) }) 3. Bb5 { The Rossolimo is a very fashionable opening. White primarily avoids the Sveshnikov variation. } { [%clk 1:31:36] } 3... d6!? { It's a popular move nowadays. I would say Hikaru enjoys playing this move frequently. The idea is that Black aims to play ...♝d7 followed by a7-a6. } { [%clk 1:31:41] } (3... e5 { This is another tricky line that Divya has played a few times. }) 4. O-O { [%clk 1:31:40] } 4... Bd7 { [%clk 1:32:02] } 5. Re1! { A standard move. The rook overprotects the e4 pawn and frees the f1 square for the bishop. } { [%clk 1:31:58] } 5... a6!? { [%clk 1:32:23] } (5... Nf6 { In the earlier round, this occurred, allowing Divya to prepare effectively against this line. } 6. h3!? a6 7. Bf1 Rg8 8. d3 h6 9. b4!? cxb4 10. a3 b3 11. Nbd2 g5 12. d4 g4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Bb2 $14 { Zhu-Assaubayeva, 2026 }) 6. Bxc6 { [%clk 1:31:51] } (6. Bf1 { The other main line. }) 6... Bxc6 { [%clk 1:32:49] } 7. d4 { [%clk 1:32:14] } 7... cxd4 { [%clk 1:33:16] } 8. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:32:39] } 8... Rc8! { A necessary move, as Black must take on c6 with a rook for a better pawn structure. Divya surely played it instantly. } { [%clk 1:33:45] } 9. c4 { After 8 minutes of thought, Zhu began to play rather slowly from this point, indicating that she was out of her preparation. At the same time, she made natural moves, intending to establish a solid "Maroczy-type" position with a spatial advantage and positional pressure. } { [%clk 1:24:01] } (9. b3 { It's likely just a transposition into the game. } 9... Nf6 10. Nxc6 Rxc6 11. c4 g6 { - 9.c4 }) 9... g6 { It is natural to aim to develop the bishop to g7. } { [%clk 1:33:31] } 10. b3 { [%clk 1:13:15] } (10. Nc3 { It's more natural, as the knight will go to c3 anyway, but White has a line where the b3 square can be used with the queen, so it's needed to keep the options more flexible. } 10... Bg7 (10... Nf6?! 11. Nxc6! Rxc6 (11... bxc6 12. c5! $14) 12. Qb3! Qb6 13. Qxb6 Rxb6 14. Nd5! Rc6 (14... Nxd5 15. exd5! Bg7 16. Rb1 $36 { [%cal Gc1g5] }) 15. Nxf6+ exf6 16. b3 $14) 11. b3!? Nf6 12. Bg5!? h6 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Rc1 $14) 10... Nf6 { [%clk 1:33:31] } 11. Nxc6 { White is aiming for a minimal edge, pushing without taking risks. } { [%clk 1:13:25] } 11... Rxc6 { [%clk 1:33:49] } 12. Bb2 { It's common to move the bishop to b2, but once Black's bishop is on g7, we are likely to face numerous exchanges. Based on my analysis, it’s better to avoid this and instead develop the bishop along the c1-h6 diagonal. If the knight goes to d7, we can play ♘d5, which also means that the knight on c3 is not pinned. } { [%clk 1:13:46] } (12. Nc3 Bg7 13. Bf4!? O-O 14. Rc1 $14 { [%cal Gh2h3,Gd1e2,Ge1d1] } 14... Nd7?! 15. Nd5! $36) 12... Bg7 { [%clk 1:34:14] } 13. Nc3 { [%clk 1:12:48] } 13... O-O { [%clk 1:34:29] } 14. Nd5?! { It's a very simple way to play, and Black is quite comfortable in this position. } { [%clk 1:09:55] } (14. a4!? e6! $132 { [%cal Gd8a5,Gf8d8,Gc6c8] }) (14. Rc1 Nd7!? $132 { [%cal Gd8a5] }) 14... e6 { [%clk 1:30:42] } (14... Nxd5! { This is the simplest way to equalize. } 15. exd5 (15. Bxg7 Ne3! 16. Rxe3 Kxg7) 15... Bxb2 16. Rb1 Rc5!? 17. Rxb2 b5 $132) 15. Nb4!? { [%clk 0:53:27] } 15... Rc8 { [%clk 1:18:59] } 16. Qf3!? { [%clk 0:53:35] } 16... Qe7 { [%clk 1:17:51] } (16... b5! { Di