1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:37] } 1... c6 { In a must-win situation, Black goes for the Caro-Kann! } { [%clk 1:30:52] } 2. d4 { [%clk 1:30:53] } 2... d5 { [%clk 1:31:15] } 3. e5 { Vaishali goes for the Advance Variation, which usually leads to closed positions where strategic understanding matters the most. } { [%clk 1:31:14] } 3... Bf5 { Even though this move has been played in more than 9,000 games, it’s only the fourth most popular choice. } { [%clk 1:31:38] } 4. Bd3 { [%clk 1:31:24] } 4... Bxd3 { [%clk 1:31:47] } 5. cxd3 { This move hasn’t been played very often, as most top players prefer Qxd3. } { [%clk 1:31:39] } 5... e6 { [%clk 1:31:55] } 6. Nc3 { [%clk 1:32:00] } 6... Ne7 { This is a pretty typical development—since Black can’t place both the knight and the bishop on e7 at the same time, the knight comes out first. } { [%clk 1:23:08] } 7. Nf3 { [%clk 1:32:17] } 7... h6 { [%clk 1:23:09] } 8. h4 { This is a common idea in the Caro-Kann, where White grabs space on the kingside with the potential for a later attack. } { [%clk 1:26:13] } 8... Nd7?! { [%clk 1:21:56] } (8... h5) 9. Ne2 { This move looks a bit slow. } { [%clk 1:25:53] } (9. h5 c5 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. d4 Ne4 12. Qd3 $14) 9... b6 { [%clk 1:18:26] } 10. Bd2 { [%clk 1:02:03] } 10... c5 { [%clk 1:17:02] } 11. Rc1 { [%clk 1:02:11] } 11... Nc6 { Black has placed the knights in the most effective way, both putting pressure on White’s two central pawns. } { [%clk 1:13:46] } 12. h5 { [%clk 1:00:32] } 12... Qc8 { [%clk 1:05:21] } (12... Be7 13. Rh3 O-O 14. Rg3 Kh7) 13. dxc5? { [%clk 0:36:06] } (13. Rh4 Be7 14. Rg4 O-O?? 15. Bxh6 $18) 13... bxc5 { [%clk 1:04:54] } 14. Qa4 { [%clk 0:36:08] } 14... Qb7 { [%clk 1:02:19] } 15. O-O { [%clk 0:33:23] } 15... Rb8? { This is Black’s first mistake—the rook isn’t well placed on b8, as we’ll see in the following variations. } { [%clk 0:58:51] } (15... a5 16. d4 Be7 17. dxc5 O-O) 16. Rc2 { [%clk 0:17:59] } (16. Qg4 Ncxe5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Qg3 { threatening Bf4 } 18... Nc6 19. b4! { with a very big initiative for White, as Black's kingside is still undeveloped. }) 16... a6 { [%clk 0:23:51] } 17. Qf4 { [%clk 0:13:46] } 17... Qb5 { [%clk 0:24:12] } 18. Nc1 { [%clk 0:13:32] } 18... Rg8 { [%clk 0:23:53] } (18... Be7 { For better or worse, Black had to develop the bishop } 19. Qg4 Kf8 { with a complicated, but balanced game. }) 19. b3 { [%clk 0:12:35] } (19. d4 cxd4 20. Nb3 d3 21. Nbd4 Nxd4 22. Nxd4 Qb7 23. Rc3 Be7 24. Qe3 Bb4 25. Rxd3 Bxd2 26. Rxd2 { White is clearly better since Black cannot castle. }) 19... g5 { A nice way to activate the rook. } { [%clk 0:23:11] } 20. hxg6 { [%clk 0:13:02] } 20... Rxg6 { [%clk 0:23:36] } 21. d4 { [%clk 0:11:45] } 21... Be7 { [%clk 0:20:59] } (21... Nxd4 22. Nxd4 cxd4 23. Qxd4 Bc5 24. Qf4 f6 $13) 22. Be3 { [%clk 0:07:06] } 22... c4 { [%clk 0:16:47] } 23. bxc4? { [%clk 0:06:20] } (23. Qh2 { with the idea Nb1-e2-f4! }) 23... dxc4 { [%clk 0:17:12] } 24. Ne2 { [%clk 0:06:25] } 24... Nb4 { [%clk 0:16:50] } 25. Rb2 { [%clk 0:04:24] } 25... Qc6 { [%clk 0:15:16] } 26. Rfb1? { This is a miscalculation. The passed pawn has started to become quite dangerous, so White should have played more carefully. } { [%clk 0:04:49] } (26. Bd2 Nd3 27. Rxb8+ Nxb8 28. Qe3 { was still holding the equality. }) 26... Rb5! { By putting the rook under protection, the knight is no longer pinned. } { [%clk 0:11:42] } (26... c3? 27. d5 exd5 28. Rxb4 $18) 27. d5 { 27...was a big threat. } { [%clk 0:03:43] } 27... Nxd5 { [%clk 0:10:41] } 28. Qe4 { [%clk 0:03:53] } 28... Qb7 { The position is still complicated but Black has much better chances now. } { [%clk 0:06:13] } 29. Bd4 { [%clk 0:02:25] } 29... h5! { Will help Black to activate the other rook too. } { [%clk 0:03:22] } 30. Kh1 { [%clk 0:01:27] } 30... Rg4 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 31. Qh7 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 31... h4 { The position is starting to look worrying for White, as the long diagonal could become extremely weak if Black manages to push h4–h3. } { [%clk 0:02:29] } 32. Qh5 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 32... Rg6 { [%clk 0:01:57] } 33. Qh8+ { [%clk 0:00:35] } 33... Nf8 { [%clk 0:02:23] } 34. a4 { [%clk 0:00:46] } 34... Rb3 { [%clk 0:02:22] } (34... Rxb2 35. Rxb2 Qc7 $17 { Although the move played in the game looks much more natural and safe, since it doesn’t allow White to take control of the b-file. }) 35. Rxb3 { [%clk 0:00:34] } 35... cxb3 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 36. Nc1?? { This is the final blunder in an already pretty difficult position. } { [%clk 0:00:36] } (36. Qh5 Nd7 37. Ne1 $15 { was much more resiliant }) 36... h3! { All of a sudden, Black’s queen, rook, and knight come together like the final pieces of a puzzle, all targeting the White king. } { [%clk 0:01:46] } 37. Nxb3 { [%clk 0:00:33] } (37. Qxh3 Nf4 38. Qh8 Rxg2 $19) 37... hxg2+ { [%clk 0:02:04] } 38. Kh2 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 38... g1=Q+ { [%clk 0:01:33] } 39. Nxg1 { [%clk 0:01:10] } 39... Nc3 { And since the checkmate threat is immediate, White loses the rook. } { [%clk 0:01:52] } 0-1


