ra pawn, Black looks quite active. }) 22. Qe2 { [%clk 1:00:30] } 22... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:44:28] } 23. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:53:02] } 23... Rxe5 { [%clk 0:44:56] } 24. Qd3 { [%clk 0:51:39] } 24... b3? { Probably, this is a miscalculation. } { [%clk 0:32:01] } (24... Re7 25. b3 c5 26. Rxe7 Bxe7) 25. c3! { White finds the best move. As the position starts to open up, White’s pieces are better prepared for it. } { [%clk 0:39:49] } 25... dxc3 { [%clk 0:22:35] } 26. Qxd8 { [%clk 0:40:03] } 26... Rxd8 { [%clk 0:22:59] } 27. Bxc3 { The pawn on c7 is hanging, and the pawn on b3 is also weak, so it’s becoming difficult for Black to defend both. } { [%clk 0:40:26] } 27... Rb5 { [%clk 0:22:47] } (27... Rc5 28. Rb7 g5 29. Rxb3 Bg7 30. Bxg7 Kxg7 31. Re2 { with good chances for a draw. }) 28. Rxc7 { [%clk 0:33:39] } 28... Bb4 { [%clk 0:22:23] } 29. Bxb4 { [%clk 0:29:19] } 29... Rxb4 { [%clk 0:22:51] } 30. Re2 { [%clk 0:28:53] } 30... Rd1+ { [%clk 0:17:47] } 31. Kh2 { [%clk 0:29:13] } 31... Rbd4 { [%clk 0:15:20] } 32. Rc3 { [%clk 0:28:07] } 32... R4d2 { [%clk 0:15:20] } 33. Rxd2 { [%clk 0:28:09] } 33... Rxd2 { [%clk 0:15:49] } 34. Rxb3 { [%clk 0:28:32] } 34... Rxf2 { At the end of the fairly forced line, we reach another rook endgame where White has an extra pawn. I would estimate White’s winning chances here to be higher compared to the variation mentioned above, as it’s always tricky to play against a passed pawn. } { [%clk 0:16:16] } 35. Kg3 { [%clk 0:28:51] } 35... Rc2 { [%clk 0:14:59] } 36. h4 { [%clk 0:27:14] } 36... Kf8 { [%clk 0:13:02] } 37. Rb7 { [%clk 0:24:50] } 37... Rc6? { In rook endgames, the right decisions don’t come easily. Black should have tried to create at least some counterplay on the kingside by pushing the pawns and activating the king. Since White’s typical plan is to bring the king to support the pawn, Black needed to be better prepared for that. } { [%clk 0:07:32] } (37... g5 38. hxg5 hxg5 39. Kf3 Kg7 40. b4 Kf6 41. b5 Rc3+ 42. Kf2 Ke6 43. b6 Rb3 { with very good chances for a draw. }) 38. b4 { [%clk 0:19:45] } 38... Rg6+ { [%clk 0:05:25] } 39. Kf3 { [%clk 0:20:07] } 39... Rf6+ { [%clk 0:05:40] } 40. Ke3 { In a way, Black helped White bring her king over to the other side of the board. } { [%clk 0:20:23] } 40... Rg6 { [%clk 0:05:55] } 41. b5! { The passed pawn is becoming extremely dangerous, so White shouldn’t worry about anything else. } { [%clk 0:17:24] } 41... Rxg2 { [%clk 0:05:42] } 42. b6 { [%clk 0:17:39] } 42... g5 { The threat was already serious: Rc7, b7, Rc8+ with promotion. Black has to create an escape square for the king, but now it’s becoming too late. } { [%clk 0:03:02] } 43. Rc7 { [%clk 0:05:52] } 43... Rb2 { [%clk 0:01:06] } 44. b7 { [%clk 0:06:09] } 44... Kg7 { [%clk 0:01:25] } 45. e5! { With a threat of creating one more passer. } { [%clk 0:32:58] } 45... Kg6 { [%clk 0:21:51] } (45... gxh4?? 46. e6 Kf8 47. Rc8+ Kg7 48. e7 $18) 46. h5+! { Distraction! } { [%clk 0:31:23] } 46... Kf5 { [%clk 0:20:14] } (46... Kxh5 47. Rxf7 g4 48. e6 $18 { 2 passed pawns would have brought an easy win to White. }) 47. Kd4 { [%clk 0:24:39] } 47... Ke6 { [%clk 0:19:49] } 48. Kc5 { [%clk 0:22:07] } 48... Kxe5 { [%clk 0:20:02] } 49. Kc6 { [%clk 0:06:53] } (49. Rd7! g4 50. Rd5+ Ke6 51. Rd6+ Ke7 52. Rb6 $18) 49... g4 { [%clk 0:16:55] } 50. Re7+ { [%clk 0:05:47] } 50... Kf6 { [%clk 0:12:08] } 51. Re8 { [%clk 0:06:12] } 51... Rxb7 { [%clk 0:10:30] } 52. Kxb7 { This endgame must be relatively easy to win for White, as Black’s pawns haven’t advanced too far yet, although it requires good nerves and precise calculation. } { [%clk 0:06:40] } 52... Kg5 { [%clk 0:10:55] } 53. Kc6 { [%clk 0:05:20] } 53... Kxh5 { [%clk 0:08:39] } 54. Kd5 { [%clk 0:05:40] } 54... Kh4 { [%clk 0:08:33] } 55. Ke4 { [%clk 0:05:33] } 55... Kg3 { [%clk 0:08:01] } 56. Ra8 { So far, White is doing a perfect job—bringing the king closer and placing the rook on the right side from where it will be able to give side checks. } { [%clk 0:04:39] } 56... h5 { [%clk 0:07:57] }