The stakes in this game were extremely high, as both players chased the tournament leaders, separated by just half a point. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:55] } 1... e5 { [%clk 1:30:54] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:20] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 1:31:17] } 3. d4 { The Scotch Game is probably your best choice if you want to avoid playing the Italian Game (3.Bc4) or the Ruy Lopez (3.Bb5) } { [%clk 1:31:46] } 3... exd4 { [%clk 1:31:32] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:32:11] } 4... Nf6 { [%clk 1:31:29] } 5. Nxc6 { [%clk 1:32:34] } 5... bxc6 { [%clk 1:31:56] } 6. Qe2 { [%clk 1:32:57] } 6... Qe7 { [%clk 1:29:04] } 7. Nc3 { This is a rather rare variation as White usually goes for 7.e5 } { [%clk 1:33:20] } 7... d5 { [%clk 1:26:23] } 8. exd5 { [%clk 1:33:43] } 8... Nxd5 { This is a less common approach, which gives White a slight opening advantage, as two more natural moves are available. } { [%clk 1:20:06] } (8... cxd5 9. Nb5 Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 Kd7 11. Bg5 a6) (8... Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 cxd5 10. Bf4 c6) 9. Bd2 $14 { White holds a slight advantage due to superior development and Black’s structural weakness with doubled pawns. } { [%clk 1:33:43] } 9... Bg4 { [%clk 1:15:01] } 10. f3 { [%clk 1:33:06] } 10... Qxe2+ { [%clk 1:15:17] } 11. Bxe2 { [%clk 1:32:05] } 11... Be6 { [%clk 1:14:11] } 12. O-O-O { [%clk 1:30:22] } 12... Be7 { [%clk 1:10:18] } 13. Nxd5! { It looks like White is helping Black by undoubling the pawns, but this is actually the right moment to disrupt Black’s normal development. } { [%clk 1:22:11] } 13... cxd5 { [%clk 0:52:35] } 14. Bb5+ { [%clk 1:22:20] } 14... Bd7 { [%clk 0:52:53] } (14... Kf8 15. Bc6 Rb8 16. Be3 $16 { This leads to a clearly superior position for White, as Black is still unable to complete development. }) 15. Rhe1! { Black is already in trouble, with her king still in the center and likely to come under increasing pressure, leading to material loss. } { [%clk 1:19:07] } 15... Bxb5 { [%clk 0:46:27] } 16. Bb4 { [%clk 1:19:28] } 16... O-O-O { [%clk 0:46:39] } 17. Rxe7 { [%clk 1:19:34] } 17... Rd7 { [%clk 0:45:40] } (17... Rhf8 { Black could have tried } 18. Bc3 g6 19. Ba5 Rd7 20. Rxd7 Kxd7 21. Rxd5+ $16 { resulting in unavoidable material losses. }) 18. Rxd7 { [%clk 1:19:51] } 18... Bxd7 { [%clk 0:46:05] } 19. Rxd5 { Although White is a pawn up, opposite-colored bishops mean the chances of a draw are still very high, but the presence of a pair of rooks on the board adds to White’s advantage. } { [%clk 1:20:11] } 19... h5 { [%clk 0:44:54] } 20. Bc3 { [%clk 1:18:01] } 20... f6 { [%clk 0:44:40] } 21. h4 { In the last two moves, White has managed to fix the pawn structure on the kingside and will soon start pushing the pawns on the side where they have a pawn majority. } { [%clk 1:15:46] } 21... Be6 { [%clk 0:36:38] } 22. Rc5 { [%clk 1:13:44] } 22... Kb7 { [%clk 0:36:51] } 23. a4 { [%clk 1:12:49] } 23... Bf7 { [%clk 0:33:00] } 24. b4 { [%clk 0:48:30] } 24... Rd8 { [%clk 0:27:42] } 25. b5 { White has greatly improved her position, keeping Black tied down to passive defence. } { [%clk 0:45:01] } 25... Rd5 { [%clk 0:27:39] } 26. Rc6 { [%clk 0:44:03] } 26... Rd6 { [%clk 0:25:15] } 27. Rxd6 { White decides to exchange the rooks, as too many of Black’s pawns are on dark squares and may become a clear target for White’s bishop. } { [%clk 0:44:05] } 27... cxd6 { [%clk 0:25:45] } 28. Kd2 { Bringing the king into play is always a strong endgame strategy. } { [%clk 0:40:34] } 28... Be6 { [%clk 0:06:47] } 29. Bb4 { [%clk 0:39:05] } 29... Kc7 { [%clk 0:07:14] } (29... a6 30. bxa6+ Kxa6 31. Bxd6 Ka5 32. Ke3 Kxa4 33. Kf4 Kb5 34. Bf8 g6 35. Bg7 Bf5 (35... f5? 36. Kg5 Bf7 37. Kf6 Be8 38. Ke7 Bc6 39. Kf7 $18) 36. c3 Bd3 37. Bxf6 $18 { also gives White a highly promising winning endgame. }) 30. Ke3 { [%clk 0:34:24] } 30... Bc4 { [%clk 0:03:31] } 31. Ba5+ { [%clk 0:22:26] } 31... Kd7 { [%clk 0:03:38] } 32. Bc3 { [%clk 0:22:40] } 32... a6?! { This is an inaccuracy, allowing White to create a passed pawn and making the position harder to defend. } { [%clk 0:03:02] } (32... Kc7 33. g4 Bf7 34. Bb4 g5 35. hxg5 fxg5 36. Bd2 Kb7 37. Kd3 hxg4 38. fxg4 Be6 $16 { was, probably, more resilient. }) 33. b6 { [%clk 0:19:43] } 33... Bf7 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 34. a5 { [%clk 0:11:09] } 34... Bg6 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 35. Kd2 { [%clk 0:11:34] } 35... Bf5 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 36. Bd4 { [%clk 0:11:43] } 36... Kc6 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 37. c3 { [%clk 0:09:17] } 37... Bc8 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 38. Ke3 { [%clk 0:07:39] } 38... Kd5 { [%clk 0:00:55] } (38... Kb5 39. Ke4 Kxa5 40. Kd5 Bb7+ 41. Kxd6 Kb5 42. Kc7 Ba8 43. b7 Bxb7 44. Kxb7 $18) 39. g4 { [%clk 0:07:48] } 39... g6 { [%clk 0:00:39] } (39... hxg4 40. fxg4 Ke6 41. Kf4 Bb7 42. h5 Bc6 43. c4 Kf7 44. Bb2 Bb7 45. g5 fxg5+ 46. Kxg5 Bc6 47. Bxg7 Kxg7 48. h6+ Kh7 49. Kf6 $18) 40. Bxf6 { [%clk 0:07:28] } 40... Bb7 { [%clk 0:00:41] } 41. Kf4 { [%clk 0:04:56] } 41... Ke6 { [%clk 0:28:47] } 42. Kg5 { [%clk 0:34:35] } 42... Kf7 { [%clk 0:24:21] } 43. gxh5 { [%clk 0:34:35] } 43... gxh5 { [%clk 0:24:47] } 44. f4 { After this game, we have a new tournament leader, although the standings remain very unclear. Unlike in the Open section, everything is still to play for here, and tomorrow’s final rounds will decide it all. } { [%clk 0:35:01] } 1-0


