1. d4 { The winner has already taken it all, but one may not simply call the last Candidates round a joke. Including the mere Matthias Bluebaum, who hadn’t had a single victory at this event. } { [%clk 1:59:57] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:57] } 2. c4 { [%clk 1:59:52] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:59:54] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:47] } 3... d5 { [%clk 1:59:50] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:43] } 4... Bb4!? { As of today, the Ragozin System is one of the main lines that lures us into extremely complex play. } { [%clk 1:59:47] } 5. Qa4+ { [%clk 1:59:35] } 5... Nc6 { [%clk 1:59:43] } 6. e3 { [%clk 1:59:28] } 6... O-O { [%clk 1:59:38] } 7. Bd2 { [%clk 1:59:25] } 7... dxc4 { [%clk 1:59:33] } 8. Bxc4 { [%clk 1:59:19] } 8... Bd6 { [%clk 1:59:29] } 9. Ng5!? { Bluebaum is off to play sharp! My database indicates that the move was played only twice. } { [%clk 1:59:09] } 9... a6! { Anish might know something and makes the strongest choice. } { [%clk 1:52:45] } (9... Nd5!? { 1-0 Krasenkow,M (2660)-San Segundo Carrillo,P (2505) Madrid Magistral 7th 1998 (6) was also possible }) 10. Qc2 { [%clk 1:58:06] } 10... h6 { [%clk 1:46:52] } 11. h4! { White leaves his knight en prise and plans to castle queenside in order to carry out a kingside attack. } { [%clk 1:53:03] } 11... Re8!? { A logical move, Black vacates the f8 square for his king and perhaps is getting ready to push e5 at some point } { [%clk 1:11:29] } 12. a3 { [%clk 1:41:36] } (12. Nce4!? { An interesting alternative, however Black has no trouble should his reaction be correct. } 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 e5 14. Qb3 Qd7 15. d5 Ne7 $13 { [%cal Gd7g4] }) 12... b5 { [%clk 1:08:43] } 13. Ba2 { [%clk 1:33:32] } 13... Bb7 { [%clk 1:07:11] } 14. O-O-O?? { It’s highly likely that Bluebaum has messed up with his preparation. Unfortunately, the move makes White lose instantly. } { [%clk 0:51:35] } (14. Nce4! { The most logical move here. } 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Ne7 16. Rc1 Rc8 17. Ba5 $13 { The queenside castling idea did not work, but it’s possible to go kingside and still remain in control of the a5 and c5 squares. The soulless computer is cold and shows equality, the people are human and rush into play. } { [%csl Ga5,Gc5,Ge4][%cal Ge1g1,Ge4c5] }) 14... b4 { [%clk 1:04:48] } 15. d5 { [%clk 0:47:02] } 15... Nd4!! { I dearly suspect Matthias has missed this resource. White’s attack is smothered without a single breath. } { [%clk 0:59:08] } (15... exd5 { At least White could draw: } 16. Bxd5! (16. Nxd5!? { A risky, yet luring path! } 16... hxg5 17. hxg5 Nxd5 18. f4!! $13 { Totally insane and sharp! White would want to play Qh7-Qh8 and grab the pawn on g7. } { [%cal Gc2h7,Gh7h8,Ge3e4] }) 16... hxg5 17. hxg5 bxc3 18. Bxc3 Nxd5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Rh7+ Kg8 21. Rxf7! Kxf7 22. Qh7+ Ke6 23. Qh3+) 16. exd4 { [%clk 0:38:08] } 16... bxc3 { [%clk 0:58:58] } 17. dxe6 { [%clk 0:37:07] } 17... cxd2+ { [%clk 0:58:48] } 18. Qxd2 { [%clk 0:36:45] } 18... fxe6 { [%clk 0:57:39] } 19. Nxe6 { [%clk 0:36:42] } 19... Qc8 $19 { The following is too simple to comment… } { [%clk 0:51:28] } 20. Qa5 { [%clk 0:21:23] } 20... Bd5 { [%clk 0:45:13] } 21. Bxd5 { [%clk 0:19:45] } 21... Nxd5 { [%clk 0:45:08] } 22. Nxg7 { [%clk 0:19:22] } 22... Kxg7 { [%clk 0:38:24] } 23. Qxd5 { [%clk 0:18:47] } 23... Qe6 { [%clk 0:36:42] } 24. Qxe6 { [%clk 0:17:46] } 24... Rxe6 { [%clk 0:36:41] } 25. g3 { [%clk 0:17:30] } 25... Rf8 { [%clk 0:35:51] } 26. Rd2 { [%clk 0:16:53] } 26... Ref6 { [%clk 0:35:18] } 27. Rf1 { [%clk 0:15:35] } 27... Rf3 { [%clk 0:34:24] } 28. Kd1 { [%clk 0:15:19] } 28... Rxg3 { Alas! Matthias could show us the full range of advantages of his opening idea, whilst we give a "bravo" to Anish – both for this game and for the second part of the Candidates! } { [%clk 0:34:02] } 0-1


