1. e4 { [%clk 1:59:57] } 1... c5 { [%clk 1:59:56] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:59:49] } 2... d6 { [%clk 1:59:53] } 3. d4 { [%clk 1:59:33] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 1:59:47] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:59:28] } 4... Nf6 { [%clk 1:59:42] } 5. Nc3 { [%clk 1:59:23] } 5... a6 { [%clk 1:59:39] } 6. Qd3!? { Don’t tell me who is playing white: in this tournament Esipenko remains creative! } { [%clk 1:58:49] } 6... g6 { [%clk 1:58:56] } 7. Bg5 { [%clk 1:55:52] } 7... Bg7 { [%clk 1:58:18] } 8. O-O-O { [%clk 1:54:46] } 8... O-O { [%clk 1:50:50] } 9. Be2!? { A rare move. } { [%clk 1:43:35] } (9. f4 Nbd7 10. Be2 { the main line }) 9... Nc6 { [%clk 1:37:02] } 10. Nb3?! { Oops, Andrey seems to have forgotten his preparation… } { [%clk 1:31:29] } (10. Qe3! { Obligatory, involving the following moves: } 10... Bd7 11. h4 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Rc8 13. h5 Qa5 $13 { and we have a Siciliano tipico all over the boardo. Hot, spicy, fire-y!! } { [%cal Gc8c3,Gh5g6] }) 10... Be6 { [%clk 1:22:16] } 11. Qe3 { [%clk 1:28:48] } 11... Rc8 $15 { It’s unclear what the purpose of the b3 knight was. } { [%clk 1:18:44] } 12. Kb1 { [%clk 1:24:52] } 12... Ne5 { [%clk 1:09:48] } 13. h3? { A mistake that involves Maestro Caruana to offer us a brilliant Sicilian masterclass. } { [%clk 1:07:47] } (13. Bxf6! { A must to be able to play f4 with an attempt of some game action } 13... Bxf6 14. f4 Nc4 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 16. Nd5 $13 { Black’s still a bit better, but with a lot of battles ahead. }) 13... Rxc3! { Oh, si. A rook trade to get an extremely better position. } { [%clk 1:02:53] } 14. bxc3 { [%clk 0:50:28] } (14. Qxc3 Nxe4 15. Qe3 Nxg5 16. Qxg5 b5 $17 { Black is very clear about his plans: Qc7, Rb8, Nc4, a5 and so on. } { [%cal Gd8c7,Ge5c4,Ga6a4,Gf8b8] }) 14... Qc7 { [%clk 1:02:28] } 15. f4 { [%clk 0:35:26] } 15... Ned7 { [%clk 1:01:06] } 16. Rd4 { [%clk 0:31:29] } 16... b5 { [%clk 0:53:06] } 17. g4? { A snail-slow move. White has no time for such ideas, it has to be something swift to get any counterplay. } { [%clk 0:22:09] } (17. f5! gxf5 1